category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with a father, mother, daughter, and son.
The Family: Man, Woman, Girl, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👩 Woman, 👧 Girl and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Woman, Girl, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A banded stack of U.S. dollar bills with feather wings, as if flying. Its flight may represent losing, transferring, or earning money, but commonly used for wealth, money, and success more generally, often with a flourish or sense of flair.

Money With Wings was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Namibia, which may show as the letters NA on some platforms.
The Flag: Namibia emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Namibia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and full-toothed grin, as if saying Cheese! for the camera. Teeth may be smoothed-over or crosshatched. Often expresses a radiant, gratified happiness. Tone varies, including warm, silly, amused, or proud.
Prior to 2017, Apple's design resembled its 😬 Grimacing Face.

Beaming Face With Smiling Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The back of an envelope, generally shown in white and sealed with a red heart. Represents a love letter or note, valentine, or affectionate greeting card. Commonly used to convey various feelings or messages of love and happiness.
Microsoft’s envelope is open, Facebook’s is pink.

Love Letter was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Latvia, which may show as the letters LV on some platforms.
The Flag: Latvia emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Latvia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A cartoon-styled representation of dizziness. Generally depicted as one or more yellow stars swirling in a yellow or blue circle.
Resembles squeans, stylized stars and circles over the heads of characters in comics and animation to show they are dizzy, disoriented, intoxicated, or sick.
Commonly used for emphasis and flair or to indicate various positive sentiments. Like 🌠 Shooting Star, sometimes used as a visual reference to NBC’s More You Know public service announcement, popular in the 1990s and featuring a shooting star logo.
Not to be confused with ⭐ Star, 🌟 Glowing Star, and ✨ Sparkles, though their applications may overlap.
Facebook’s design features two stars spinning along two intersecting purple circles, though it previously only featured one yellow ring. Samsung’s design previously displayed several yellow circles and stars.

Dizzy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Dizzy Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for American Samoa, which may show as the letters AS on some platforms.
The Flag: American Samoa emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: American Samoa was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two hands held out together with open palms facing up, in a slightly cupped manner.
May be used to represent an open book in American Sign Language (ASL), or the gesture used by followers of Islam when praying. This gesture also appears similarly to one used to beg for for money.

Palms Up Together was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person shrugging their shoulders to indicate a lack of knowledge about a particular topic, or a lack of care about the result of a situation.
Displays as raised shoulders, sometimes in conjunction with raised arms and flat hands. The shrug gesture in text (emoticon) form is known as a shruggie and typed as: ¯\_(ツ)_/¯
The Unicode character Shrug ("Person Shrugging") does not specify a gender though is displayed as a woman on most major platforms. See also Woman Shrugging or Man Shrugging.

Person Shrugging was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Shrug”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol representing Blood Type A. Displayed as the letter A on a red background.

A Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter A”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with closed eyes, mouth slightly open, and a blue snot bubble coming from its nose. Snot bubbles indicate a character is tired or sleeping in anime or manga. Not to be confused with 😴 Sleeping Face 
While sometimes used to convey sadness, dissastification, or illness, Sleepy Face is also not to be confused with 😢 Crying Face, 😥 Sad but Relieved Face, or other emojis with tear or sweat droplets. Samsung’s design previously featured two, cartoon-styled, sleeping-symbol Zz’s overhead.

Sleepy Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A crab, a squat crustacean with pincers. Depicted as a reddish-orange crab (as cooked) shown from above, with a round, shelled body, shorted, tentacle-like eyes, and ten legs, the top two of which are large pincers.
May be used to represent crab as food or metaphorical senses of crab (e.g., crabby). Often used to represent ♋ Cancer, the Crab, in the Western zodiac.
Not to be confused with 🦞 Lobster.
Facebook’s pincers have black tips.

Crab was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A whitish-gray, cartoon-styled human skull with large, black eye sockets. Commonly expresses figurative death, e.g., dying from extreme laughter, frustration, or affection.
Popular around Halloween. Not to be confused with ☠️ Skull and Crossbones, though their applications may overlap.
Available as an Apple Animoji.

Skull was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An angelic baby with wings, and a halo above its head. Commonly known as a cherub.

Baby Angel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Liechtenstein, which may show as the letters LI on some platforms.
The Flag: Liechtenstein emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Liechtenstein was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A face with open eyes and a small, open frown. Its eyebrows are furrowed, with a single bead of cold sweat dripping down, and its forehead is pale blue, as if experiencing a cold flash. Samsung's design shows upper teeth and tongue.
Meaning widely varies, but commonly conveys such feelings as sadness, disappointment, fear, and anxiety. Similar to 😥 Sad but Relieved Face, but with a blue head and larger frown.
Not to be confused with 😢 Crying Face, 😪 Sleepy Face, or other emojis with tear or sweat droplets. Microsoft and Samsung previously featured smileys that appeared more excited in expression.

Anxious Face With Sweat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face With Open Mouth and Cold Sweat”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman singer or rock star generally displayed with a microphone, and sometimes musical notes.
iOS and Android display this emoji as a Bowie-esque figure while WhatsApp appears heavily inspired by Prince.
The Woman Singer emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🎤 Microphone emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Singer was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Finland, which may show as the letters FI on some platforms.

🇫🇮 Finnish Flag Emoji

The Flag: Finland emoji is a sequence of the 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Finland was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two mothers, and two daughters.
The Family: Woman, Woman, Girl, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👩 Woman, 👧 Girl and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Woman, Girl, Girl was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A capsule of medicine. Generally depicted at a 45° angle, half red, half yellow. Commonly used for content concerning health, medicine, and related professions as well various types of drugs.
Samsung’s design previously featured a blue-and-white capsule with two round pills, one orange, the other white. Google and Microsoft’s designs previously featured blue in their capsules.

Pill was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A generic, high-rise office building. Generally found in cities, and most active during business hours.
The office building shown in Twemoji 2.0 is of Twitter HQ in San Fransisco.

Office Building was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with a father, mother, and two daughters.
The Family: Man, Woman, Girl, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👩 Woman, 👧 Girl and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Woman, Girl, Girl was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A loose stack of three of more different-colored, hardcover books. Commonly used for various content concerning reading and schooling. Color and orientation vary across platforms, but often shown with red, green, and blue covers.
Samsung’s design features the easter egg initials MJ printed on the pages of its bottom book.

Books was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Lesotho, which may show as the letters LS on some platforms.
The Flag: Lesotho emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Lesotho was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes, raised eyebrows, and a small, open mouth, as if it has been hushed by concern or correction. Meaning widely varies, but its expression is commonly taken as surprise, embarrassment, or mild excitement.
Similar to 😲 Astonished Face, which features larger eyes and mouth. Google previously interpreted hushed as "silenced," depicting the emoji with a zipper mouth until Android 6.0.1.

Hushed Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A female astronaut or cosmonaut shown wearing a space suit and helmet.
The Woman Astronaut emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🚀 Rocket emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Astronaut was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Passenger Ship was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An elderly woman with gray (grey) hair, and visible wrinkles. Wears glasses on some platforms.

Old Woman was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Older Woman”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A short, flat glass, as used for brown liquors like whiskey or Scotch whisky. Apple and WhatsApp serve theirs neat, while other platforms include ice ("on the rocks"). Samsung's glass features the faint initials ONI, an apparent in-company easter egg.  

Tumbler Glass was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A classic, five-point gold star.
Commonly used for various metaphorical senses of star (e.g., for fame, success, excellence, reviews). Also used for emphasis or flair. Occasionally used for astronomical stars.
Not to be confused with 💫 Dizzy, 🌟 Glowing Star, 🌠 Shooting Star, or ✨ Sparkles, though their applications may overlap.
Samsung and Facebook’s stars were once silver.
See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

Star was approved as part of Unicode 5.1 in 2008
under the name “White Medium Star”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for India, which may show as the letters IN on some platforms.
The Flag: India emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: India was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A lit-up bridge, shown at night.

Bridge at Night was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A sun with a smiling face, as a Sun of May. Generally depicted as a golden-yellow disc with a smiling, often human face with a nose, radiating triangular rays, representing the sun's heat and light.
May be used to represent the sun more generally. Also used to represent sunny, warm, or hot weather and various positive and happy (sunny) feelings.
See also ☀️ Sun. Not to be confused with 🔆 Bright Button or 🔅 Dim Button.
Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook's suns feature human faces. Other platforms, including Twitter, feature a simple smiley, as 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face.
Microsoft's eyes previously appeared closed, Facebook's expression resembled 😁 Beaming Face With Smiling Eyes.

Sun With Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A small rowboat suitable for a small number of people. Couples or families sometimes hire these as an activity on calm waters.

Person Rowing Boat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Rowboat”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
1st Place Medal was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “First Place Medal”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Fairy was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The word "soon" with an arrow above it, pointing to the right.

Soon Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Soon With Rightwards Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A menorah showing nine lit candles, used on the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah.

Menorah was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Menorah With Nine Branches”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Ding! A call bell, as pressed at a front desk or reception to alert staff for service, such as from a concierge or bellhop (porter) to carry luggage at a hotel. Generally depicted as a golden bell on a wooden stand.
Commonly represents alerts or notifications to bring attention to important content. May also be used of various content concerning the hospitality and service industries.
Microsoft’s design features a silver bell radiating yellow rays, as if ringing.

Bellhop Bell was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Called a “No Entry” sign Emoji, but does not look like the no entry road sign that one might expect.
The artwork for this Emoji looks more like a restriction sign, as in No Smoking, No Bikes, or similar.

Prohibited was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “No Entry Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face winking with puckered lips blowing a kiss, depicted as a small, red heart. May represent a kiss goodbye or good night and convey feelings of love and affection more generally. 
Many platforms feature the same eyes as on their 😉 Winking Face.
Microsoft’s design previously featured a feminine smiley with long eyelashes and red lipstick, which could leave a kiss mark.

Face Blowing a Kiss was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face Throwing a Kiss”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 👳 Man Wearing Turban emoji.
The Woman Wearing Turban emoji is a sequence of the 👳 Man With Turban and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Wearing Turban was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A black fountain pen with a silver nib, as used for signing important documents. Often depicted with gold hardware. Positioned at a 45° angle with its tip at the lower left. Like ✒️ Black Nib, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).
Apple and Twitter feature the same designs as their ✒️ Black Nib, but with their tips angled to the lower left.

Fountain Pen was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Lower Left Fountain Pen”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A purple heart emoji. Shown as pink in Android 4.4.

Purple Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Thin-cut, golden-brown French fries, served in a red carton, as at McDonald’s. Apple features Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes on its carton.

French Fries was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman of adult age. Differentiated from the girl emoji by the lack of pig-tails in her hair.

Woman was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A llama, a long-necked, camel-like animal, native to South America and used for transport and wool. Depicted as a shaggy white, light-brown, or multicolored llama in full profile on all fours facing left.
May be used to represent an alpaca or related animals.

Llama was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face sticking out its tongue and making a zany wink, usually shown with its right eye closed and left wide open. Often conveys a sense of fun, excitement, wackiness, buffoonery, or joking.
Generally goofier than 😛 Face With Tongue and 😝 Squinting Face With Tongue but less "crazy" than 🤪 Zany Face.

Winking Face With Tongue was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face With Stuck-Out Tongue and Winking Eye”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An icon used to represent a cyclone. Some versions of this emoji show a spiral shape, which may be used for decorative purposes.

Cyclone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A car being shown from the front. The windscreen and hood (bonnet in British English) of the car can be seen facing forward.
This car shows in red or blue on most platforms. Silver on Android.

Oncoming Automobile was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
An ambulance, used to transport patients between their home and the hospital.

Ambulance was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 💁 Information Desk Person emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Woman Tipping Hand emoji is a sequence of the 💁 Information Desk Person and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Tipping Hand was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A metal wrench (spanner), as used for turning nuts and bolts. Depicted with two open, crescent-shaped ends or one open end and a closed, ring-shaped end. Generally positioned at a 45° angle.
Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, maintenance, and skilled trades like car mechanics and plumbing.

Wrench was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A heart with vibration / movement lines above it, indicating it is a beating heart. Displayed in pink or red on most platforms, this emoji is intended to be used as a beating heart representing either life, or love.

Beating Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Mage emoji is a sequence of the 🧙 Mage and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Mage was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A long, bulbous, bright purple eggplant, or aubergine in British English, shown with a leafy stem. Considered lucky in Japan to dream of an eggplant the first night of the New Year. 
Widely used to represent a penis. Due to its phallic use, the hashtag #🍆 was once banned (2015) on Instagram's search function.

Eggplant was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Aubergine”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A type of bus that uses overhead electrical wires for power. Appears similar to a cross between a bus and a tram car.

Trolleybus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A blowfish (puffer), which puffs up and becomes spiky when alarmed. Depicted as an orange or brown blowfish in full profile facing left, with small fins, a white underside, and a round, spiky body, as if inflated.
Called fugu in Japan, where it’s consumed as a delicacy.
May be to represent a variety of fish (saltwater or freshwater), fishing, metaphorical senses of fish, and fish as food, as consumed in the form of 🍣 Sushi. Not to be confused with 🐟 Fish or 🐠 Tropical Fish, though their applications may overlap. See also 🎣 Fishing Pole.
Google’s blowfish was previously blue, Microsoft’s yellow, and Facebook’s white.

Blowfish was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man: Curly Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🦱 Emoji Component Curly Hair emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man: Curly Hair was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A rooster (cock), a male chicken known for its cock-a-doodle-do. Depicted as a white or multicolored rooster standing on its legs in full profile facing left, with a red comb on its head and red wattle on its neck.
Not to be confused with 🐔 Chicken, though their applications overlap. See also 🐣 Hatching Chick, 🐤 Baby Chick, and 🐥 Front-Facing Baby Chick. Occasionally used as sexual slang.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.
Google’s rooster is brown with a green tail, Facebook’s brown with a blue tail. Google’s rooster was previously white, Microsoft’s yellow, Samsung’s looking straight ahead.

Rooster was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😀 Grinning Face. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Grinning Cat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smiling Cat Face With Open Mouth”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Baggage Claim was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Bars increasing in height, showing the strength of the mobile (cellular) phone signal. More bars signifies better reception.

Antenna Bars was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Antenna With Bars”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A vertical line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing up and down.

Up-Down Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Up Down Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The face of a frog, the hopping amphibian. Generally depicted as a friendly, cartoon-styled, light-green frog looking straight ahead, with large eyes, slightly open mouth, and nostrils.
Popularly paired with ☕️ Hot Beverage to represent the But That’s None of My Business meme (used for gossip or sarcasm) or Pepe the Frog (associated with trolling and the alt-right).
Facebook’s design previously resembled Kermit the Frog.

Frog was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Frog Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person running, with a large stride and arms outstretched. May be wearing a running shirt.
This emoji does not specify a gender, but is shown as a man on most platforms. See also: 🏃‍♀️ Woman Running or 🏃‍♂️ Man Running.

Person Running was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Runner”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 👮 Police Officer emoji.
The Woman Police Officer emoji is a sequence of the 👮 Police Officer and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Police Officer was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 👳‍♀️ Woman Wearing Turban emoji.
The Man Wearing Turban emoji is a sequence of the 👳 Man With Turban and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Wearing Turban was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Spain, which may show as the letters ES on some platforms.
The Flag: Spain emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Spain was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A fist raised in the air that may be used as a celebratory gesture: the fist pump. Can also be used to represent zero items, due to a lack of any fingers being held up.
Sometimes used as a symbol of resistance or defiance.

Raised Fist was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol representing Blood Type AB. Displayed as the letters AB on a red background.

AB Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Negative Squared AB”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A light-brown or yellow rectangular tag, as labelled and attached to a key. Depicted at various angles punched with a hole, generally with a metal ring or loop of string.
Commonly used to represent a price tag or metadata tag as well as for various senses of label.
Google's design features two tags, WhatsApp's is white. Apple removed its ring from earlier designs. Samsung previously featured the easter egg initials HMJ.

Label was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Israel, which may show as the letters IL on some platforms.
The Flag: Israel emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Israel was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The mark left after a firm kiss is placed with bright lipstick. Used in place of ‘xxx’ (kisses), or to send a kiss to someone. More seductive than the kiss emoji.

Kiss Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
The Tokyo Tower is the second-tallest building in Japan, located in Minato, Tokyo.
Built in 1957, the design of the Tokyo Tower  was inspired by the Eiffel Tower in Paris, France and may be confused for it due to the small size of the emoji.

Tokyo Tower was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Puzzle Piece was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Jigsaw Puzzle Piece”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Tajikistan, which may show as the letters TJ on some platforms.
The Flag: Tajikistan emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇯 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter J emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Tajikistan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Man, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Boy was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A slice of watermelon, showing its rich pink flesh, black seeds, and green rind.

Watermelon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A ball of yarn, as used to knit a scarf. Color varies across platforms, but often depicted in green, blue, or magenta and shown with an end unraveling. Sometimes depicted with a pair of knitting needles stuck in the ball.
Commonly used for various content concerning knitting and needlework (e.g., sewing, crocheting), clothing and fashion, arts and crafts, cold weather, and cats.

Yarn was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Ball of Yarn”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Ukraine, which may show as the letters UA on some platforms.
The Flag: Ukraine emoji is a sequence of the 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Ukraine was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A car shown from the side, facing right-to-left. Appears as a red car on most platforms (which goes faster), except on Android where this displays as a silver car (previously blue).

Automobile was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The double helix of DNA, the genetic blueprint for life. Color and orientation vary across platforms, but positioned at a 45° angle and in multiple, bright colors to represent the molecule’s spiraling, ladder-like structure.
May be used for various content concerning biology, genetics, and science more generally. May also be used for various content concerning literal or figurative life and evolution.

DNA was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “DNA Double Helix”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A Mexican or Tex-Mex burrito, featuring a wrapped flour tortilla filled with such ingredients as beef, rice, beans, cheese, tomato, lettuce, and sour cream. Served in foil on several major platforms, suggesting a Mission burrito associated with San Francisco. Not to be confused with the Stuffed Flatbread.

Burrito was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The silver nib of a fountain pen, which distributes ink onto a writing surface. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Like 🖋️ Fountain Pen, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports).
Several platforms, including Google, Microsoft, and Samsung, depict only a nib, sometimes ringed with gold. Other platforms, including Apple and Twitter, feature the same designs as their 🖋️ Fountain Pen, but with their tips angled to the lower right.

Black Nib was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993

and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A non-motorized scooter, with two wheels and handles.

Kick Scooter was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Scooter”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🚵 Mountain Bicyclist emoji.
The Woman Mountain Biking emoji is a sequence of the 🚵 Mountain Bicyclist and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Mountain Biking was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Lipstick shown with the lid removed. Displays in a shade of red on most platforms, except Android which has a pink color.

Lipstick was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A liquid-in-glass thermometer, as used to measure temperature. Depicted at various angles with a red liquid risen from the bulb to various levels on the scale. Commonly used for content concerning high temperatures, including warm weather, illness (having a fever), and various slang senses of hot.

Thermometer was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for San Marino, which may show as the letters SM on some platforms.
The Flag: San Marino emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: San Marino was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Index finger pointing to the left.

Backhand Index Pointing Left was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “White Left Pointing Backhand Index”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Firefighter emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🚒 Fire Engine emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Firefighter was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 👱 Person With Blond Hair emoji.
The Woman: Blond Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👱 Person With Blond Hair and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman: Blond Hair was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a thin, closed smile. Conveys a wide range of positive, happy, and friendly sentiments. Its tone can also be patronizing, passive-aggressive, or ironic, as if saying This is fine when it’s really not.

Slightly Smiling Face was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for East Timor, which may show as the letters TL on some platforms.
The Flag: Timor-Leste emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Timor-Leste was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Farmer emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🌾 Ear of Rice emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Farmer was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Cityscape was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An open, curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag raised and a letter in its open slot. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag and white envelope (Google's design is yellow). Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.
Indicates in the United States that there is outgoing mail (post) for pickup. May also indicate that incoming mail has been delivered.
Compare 📫 Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, 📪 Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📭 Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag.

Open Mailbox With Raised Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Sint Maarten, which may show as the letters SX on some platforms. This is the Dutch half of the of the Caribbean island of Saint Martin. Not to be confused with St. Martin, the French half of the same island.
The Flag: Sint Maarten emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇽 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter X emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.


Flag: Sint Maarten was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A metal bolt with a nut threaded around it, as by a wrench. Often positioned at a 45° angle, the head of the bolt at the upper left. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction. May also be used for other hardware, including screws.
Apple’s bolt previously resembled a screw, Google’s a dumbbell; Microsoft’s design previously featured the nut and bolt separately.

Nut and Bolt was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Motor Boat was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Student emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🎓 Graduation Cap emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Student was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A Japanese senbei, or rice cracker, wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed, a snack commonly enjoyed with green tea.

Rice Cracker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A graph showing a colored trend line, often blue, decreasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of decrease, from numeral data to being metaphorically down. May also represent facts, figures, and charts more generally.
Google’s line is green, WhatsApp’s red, and Facebook’s orange.

Chart Decreasing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Chart With Downwards Trend”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person shown in water with a ball, playing the sport of water polo. 

Person Playing Water Polo was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Water Polo”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A rich green, tree-like head or floret of broccoli. 

Broccoli was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes, rosy cheeks, and puckered lips giving a kiss. Commonly conveys sentiments of romantic love and affection. Several platforms, including Apple, feature the same eyes and cheeks as their ☺️ Smiling Face.
With its closed eyes, features an expression more intimate than 😙 Kissing Face With Smiling Eyes’s and 😗 Kissing Face’s.
This emoji has a cat variant, 😽 Kissing Cat Face.

Kissing Face With Closed Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A British guardsman, known as a foot guard. Wears a tall black hat with a yellow chin-strap. Must look straight ahead at all times, even when tourists attempt to distract them.

Guard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Guardsman”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A golden-yellow custard dessert, as a crème caramel or flan, topped with a layer of caramel. Shown on a plate, molded in a ramekin-shape and often in a pool of caramel sauce.

Custard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-right, or south-east direction.

Down-Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “South East Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person bowing deeply which is known as dogeza in Japan. Used to express a sincere apology, or to request a large favour.
Many variations of this emoji are misinterpreted as a person doing push-ups, lying down to have a massage, or doing a cute "head resting on hands" gesture.

Person Bowing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Person Bowing Deeply”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A person checking passports at an international border.

Passport Control was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Swaziland, which may show as the letters SZ on some platforms.
The Flag: Eswatini emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Eswatini was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Firefighter emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🚒 Fire Engine emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Firefighter was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys.
Trams tend to be similar to light rail, with the difference being that they don’t tend to have their own dedicated tracks.
This emoji is generally shown as the side of the tram. The intended usage of this emoji, instead of the tram emoji is not clear.

Tram Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A bone which may be used for a dog to chew on, or as a part of the human body. The type of bone is not specified.

Bone was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth and tongue on some platforms. Often conveys general pleasure and good cheer or humor.
Not to be confused with 😃 Grinning Face With Big Eyes or 😄 Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes, which have the same smiles but more expressive eye shapes. 
This emoji has a cat variant, 😺 Grinning Cat Face.

Grinning Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Aries astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Ram.

Aries was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The back of envelope with a down arrow on top. Generally depicted in white (except for Google’s yellow design) with a red or blue arrow.
Commonly used an icon before an email address. May also represent downloading, direct messages, or mail (post) more generally. Its original intent may have been to indicate sealing and delivering a letter in an envelope.
Microsoft’s design previously resembled an incoming envelope. Early designs from Apple featured a right arrow with the envelope oriented lengthwise. SoftBank originally animated a rightward-moving arrow and envelope, suggesting sending or sent.

Envelope With Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Envelope With Downwards Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Means “Here” in Japanese, referring to a destination.

Japanese “Here” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared Katakana Koko”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with an open mouth, the top of its head exploding in the shape of a brain-like mushroom cloud. A visual form of the expression mind blown, it may represent such emotions as shock, awe, amazement, and disbelief.
Apple’s design features the same expression as its 😦 Frowning Face With Open Mouth.

Exploding Head was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Shocked Face With Exploding Head”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A mouse, as used to control a cursor on a computer. Generally depicted as a white or gray, cordless device with a scroll wheel between left- and right-click buttons.
Used for various content concerning computers, including gaming and various senses of click (e.g., clickbait).
Apple’s design resembles the company’s Magic Mouse, with a single button. Google’s mouse has a cord.
Not to be confused with 🐁 Mouse.

Computer Mouse was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Three Button Mouse”
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A place where people are taken to receive medical care. This hospital has a large red cross on the front, often used as a symbol for health care.

Hospital was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A human leg, shown detached from a human body. Displayed from the thigh and may include the foot.

Leg was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A bright red Mexican chili pepper, slightly curled and with a green stem. May be used to represent something “hot and spicy,” figuratively or literally, as a dish on a restaurant menu.

Hot Pepper was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Genie emoji is a sequence of the 🧞 Genie and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Genie was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A mobile phone (cell phone), as used to text, check social media, or take selfies. Depicted as a black or gray smartphone with a generic blue screen or multicolored app icons. Commonly used for various content concerning mobile phones, technology, and communication.
The designs from Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Samsung resemble phones offered by their respective companies, e.g., iPhone. WhatsApp’s design features a night sky as its wallpaper, displaying the time as 9:34. Early designs from au by KDDI resemble a traditional telephone receiver.
See also 📲 Mobile Phone With Arrow.

Mobile Phone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol for potable (drinkable) water, usually shown with a faucet filling a drinking glass. Commonly used for various content concerning water, drinking, thirst, and dripping.
Some platforms, including Apple and WhatsApp, depict the emoji as an object while others feature a stylized, white faucet on a blue square, as a sign or icon of water that is safe to drink. Compare 🚱 Non-Potable Water, which indicates water that is not safe to drink.
Apple's design previously featured a blue symbol design, Microsoft's a cup filled with water.

Potable Water was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Potable Water Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Hearts revolving around one or more other hearts. This emoji was originally animated on a number of Japanese devices.
Apple’s artwork for this emoji shows two hearts switching places, with a circular line simulating the action this would make. Google’s artwork previously displayed five hearts in a circle-like shape.

Revolving Hearts was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A yellow sun half covered by a white rain cloud with blue raindrops. Most platforms depict the raindrops falling to the left. Position of the sun varies across platforms.
May be used as a weather icon to represent a mix of sunshine and scattered showers.
Not to be confused with ⛅ Sun Behind Cloud.
Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish.
See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

Sun Behind Rain Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “White Sun Behind Cloud With Rain”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic television set, as people watched before streaming on flatscreens. Depicted in various colors and styles with a screen, knobs, and, on many platforms, rabbit-ear antennae.
Commonly used for television broadcasting as well as various content involving screens, from watching movies to playing video games.
Google’s design features a more modern-looking orange TV; Microsoft’s previous design was a flatscreen.

Television was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A badger, a stocky mammal in the weasel family with a long, pointed head. Generally depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a gray coat, black-and-white-striped face, and short tail.
Google’s design features a friendly, cartoon-styled black-and-white badger face. Facebook’s badger is sitting on its hind legs.

Badger was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Maldives, which may show as the letters MV on some platforms.
The Flag: Maldives emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Maldives was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A pink heart, inside a slightly larger pink heart, inside a larger-again pink heart. Intended to give the impression of a heart increasing in size.

Growing Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A silver fork and knife on either side of a white plate, as set for dinner or another meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon.  

Fork and Knife With Plate was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Index finger pointing downward.

Backhand Index Pointing Down was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “White Down Pointing Backhand Index”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A slice of strawberry shortcake, layered with whipped cream and topped with a whole strawberry. Like the Birthday Cake, may be used to represent birthday celebrations or cake in general.

Shortcake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A bed with a gender-unspecified person sleeping in it, as at a house, hotel, hostel, or other sleeping accommodation. Used especially for various content concerning sleeping as well as beds, furniture, housing, relaxing, and other bedroom activities.
Shown with a headboard at the left and footboard with a person under the covers, head on the pillow. Most platforms suggest a wooden frame and feature blue or red sheets.
The appearance of the person varies. Apple and Facebook's designs show only the hair of the sleeper, Apple's black and Facebook's brown and tousled. Other major vendors show the head of the sleeper in default yellow with short, brown or blonde hair. Skin tone support is not recommended for this emoji, though it is supported on some platforms.
Vendors implement the same style of bed as for their 🛏️ Bed, but with a sleeper in it.

Person in Bed was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Sleeping Accommodation”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A microphone, used to amplify a person’s voice when speaking or singing. Shown with music notes on most platforms, implying it to be used for a singer / singing.

Microphone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Two emoji is a sequence of the 2 Digit Two and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Two was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person snowboarding downhill at a ski resort. Wearing clothing designed for cold climates.

Snowboarder was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Mage was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A trackball, as rotated to control a cursor on a computer. An alternative or supplement to a computer mouse or touchpad. Generally depicted as a cordless device with a blue or red ball in a cylindrical, black or gray socket.
Occasionally used for various content concerning gaming. Google’s design features a cord, Facebook’s a rectangular base.

Trackball was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Jamaica, which may show as the letters JM on some platforms.
The Flag: Jamaica emoji is a sequence of the 🇯 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter J and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Jamaica was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Seven-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Seven-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two fathers, and one son.
The Family: Man, Man, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👨 Man and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Man, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Kenya, which may show as the letters KE on some platforms.
The Flag: Kenya emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Kenya was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A mobile phone (cell phone) with a rightward arrow pointed at it from the left. Intended to indicate an incoming call or message, but used to represent mobile phones, technology, and communication more generally.
Arrow color varies, but is often blue. Vendors implement the same design as 📱 Mobile Phone.

Mobile Phone With Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Mobile Phone With Rightwards Arrow at Left”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man singer or rock star generally displayed with a microphone, and sometimes musical notes.
iOS and Android display this emoji as a Bowie-esque figure while WhatsApp appears heavily inspired by Prince.
The Man Singer emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🎤 Microphone emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Singer was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Mother Christmas, more commonly known as Mrs. Claus, is the wife of Santa Claus. Displayed as an older woman with glasses and a festive red and white bonnet. See also: Christmas emoji list.

Mrs. Claus was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Mother Christmas”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Russia, which may show as the letters RU on some platforms.
The Flag: Russia emoji is a sequence of the 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Russia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A new moon, the first of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a full, bluish- or grayish-black, cratered disc, not illuminated by the sun.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.
See also 🌚 New Moon Face. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Google’s new moon was previously a gray circle with a yellow outline. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a new moon in a night sky with stars.

New Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “New Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Scientist emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🔬 Microscope emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Scientist was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two fathers, and two sons.
The Family: Man, Man, Boy, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👨 Man, 👦 Boy and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Man, Boy, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic camera, as an SLR used to take pictures before camera phones. Generally depicted with a black and silver casing with lens and operating controls.
Commonly used for various content concerning photography as well as an icon for a picture, as before an upload, link, or credit.
See also 📸 Camera With Flash.

Camera was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow, pointing right.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Rightwards Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Black Large Square was approved as part of Unicode 5.1 in 2008
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Translated from Japanese, this means "congratulations" or "pray for happiness".

Japanese “Congratulations” Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Circled Ideograph Congratulation”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
White Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “White Exclamation Mark Ornament”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A couple standing next to each other, smiling, with a pink love heart floating in the air between them. Previously shown as with the same appearance as 👩‍❤️‍👨 Couple With Heart: Woman, Man on most platforms, but now displays two people with an ambiguous gender appearance.

Couple With Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A toothed, wheel-shaped metal gear, as rotates to power machines.
Commonly used for content concerning tools, equipment, and technology in a range of contexts, such as engineering, motor vehicles, and video games. May also represent hard work, e.g., grinding in sports.
Samsung’s design features a stylized, white gear on a green square, as a sign or icon of machinery.

Gear was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An electric plug, as inserted into socket to power a device. Depicted as a black, two-pronged plug at various angles at the end of a cable. Prongs are silver or gold.
Commonly used for various literal and figurative content concerning electricity and power. May also be used for various slang senses of plug, e.g., a connection or hookup.
Apple and WhatsApp’s designs suggest a plug used in North America and Japan while other platforms, including Google and Samsung, suggest one used in Europe and many other parts of the world.

Electric Plug was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A tropical fish, as swims in the warm waters of a coral reef or is kept as a pet in an aquarium. Depicted as a brightly colored fish in full profile facing left, with slender fins. Often shown as a blue-and-yellow fish with stripes, as an angelfish.
May be used to represent a variety of fish (saltwater or freshwater), fishing, metaphorical senses of fish, and fish as food, as consumed in the form of 🍣 Sushi. Not to be confused with 🐟 Fish or 🐡 Blowfish, though their applications may overlap. See also 🎣 Fishing Pole.
Microsoft’s fish is orange with white stripes. Google and Facebook’s fish previously resembled a goldfish. Microsoft’s was previously yellow and blue, Samsung’s black and white.

Tropical Fish was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The face of a girl, smiling. Differentiated from the woman emoji by the hairstyle which features pigtails which are not present on the woman.

Girl was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with a father, mother, and two sons.
The Family: Man, Woman, Boy, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👩 Woman, 👦 Boy and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Woman, Boy, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
An industrial factory, with flue-gas stacks releasing exhaust into the air.

Factory was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Used a decorative bullet-point, the sparkle has both a ❇︎ text and ❇️ emoji presentation available on most platforms.

Sparkle was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😢 Crying Face. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Crying Cat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Crying Cat Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing right. Commonly used as a symbol for play.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.
