Play Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Right-Pointing Triangle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A green heart emoji.
The Android 4.4 artwork for this emoji appeared to show beads of sweat on an orange and pink heart.

Green Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: Bosnia & Herzegovina emoji is a sequence of the 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Bosnia & Herzegovina was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Denmark, which may show as the letters DK on some platforms.
The Flag: Denmark emoji is a sequence of the 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Denmark was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Goggles of a type that are not specified, but implied to be safety goggles instead of swimming goggles.

Goggles was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A package (parcel), as contains items ordered online. Depicted at various angles as a light-brown, cardboard box, with a shipping label and its top taped shut.
Commonly used for content concerning shipping, delivery, and moving as well as for boxes more generally.
Apple’s design features an image of a wine glass, indicating fragile contents, and “this way up” orientation arrows. It was briefly identical to its 🎁 Wrapped Gift.

Package was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for New Zealand, which may show as the letters NZ on some platforms.
The Flag: New Zealand emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: New Zealand was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Libra astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents weighing scales.

Libra was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The back of an envelope, as used to send a letter or card in the mail (post). Generally depicted in white, though Google’s design is yellow. Used for various content concerning mail and messages, including email.
Samsung’s design previously featured a red, wax seal imprinted with the initial M.

Envelope was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A basket, as used for storing or carrying such things as food or clothes. Appearance widely varies across platforms but generally depicted as woven from wicker with one or more handles. Commonly used to represent doing laundry or having a picnic.
Microsoft’s design suggests a laundry basket holding a blue garment or cloth. Apple and WhatsApp’s designs, featuring a white cloth, suggest a bread or picnic basket. Samsung’s design displays green fabric, as knitted from yarn.
Not to be confused with 🗑️ Wastebasket.

Basket was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The distinctive, star-shaped leaf of the maple tree. Depicted as a reddish-orange maple leaf, as has changed color in the fall/autumn, with five pointed segments.
Used as an emblem of Canada, featured on the 🇨🇦 Flag of Canada. Also used to represent trees and the season of fall/autumn more generally.
Microsoft's leaf was previously yellow.

Maple Leaf was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A water buffalo, a bovine used to plough rice fields in parts of Asia. Depicted in gray or black in full profile on all fours facing left, with a tail and broad horns curled up at the tips.
Often used to represent a bull. Not to be confused with 🐂 Ox, though their applications may overlap.
Microsoft’s design was previously brown.

Water Buffalo was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A ripe banana, peeled and ready to eat on major platforms. Great snack for a child or monkey.

Banana was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Means “work” in Japanese.  This Emoji used to mean “open for business” and precedes business hours.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Open for Business” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-55b6”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Austria, which may show as the letters AT on some platforms.
The Flag: Austria emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Austria was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Black Medium Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A face, usually purple, with devil horns, a wide grin, and eyes and eyebrows scrunched downward in the same manner as 😠 Angry Face on most platforms. Google’s design is red and Facebook’s has black horns and green eyes.
Commonly used to convey mischief, naughtiness, and excitement or excellence (slang, bad or wicked). May also represent devils or devilish behavior, especially around Halloween. More playful and suggestive than its impish counterpart, 👿 Angry Face With Horns.
Google and Samsung previously depicted orangish-red characters, with Google once featuring a frown and Samsung a sharp snaggletooth.

Smiling Face With Horns was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Réunion, which may show as the letters RE on some platforms.
Shown as either the Volcano + Sunbeams flag proposal by the Vexillological Association of Réunion, or the blue, white, red stripes + four colored quadrants proposal by the Association for the Réunion Flag.
The Flag For France is the official flag of Réunion. All local flags used are unofficial.
The Flag: Réunion emoji is a sequence of the 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Réunion was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A Tyrannosaurus rex, a massive, meat-eating dinosaur with huge jaws, tiny arms, and a long tail. Depicted as a green or brown tyrannosaur standing on its hind lefts facing left, often with a textured back, sharp teeth, and clawed toes.
May be used to represent various dinosaurs, including raptors. See also 🦕 Sauropod.
Google’s T-Rex resembles a velociraptor. Samsung’s T-Rex was previously red, Facebook’s only a green head with open jaws.

T-Rex was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Similar to a monorail, a suspension railway is elevated, but the vehicle is suspended under the track.

Suspension Railway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A yellow or gold colored love-heart. Inexplicably, this displayed as a pink hairy heart on Android 4.4.
On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes a person that you snap the most, and who also snaps you the most (#1 best friend). The yellow #1 BF heart turns into a red heart after two weeks. A bug in October 2019 has this yellow heart emoji showing instead of 💕 for some Snapchat users.


Yellow Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man dancing, added as a gender pair for the 💃 Woman Dancing. Shown on most platforms in a 70s-era suit, and one hand in the air in a disco-dancing style.

Man Dancing was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A heart shaded completely black. May be used to express morbidity, sorrow, or a form of dark humor.
Not to be confused with the Heavy Black Heart or Black Heart Suit which are both red.

Black Heart was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A crossing sign for children, usually positioned near schools or other areas that drivers should be cautious of young children in the area.

Children Crossing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Blue Circle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Large Blue Circle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A club symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the clubs suit.

Club Suit was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Club Suit”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A human mouth which is generally displayed as a pair of lips and a top row of teeth, instead of the inside of the mouth.
May be used to indicate the spoken word or as an alternative to Kiss Mark.

Mouth was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Suriname, which may show as the letters SR on some platforms.
The Flag: Suriname emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Suriname was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A burger with a beef patty, usually depicted on a sesame bun with cheese, lettuce, and tomato—making it a cheeseburger, though officially called Hamburger by Unicode.
Platforms stack the ingredients in various orders. Google previously placed the cheese under the patty, a "controversy" CEO Sundar Pichai addressed in 2018. 

Hamburger was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A bottle of lotion for the skin, such as moisturizer or sunscreen (sunblock). May be used for other hygienic liquids, including shampoo and body wash, as well as beauty products.
Appearance varies across platforms, but commonly depicted in white and gold colors. Some platforms, like Apple and Twitter, feature a bottle with a pump while others show a cylinder with a cap.

Lotion Bottle was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A dove carrying an olive branch, a symbol of peace in Western and Judeo-Christian culture. Depicted as a white bird in full profile facing left, flying as it holds a green sprig in its beak.
Commonly used to represent such sentiments as peace, love, hope, and reconciliation.
Microsoft’s dove was previously flying right, without an olive branch.

Dove was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Dove of Peace”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person with a ball, which is generally displayed as a basketballer running and dribbling (bouncing) the basketball.

Person Bouncing Ball was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Person With Ball”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Netherlands, which may show as the letters NL on some platforms.
The Flag: Netherlands emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Netherlands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A heart-shaped box, tied with a ribbon. May be a gift box, box of chocolates, or a jewellery box.

Heart With Ribbon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Large Blue Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Small Blue Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The gesture for “I love you” in American Sign Language, shown as a raised pinky (little) finger, index finger, and an extended thumb.

Love-You Gesture was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “I Love You Hand Sign”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A flat, shallow, black pan with side handles, containing saffron-colored rice, vegetables, a leg of poultry, and/or shrimp and lemon slices. Commonly associated with paella, a traditional dish from Spain. May be used for eating, cooking, dining, and meals more generally.
Apple's version of this emoji is considered to be representative of the traditional ingredients from Valencia. Samsung previously displayed this emoji as a Korean hot pot.

Shallow Pan of Food was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Red wine served in a stemmed glass. Google previously displayed an orange-colored drink that resembled cognac.

Wine Glass was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page on a two-ringed, daily desk calendar, as flipped or torn off to change the date. Displays month (usually abbreviated and in a red or blue header) and day on a white, square page, curled up at the bottom right.
Like 📅 Calendar and 🗓️ Spiral Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally.
Apple, Google, Samsung, and JoyPixels's dates show July 17. Apple first featured this date in reference to its calendar app on July 17, 2002; originally known as iCal, the app's icon also displays July 17. Emojipedia so chose July 17 as the date for World Emoji Day, first celebrated in 2014. Several major platforms, including Google and Samsung, have since featured July 17 in honor of the occasion. Other vendors feature easter egg dates marking company founding or other milestones:

📅 Apple: July 17 (Mac iCal announcement in 2002, later World Emoji Day)
📅 Google: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a generic 12, as months in the year)
📅 Microsoft: generic 31 (as number of days in most months)
📅 Samsung: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a generic 31)
📅 WhatsApp: Feb 24 (incorporation of WhatsApp in 2009)
📅 Twitter: March 21 (founding of Twitter in 2006; changed from July 15, when launched)
📅 Facebook: February 4 (date of founding in 2004; previously a generic 31)
📅 JoyPixels: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
📅 emojidex: December 12 (unknown)

Discontinued:

📅 Messenger: August 9 (first release of Messenger apps in 2011)
📅 LG: March 27 (unknown)
📅 HTC: generic 3
📅 Mozilla: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
📅 Softbank: 12 (suggesting the number of months in a year)  
📅 Docomo: 12
📅 au by KDDI: 12


Tear-Off Calendar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Superhero emoji is a sequence of the 🦸 Superhero and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Superhero was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A decorative heart that displays on Apple devices as a white heart-shaped cutout in a pink or purple roundrect.

Heart Decoration was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A kiwifruit, or Chinese gooseberry, with its fuzzy, brown skin sliced open to show its light-green flesh, white core, and black seeds. 
May be associated with New Zealand, whose residents are nicknamed Kiwis, after the bird.

Kiwi Fruit was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Kiwifruit”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A yellow sun mostly covered by a large, white cloud. Position of the sun varies across platforms.
May be used as a weather icon to represent a mostly cloudy day.
Not to be confused with ⛅ Sun Behind Cloud or 🌤️ Sun Behind Small Cloud, though their applications may overlap.
Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish.
See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

Sun Behind Large Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “White Sun Behind Cloud”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🙆 Face With OK Gesture emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Woman Gesturing OK emoji is a sequence of the 🙆 Face With OK Gesture and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Gesturing OK was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A turkey, a gobbling bird traditionally eaten at Thanksgiving or Christmas. Depicted in full profile facing left, standing on its legs with a dark-brown body, a white-fringed plume, pink or blue head, and its distinctive red snood and wattle.
May be consumed in the form of 🍗 Poultry Leg.

Turkey was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman breastfeeding a child. This emoji supports skin tone modifiers, which apply to the mother.
The head of the baby is recommended to be hidden to avoid a situation where the skin tone of the baby would only correlate to the skin tone of the mother.

Breast-Feeding was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Slovakia, which may show as the letters SK on some platforms.
The Flag: Slovakia emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Slovakia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Ethiopia, which may show as the letters ET on some platforms.
The Flag: Ethiopia emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Ethiopia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Santa Claus, sometimes referred to as Father Christmas, brings joy to children at Christmas time. Displayed with a beard and red festive hat.
The Santa emoji had a frown on Android 4.4, which was resolved in Android 5.0. See also: Christmas emoji list.
Note: Father Christmas has a different origin to Santa Claus but both are represented by this single emoji.

Santa Claus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Father Christmas”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A sickly-green face with concerned eyes and puffed, often red cheeks, as if holding back vomit. May represent physical illness or general disgust. Not to be confused with 🤮 Face Vomiting.
Differs from other smileys conveying sickness, including 🤒 Face With Thermometer (used especially for colds and flus) and 🤕 Face With Head-Bandage (physical injury).

Nauseated Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Two rich red cherries with a green leaf and joined at their long stems.
May be used to refer to male or female genitalia.

Cherries was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A mountain shown with two peaks and blue sky. Similar to the snow capped mountain emoji.

Mountain was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Guam, which may show as the letters GU on some platforms.
The Flag: Guam emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Guam was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A campsite featuring a tent and a tree, and perhaps a campfire. Similar to the tent emoji.

Camping was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A new moon with a smiling face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts the moon as a dark disc with a slightly smiling human face and nose.
See also 🌑 New Moon. May be used to represent the moon more generally. Popularly perceived as creepy, used to throw shade (express disapproval), or convey various suggestive or ironic sentiments.
Apple and WhatsApp’s eyes are looking left, as if giving the side-eye. Samsung and Facebook’s faces are looking straight ahead. Google’s facial expression resembles 😏 Smirking Face, Twitter’s 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face.
Google’s face previously evoked Lenny Face, Microsoft’s eyes appeared closed, and Facebook’s face was a simple smiley.

New Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “New Moon With Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A ruler, as used to draw straight lines and measure distances. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic straightedge with length markings at a 45° angle.
Commonly used for content concerning schooling, building, and measurement in various disciplines. May also represent various concepts of straightness and size.

Straight Ruler was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🏃 Runner emoji.
The Woman Running emoji is a sequence of the 🏃 Runner and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Running was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man wearing a turban; a form of customary headwear worn by Sikhs or Muslims.

Person Wearing Turban was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Man With Turban”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A horse, a hoofed mammal used for riding and racing. Depicted as a brown horse in full profile galloping to the left, with a dark, flowing mane and tail.
May be used to represent various types of horses and their metaphorical senses (e.g., mustang, stallion).
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.
Not to be confused with 🐴 Horse Face, 🎠 Carousel Horse, and 🏇 Horse Racing, which features a jockey on its back.
Apple’s horse is wearing a green saddle blanket, Facebook’s a blue blanket with saddle. SoftBank’s design previously featured a racing horse with a jockey.

Horse was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
White Square Button.

White Square Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The back of an envelope, shown coming into an inbox or arriving with motion lines.
Commonly used as an icon for an email address. May also represent posting mail or sending messages more generally.
Apple and WhatsApp’s designs include an inbox tray. Microsoft and Facebook’s designs feature a yellow envelope angled forward and trailed by three, blue lines, indicating sending.
Apple’s design previously featured three red motion lines, Microsoft’s a right arrow.

Incoming Envelope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A waxing crescent moon (appearing to become larger), the second of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its right side illuminated in a thin, golden or silver crescent, its remainder dark.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.
See also 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌘 Waning Crescent Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a crescent moon in a night sky with stars.

Waxing Crescent Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Waxing Crescent Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A traditional coffin, as used to bury the dead. Depicted at various angles as a closed, six-sided, wooden coffin, tapered at the head and foot with golden handles.
Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative death. May also be used for various content concerning funerals, horror, and Halloween.
Apple and Microsoft’s designs place flowers on their lids.

Coffin was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The glittering flashes of sparkles. Generally depicted as a cluster of three, yellow four-point stars, with one large sparkle and two small ones to its left or right.
Commonly used to indicate various positive sentiments, including love, happiness, beauty, gratitude, and excitement. May also be used to convey newness or cleanliness.
Not to be confused with ⭐ Star, 🌟 Glowing Star, or 💫 Dizzy, though their applications may overlap.
Microsoft’s sparkles are multicolored, as Twitter’s previously were. Samsung’s sparkles are depicted on a night sky, suggesting firework sparklers.
Twitter's mobile app uses ✨ Sparkles as a button users can tap to toggle between latest and top tweets on their timeline.

Sparkles was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A palette used by an artist when painting, to store and mix paint colors.

Artist Palette was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Vanuatu, which may show as the letters VU on some platforms.
The Flag: Vanuatu emoji is a sequence of the 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Vanuatu was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
category_emoji_item: 🇬🇸 Flag: South Georgia & South Sandwich Islands
emoji_name: 🇸 Flag: South Georgia & South Sandwich Islands
emoji_description:
The Flag: South Georgia & South Sandwich Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: South Georgia & South Sandwich Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A silver fork to the left of a knife, silverware or cutlery used to eat a meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon or used with Fork and Knife With Plate.

Fork and Knife was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Scorpius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Scorpion.

Scorpio was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Scorpius”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Eight-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Eight-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A national park, generally displayed with mountains, a river or stream, and trees.

National Park was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🕵 Sleuth or Spy emoji.
The Woman Detective emoji is a sequence of the 🕵 Sleuth or Spy and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Detective was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two arrows pointing right while crossing over one another. Used to indicate putting music on shuffle: randomizing the order of tracks in the upcoming playlist. May also be used to indicate two items switching places.

Shuffle Tracks Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Twisted Rightwards Arrows”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Italy, which may show as the letters IT on some platforms.
The Flag: Italy emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Italy was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Two swords with steel blades in an X shape, as crossed for combat between two knights or warriors. Generally depicted as straight, double-edged blades with brown or black, cross-shaped hilts, points directed up. Commonly used as a symbol for battle, fighting, or a contest, as in sports.
Sometimes shown with golden handles. Several vendors implement the same design as for their 🗡️ Dagger. Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white swords on a green square, as a sign or icon of war.
May be paired with (or defended by) 🛡️ Shield. Not to be confused with ⚒️ Hammer and Pick or 🛠️ Hammer and Wrench.

Crossed Swords was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Boo! A white, cartoon ghost making a silly face. Its tongue is stuck out and arms are outstretched, as if trying to scare someone in a friendly way. Several platforms feature one larger, bulging eye. 
Resembles a classic ghost costume for Halloween. May also be used to convey something or someone is fun or goofy. Thanks to its raised arms, some use this emoji as a way of expressing an excited Yay!
Samsung's design previously depicted this as a smiley in a ghost costume.

Ghost was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😡 Pouting Face. Also resembles 😠 Angry Face. Depicted as yellow on major platforms. Sometimes used to represent the internet meme and celebrity Grumpy Cat.
Apple’s design previously displayed the face in profile.

Pouting Cat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Pouting Cat Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A night sky with stars, depicted on major platforms as a cityscape at night.

Night With Stars was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The ripe fruit of a tropical mango. Variously depicted in shades of yellow, red, orange, and green with a single, green leaf and stem.

Mango was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic hourglass, its sand still flowing from the top to bottom bulb. Indicates time is still passing—but life is short. Color varies across platforms.
Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with ⌛ Hourglass Done, whose sand has stopped flowing.

Hourglass Not Done was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Hourglass With Flowing Sand”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face placing an index finger over pursed lips, as if issuing Shh! or Shush! for silence. Some platforms feature raised eyebrows. Apple’s design suggests the face is tilting back slightly. 
May convey silence, quiet, secrecy, and discreetness. May also create a sense of buzz and anticipation, e.g., an exclusive sneak peek or news scoop.
See also 🤐 Zipper-Mouth Face. Joins 🤗 Hugging Face, 🤔 Thinking Face, and 🤭 Face With Hand Over Mouth as one of the few smileys featuring hands.

Shushing Face was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Face With Finger Covering Closed Lips”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Eleven O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Eleven O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An upset person, frowning with dismay. Gender is not specified, but generally shown as a woman.
Previously displayed as a man on Samsung and Microsoft platforms.

Person Frowning was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A kangaroo, a marsupial with a large tail and legs. Depicted in yellowish-brown in full profile facing left with large, pointed ears, shown either resting on its hind legs and tail or jumping.
Commonly used in connection with Australia, where the animal is found.

Kangaroo was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A set of tabbed dividers or file guides, as used to organize a card index or file box. Depicted with three or more multicolored tabs on manila paper.
Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files, organization, and various types of data, information, and professional or academic work.
WhatsApp’s design features tabbed index cards. Samsung’s design previously suggested a blue, multi-tabbed file folder.

Card Index Dividers was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Six O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Six O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A frosted cake with lit candles, as presented for a birthday celebration. The style of cake widely varies across platforms. With white frosting and strawberries, Apple and Google’s designs suggest a Japanese Christmas cake. Other vendors depict a chocolate, pink, and/or sponge cake.

Birthday Cake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face screaming in fear, depicted by wide, white eyes, a long, open mouth, hands pressed on cheeks, and a pale blue forehead, as if it has lost its color. Its expression evokes Edvard Munch’s iconic painting The Scream.
While intended to represent horror and fright, it commonly conveys such feelings as shock, awe, disbelief, and intense excitement, as a screaming fan.
Samsung’s design previously featured a ghost flying from its mouth. 🙀 Weary Cat Face bears a similar expression.

 Face Screaming in Fear was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A skateboard emoji, shown on some platforms from the top and others showing the under-side of the board.
Emojipedia's sample image was modelled after Tony Hawk's skateboard.

Skateboard was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A fist displayed in a position to punch someone, or to fist-bump another person.
Shown as a right hand on all supported platforms. An equivalent left-handed version does not exist.

Oncoming Fist was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Fisted Hand Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Honduras, which may show as the letters HN on some platforms.
The Flag: Honduras emoji is a sequence of the 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Honduras was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for China, which may show as the letters CN on some platforms.
The Flag: China emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: China was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🏋 Weight Lifter emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Lifting Weights emoji is a sequence of the 🏋 Weight Lifter and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Lifting Weights was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Copyright was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Copyright Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A shield, as blocks swords in close combat. Color and style varies across platforms, but generally depicted in a kite shape with a metal border and simple pattern.
Commonly used to represent various content concerning battle, defense, security, and protection.
Apple and Microsoft’s designs feature a red and white sawtooth pattern, Facebook and WhatsApp’s blue and white checkers.
May be paired with (or fending off) ⚔️ Crossed Swords or 🗡️ Dagger. Not to be confused with 🔰 Japanese Symbol for Beginner.

Shield was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Three, light blue droplets, as sweat beads, splashing down to the right. Resembles plewds, stylized sweat droplets used in comics and animation to show characters working hard or feeling stressed.
May be used to represent various types of liquids, including sexual fluids. May also be used to represent various liquid-based slang expressions (e.g., drip, “exceptional style, swagger").
Not to be confused with 💧 Droplet, though their applications may overlap.
Google, Microsoft, and Samsung's design previously featured two, upwardly directed droplets.

Sweat Droplets was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Splashing Sweat Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
An Aerial Tramway, most commonly seen at ski resorts, for transport between locations on a mountain. Can also be used as a tourist attraction, or as a form of public transport.

Aerial Tramway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Used as an alternative to a check (tick) in Japan for a something that is correct. The opposite of an X (cross mark) for something wrong.

Hollow Red Circle was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Heavy Large Circle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Badminton was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Badminton Racquet and Shuttlecock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A bag full of money. Depicted as a sack, usually tan, tied off and displaying a dollar sign. May be filled with coins, as most platforms show a rounded bag.
Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money. 

Money Bag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Facepalming emoji is a sequence of the 🤦 Face Palm and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Facepalming was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A jewel or gem, as set into a ring. Depicted in the shape of a classic diamond but in the bright blue color of an aquamarine.
Commonly used for various content concerning jewelry, as upon an engagement or marriage. May also convey various literal and figurative senses of beauty, wealth, sophistication, preciousness, and sparkling.

Gem Stone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a broad, closed smile wearing black sunglasses, as if a pair of classic Wayfarers. Often used to convey the slang sense of cool. May also express a confident, carefree attitude or that something is excellent.
🤓 Nerd Face wears similarly shaped eyeglasses.
On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you have best friends in common with this person.

Smiling Face With Sunglasses was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two human footsteps,  showing the outline of both feet, including all five toes.

Footprints was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A shrine used for the Japanese Shinto religion. This emoji generally displays the torii, which is the gate to the Shinto Shrine. The torii is generally a red colored structure, with a curved roof section above two posts.
This icon is used on maps in Japan to represent the location of a Shinto Shrine, similar to how the hot springs emoji is the icon used on Japanese maps to show the location of an onsen.

Shinto Shrine was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman with arms crossed forming an ‘X’ to indicate ‘no’ or ‘no good’. This motion is used on the TV game show Deal or No Deal to indicate ‘No Deal’. Intended to be gender-neutral but shown as a woman on most platforms.
The Woman Gesturing No emoji is a sequence of the 🙅 Face With No Good Gesture and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.


Woman Gesturing No was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
This emoji means “full” in Japanese, usually used to denote “full capacity” such as a gas/petrol tank on a car or pre-paid phone card.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “No Vacancy” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6e80”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A baked dish with a pastry crust, filled with sweet or savory ingredients. Appearance widely varies by platform. Apple depicts a whole pie in a tin, its crimped crust scored to let out steam. Google shows a slice of pumpkin pie as served at Thanksgiving, WhatsApp and Twitter a slice of cherry pie.

Pie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A sunflower, a tall, round flower with large yellow petals. Depicted as a single, vertical sunflower with a large, dark-brown center on a green stem.
Commonly used for Mother’s Day and other special occasions. May be more generally used to convey such sentiments happiness and love. Also used as a yellow accent color and in association with summer and farming.
Not to be confused with 🌼 Blossom, which is yellow on many platforms.

Sunflower was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Ceuta, Melilla, which may show as the letters EA on some platforms. Uses the same flag as Spain.
The Flag: Ceuta & Melilla emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Ceuta & Melilla was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A minidisc, depicted as a small, silver or gold optical disc housed in a square cartridge, its shutter positioned to the right.
Discontinued as an audio and data storage format in 2013 due to the success of CD and MP3 technology, though the emoji is commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, and related film and music content, especially albums.
Samsung’s design previously featured a silver disc labeled MD, for minidisc. Early designs from au by KDDI showed an angled 💾 Floppy Disk, perhaps as being inserted or ejected into a computer drive.
See also 💿 Optical Disc and 📀 DVD.

Computer Disk was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Minidisc”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A plate of Italian spaghetti with tomato sauce, as a bolognese, with a fork twirling its long, thin noodles. Garnished with a green herb, as parsley, on some platforms.

Spaghetti was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with soft, closed eyes, raised eyebrows, and a slight smile. Facebook’s design features a slightly open mouth, as if sighing.
Conveys various pleasant feelings, including contentment, calm, peace, and relief. May also convey feelings of happiness or good-natured humor more generally.
Google and Microsoft previously included sweat beads. Not to be confused with 😔 Pensive Face, which has similarly shaped eyes but in a sadder expression.

Relieved Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A comet, an icy, rocky space object that can form a tail of gas and dust when near the sun. Generally depicted as an icy-blue comet, as if streaking downwards in a night sky.
May be used for meteors and other celestial bodies, as well as for content concerning space more generally. Also occasionally used for flair or flourish.
Not to be confused with 🌠 Shooting Star, though their applications may overlap.
Samsung’s comet is fiery-red, as is Apple’s, which appears to be ascending. WhatsApp’s comet is depicted in a starry, night sky, Apple’s comet was previously descending and blue.

Comet was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A sign indicating the location of a bus stop by the side of a road.
Some platforms display this as a red, white and blue sign which can be found in parts of Japan. This interpretation has a slight resemblance to the Pepsi Globe.
Other platforms base this emoji design on bus stop signage of other regions.

Bus Stop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A merperson who may be referred to as merfolk or merpeople in plural. May be used for the display of a mermaid, mergirl, merwoman, or merman.

Merperson was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and puckered lips giving a kiss. Commonly conveys sentiments of love and affection.
Like 😗 Kissing Face, this emoji is sometimes taken to represent whistling, especially when paired with a musical note. May convey such feelings as surprise, admiration, contempt, or feigned innocence, as a person with hands in pocket casually whistling after wrongdoing, as if saying Nothing to look at here.
With its smiling eyes, features an expression fonder than 😗 Kissing Face's but less intimate than 😚 Kissing Face With Closed Eyes's.

Kissing Face With Smiling Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the front, as opposed to the taxi emoji which displays the side of the vehicle.

Oncoming Taxi was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Ascension Island, which may show as the letters AC on some platforms. This same flag is used for St. Helena and Tristan Da Cunha.
The Flag: Ascension Island emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Ascension Island was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
CL is what shows on the CLear button of some older mobile phones.

CL Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CL”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The pod of the peanut, shown in its rounded, grooved, light-brown shell. Apple depicts a pair.
May be used for peanut butter as well as other edible nuts (e.g., almonds) or metaphorical ones, including slang for “crazy” and “testicle.”

Peanuts was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A small bus or minivan designed to carry fewer people than a full-sized bus. Displayed in white on most platforms (green on Facebook).

Minibus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A lobster, a large crustacean with a prominent tail and pincers. Depicted as a reddish-orange lobster (as cooked) from above, with a long body and tail, short, tentacle-like eyes, and ten legs, the top of which are very large pincers.
Often used to represent lobster as food as well as in connection to the US state of Maine.
In its release year of 2018, Emojipedia’s original sample image was criticized as anatomically incorrect but was shortly after resolved. That year, the transgender community embraced the lobster as a symbol for their efforts for Transgender Flag emoji.
Samsung, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s lobsters are depicted at an angle.

Lobster was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
A triangular red flag on a post. Most commonly associated with golf, as shown in the flag in hole emoji.

Triangular Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Triangular Flag on Post”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man dressed for a formal occassion, wearing a tuxedo. This emoji may be used as the gender pair for the bride emoji.

Man in Tuxedo was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A stick-figure icon of a man, generally used to indicate a male restroom. The female equivalent is the Womens Symbol emoji.

Men’s Room was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Mens Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Used in a similar manner to a regular * asterisk character but tends to be shown in a similar vertical alignment to a • bullet point. The eight spoked asterisk has both a ✳︎ text and ✳️ emoji presentation available on most platforms.

Eight-Spoked Asterisk was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Eight Spoked Asterisk”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
This emoji means to own or posses.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Not Free of Charge” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6709”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A present or gift in a box tied with a bow, as given on a birthday or Christmas. Box and ribbon color vary across platforms, but commonly depicted as a gold box with a lid wrapped with a red ribbon.
Commonly used to represent gifts and presents on various holidays, celebrations, and special occasions.
Samsung’s design features a red ribbon tied around a blue box with white dots. WhatsApp’s present is wrapped with blue paper and red ribbon.

Wrapped Gift was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Wrapped Present”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A closed, hardcover book, depicted with a red, front-facing cover on most platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a red accent color.
Apple’s cover features the easter egg Vol. 1 by John Appleseed. Google’s design features a brown cover with a red bookmark, and Samsung’s artwork a blue cover printed with the initials HYDM.

Closed Book was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A white baseball, with regulation red stitching. Used in the game of the same name, baseball.

Baseball was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A waxing gibbous moon (appearing more than half full and getting larger), the fourth of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, mostly illuminated in gold or silver, but with its left side a dark crescent.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.
Not to be confused with 🌖 Waning Gibbous Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning gibbous moon in a night sky with stars.

Waxing Gibbous Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Waxing Gibbous Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A crystal ball, as a fortune teller or clairvoyant gazes into to tell the future. Depicted as a sparkling, purple or blue crystal orb resting on a stand.
Commonly used for various content concerning magic, alternative spirituality, and (predicting) the future. May also be used for its shape or color more generally.

Crystal Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A last quarter moon with a human face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts a wide, golden crescent moon with the profile of slightly smiling human face with a nose, facing right.
May be used to represent the moon more generally and saying good night.
See also 🌗 Last Quarter Moon and 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌛 First Quarter Moon Face, though their applications may overlap.
WhatsApp’s eyes are looking back. Facebook’s moon is silver but was previously golden; Twitter’s was previously silver. Google’s eyes were previously closed.

Last Quarter Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Last Quarter Moon With Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Sheets of white, printed paper with variously colored tabs to bookmark important sections or indicate signature lines. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.
The number of pages and tabs vary, with Microsoft and Twitter’s designs featuring one page with a single, purple-colored tab. Facebook’s is printed with NDA, or nondisclosure agreement. Most platforms indicate text with dark lines. Apple’s design features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie and signed Take care from John Appleseed with the text of its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:
Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.
Early designs from au by KDDI resemble 📃 Page With Curl.
Not to be confused with 📄 Page Facing Up or other emojis featuring sheets of paper.

Bookmark Tabs was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet and/or rope. The Emojipedia Sample image was created with assistance from World Champion Rock Climber Sasha DiGiulian.
Variations exist for 🧗‍♀️ Woman Climbing and 🧗‍♂️ Man Climbing.

Person Climbing was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Zimbabwe, which may show as the letters ZW on some platforms.
The Flag: Zimbabwe emoji is a sequence of the 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Zimbabwe was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A glowing, five-point gold star. Depicted as ⭐ Star with stylized bursts in between its points, representing glowing or twinkling.
Commonly used to represent various senses of glowing as well for as for a sense of flourish. Not to be confused with 💫 Dizzy, ⭐ Star, 🌠 Shooting Star, or ✨ Sparkles, though their applications may overlap.
On Snapchat, this emoji displays next to a contact who has had their snaps replayed in the past 24 hours.
Microsoft’s bursts are blue lines, though were previously yellow. Apple’s star previously resembled its ⭐ Star. Samsung’s star previously displayed a burst radiating out from its center.

Glowing Star was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A grotesque, red face with horns, wide eyes, a large nose, crooked fangs, and a fringe of shaggy hair. Depicts an oni, a kind of hideous ogre in Japanese folklore.
On New Year’s Eve in some parts of Japan, men may wear oni masks and straw coats to dress up as namahage, another mythic being, to chide naughty children or ward off evil. May popularly denote supernatural or figurative beasts and demons.

Ogre was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Japanese Ogre”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A European-style post office. A postal horn can be seen on the front, which is commonly found in the logos of European Postal Services.

Post Office was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “European Post Office”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Tunisia, which may show as the letters TN on some platforms.
The Flag: Tunisia emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Tunisia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Two parallel lengths of silver chain. Occasionally used as an icon before a hyperlink or for metaphorical connections or chains, e.g., slang off the chains.
Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white chains in a blue square, as a sign or icon for snow chains for winter driving.
Not to be confused with 🔗 Link, 📎 Paperclip, 🖇️ Linked Paperclips, or 🧷 Safety Pin.

Chains was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A bowl of steamed white rice, a staple component of cuisine throughout Asia. Bowl color varies across platforms, though is often white.

Cooked Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A dolphin, a sleek marine mammal known to be social and intelligent. Generally depicted as a light-blue dolphin with a white belly in full profile facing left, its short snout curving down to a prominent dorsal fin and tail, as a bottlenose dolphin leaping in the air.
May be used for various content concerning swimming, oceans, beaches, and summer fun. Not be confused with 🦈 Shark.
WhatsApp and Facebook’s dolphins are gray, as Microsoft and Samsung’s previously were.

Dolphin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A ladybug (ladybird, lady beetle), a beetle with a round, red shell with black spots. Generally depicted as a seven- or nine-spotted ladybug shown from above on its six legs, with antennae and its distinctively red-and-black, halved shell.
May be used a symbol of good luck.
Facebook’s ladybug is shown on its legs facing forward.

Lady Beetle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A locked (closed) padlock with a fountain pen or nib positioned at various angles in front of it. Vendors implement the same design as their 🔒 Locked and the same or similar design as their 🖋️ Fountain Pen or ✒️ Black Nib.
May represent digital certificates in public-key technology. May also have similar applications as 🔒 Locked (privacy, security) and 🖋️ Fountain Pen or ✒️ Black Nib (writing, signing).
Apple’s design previously displayed a nib, Google’s a full pen.
This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Locked With Pen was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Lock With Ink Pen”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-right, or north-east direction.

Up-Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “North East Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A peanut-shaped sponge, as used for cleaning or bathing. Generally depicted in yellow and at different angles across platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, and cleaning.

Sponge was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A full moon with a smiling face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts the moon as a dark disc with a slightly smiling human face and nose.
See also 🌕 Full Moon. May be used to represent the moon more generally. Commonly used a smiley. Occasionally used for irony and sarcasm.
Apple and WhatsApp’s eyes are looking left, as if giving the side-eye. Samsung and Facebook’s faces are looking straight ahead. Google’s facial expression resembles 😏 Smirking Face, Twitter’s 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face.
Google’s face previously evoked Lenny Face, Microsoft’s eyes appeared to be closed, Twitter’s resembled its 🌚 New Moon Face, and Facebook’s face was a simple, yellow smiley.

Full Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Full Moon With Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Male royalty, intended as a gender pair for the princess emoji. Shown as a man with a crown.
Not a reference to the musician Prince, however the man singer emoji on WhatsApp does show a character that bears a heavy resemblance to this artist.

Prince was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A baby chicken (chick), shown as if flapping its wings. Depicted as a yellow chick with an orange beak in full profile standing on its legs, generally with its wings raised.
Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent various types of baby birds. May also be used to represent chicken foods (e.g., poultry, eggs), spring, Easter, or slang senses of chick.
Not to be confused with 🐤 Baby Chick or 🐣 Hatching Chick (still in its egg), though their applications overlap. See also 🐔 Chicken and 🐓 Rooster.
Facebook's design previously featured only a chick head facing forward.

Front-Facing Baby Chick was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🙆 Face With OK Gesture emoji.
The Man Gesturing OK emoji is a sequence of the 🙆 Face With OK Gesture and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Gesturing OK was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a sly, smug, mischievous, or suggestive facial expression. It features a half-smile, raised eyebrows, and eyes looking to the side. Often used to convey flirtation or sexual innuendo.
Not to be confused with 😒 Unamused Face, which has similar eyes but a pouting mouth. This emoji has a cat variant, 😼 Cat Face With Wry Smile.
On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that this person snaps you frequently but you do not often snap them in return.

Smirking Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A cricket bat, with a cricket ball also shown. May be displayed with a wicket present.

Cricket Game was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Cricket Bat and Ball”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Cyprus, which may show as the letters CY on some platforms.
