The Flag: Cyprus emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Cyprus was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A large red cross mark, displayed in the shape of a letter X and similar to a multiplication sign.

Cross Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A slice of pepperoni pizza, topped with black olives on Google. WhatsApp adds green pepper, Samsung white onion.

Pizza was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Slice of Pizza”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A bicycle with a red stroke through it, indicating that bikes are prohibited from this location.
May be seen in pedestrian malls with a bicycle restriction or crossing train tracks in some countries.

No Bicycles was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A first quarter moon with a human face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts a wide, golden crescent moon with the profile of a slightly smiling human face with a nose, facing left.
May be used to represent the moon more generally and saying good night.
See also 🌓 First Quarter Moon and 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌜 Last Quarter Moon Face, though their applications may overlap.
WhatsApp’s eyes are looking back. Facebook’s moon is silver but was previously golden; Twitter’s was previously silver. Google’s eyes were previously closed.

First Quarter Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “First Quarter Moon With Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An antique-styled mantel clock with a flat base and rounded case, as made of wood and brass and placed above a fireplace.
Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also suggest a traditional home or old-time environment. 
Samsung’s design features a more modern-looking, blue clock.

Mantelpiece Clock was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An opened, dry umbrella. Generally depicted with purple fabric and a hooked handle.
Commonly used for various content concerning rainy weather. Occasionally used as a purple accent color.
Not to be confused with ☔ Umbrella With Rain Drops or 🌂 Closed Umbrella, though their applications may overlap.
WhatsApp’s umbrella is green. Google’s umbrella was previously blue, Microsoft and Samsung’s once red.

Umbrella was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An icon representing vibration mode on a mobile phone, indicating that a phone should be switched to silent and/or vibrate mode.
Displayed as a phone with either zig-zag lines or muted-bell icon on most platforms. Early versions of this emoji often used a heart alongside a mobile phone, as commonly seen in Japan.

Vibration Mode was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A single human eye, looking forward. This eye is in a different shape and style to the pair of eyes, which are more rounded, and looking to one side.

Eye was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Person Playing Handball was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Handball”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Guatemala, which may show as the letters GT on some platforms.
The Flag: Guatemala emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Guatemala was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Transgender Flag is a draft candidate for Emoji 13.0.
A number of platforms include this emoji but do not show it on the emoji keyboard. This can be used on supported platforms by copying and pasting the sequence below.
If included in the final release of Emoji 13.0, this emoji will be supported on major platforms in the second half of 2020, in additions to the platforms listed here.
The Transgender Flag emoji is a sequence of the 🏳 Waving White Flag and ⚧️ Male with Stroke and Male and Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Transgender Flag was added to draft Emoji 13.0 in 2019.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An open, hardcover book, often depicted with a blue cover. Some platforms include a bookmark. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling.
Apple’s design displays text from its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:
Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes.The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. And they have no respect for the status quo. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is…

Open Book was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010

and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A hammer and wrench, as kept in a toolbox, crossed in an X shape. Depicted with metal tools facing up, the hammer positioned at the upper left. Most vendors implement the same design as for their 🔨 Hammer and 🔧 Wrench.
Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, construction, and work, both manual and digital.

Hammer and Wrench was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Ten-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Ten-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
One O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face One O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Capricorn astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Goat.

Capricorn was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed.

High-Speed Train was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 👯 Woman With Bunny Ears emoji.
The Men With Bunny Ears emoji is a sequence of the 👯 Woman With Bunny Ears and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Men With Bunny Ears was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A bus used for public transport in cities and towns. Could also be used as a school bus.

Bus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A name badge, used to identify oneself in a location that others may not know your name, such as a school trip, or a work conference.
This tulip-shaped name badge is one of many designs commonly found at kindergartens in Japan.

Name Badge was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Burkina Faso, which may show as the letters BF on some platforms.
The Flag: Burkina Faso emoji is a sequence of the 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Burkina Faso was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A monkey, a small primate with long limbs and tail for climbing trees. Generally depicted as a cartoon-styled, brown monkey with a cheeky facial expression, shown in full profile facing left, sitting on its hind legs with a long, curled tail and round ears.
As with 🐵 Monkey Face, often used with a playful tone or for metaphorical senses of monkey.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.
WhatsApp’s monkey is facing right, Facebook’s has shaggy hair.

Monkey was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A banded stack of euro banknotes, the paper currency of the European Union (EU). Color and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the euro sign, €. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the EU.
Some vendors, including Apple and Samsung, depict green €100 bills; others, including Google, WhatsApp, and Facebook, depict blue €20 bills. Facebook additionally features the EU flag.

Euro Banknote was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Banknote With Euro Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with raised eyebrows and a slight frown, shedding a single, blue tear from one eye down its cheek. May convey a moderate degree of sadness or pain, usually less intensely than 😭 Loudly Crying Face.
Not to be confused with 😥 Sad but Relieved Face, 😪 Sleepy Face, or other emojis with tear or sweat droplets. Samsung’s design previously featured tears welling up in both eyes.
This emoji has a cat variant, 😿 Crying Face.

Crying Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Multiple houses.

Houses was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “House Buildings”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
An orange-colored citrus fruit with a green leaf or leaves and stem. Officially depicting a tangerine, a type of mandarin (mikan in Japan). Often used as a garden-variety orange. Either way, a good source of vitamin C.

Tangerine was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A train, of no specified type. Due to the presence of a steam train and fast train emoji, this is likely to be a regular electrified or diesel passenger train.

Train was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A sun rising, early in the morning. Can be difficult to distinguish from a sunset in some versions of this artwork.

Sunrise was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A pedestrian symbol with a red stroke through it, indicating that pedestrians are prohibited from this location.
May be seen in dedicated bike lanes, highways, or other areas not suitable to be on-foot.

No Pedestrians was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A rectangular map of the world. Generally depicted as a paper map creased at its folds, Earth’s surface shown in green on blue ocean.
Commonly represent maps, travel, exploration, and geography. May also represent various content concerning the world as a whole, e.g., global or international issues.
Microsoft and Samsung’s design previously depicted outlines of the continents.

World Map was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🙋 Happy Person Raising One Hand emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Woman Raising Hand emoji is a sequence of the 🙋 Happy Person Raising One Hand and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Raising Hand was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Moon Viewing Ceremonies (called Tsukimi in Japan) are held each year in autumn to celebrate the full moon and waxing moon in Japan.
This symbol shows Japanese pampas grass and dango (sweet dessert food) which are used in the ceremony, as well as the moon in the background.

Moon Viewing Ceremony was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A gold crown with jewels on the sides. Representative of a King, Queen, or other form of Royalty.

Crown was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A locked (closed) padlock with an upright key at its right. Vendors implement the same designs as their 🔒 Locked and 🔑 Key.
May represent digital keys in public-key technology. May have similar applications as 🔒 Locked (privacy, security) and 🔑 Key (means of access, "crucial"). Sometimes used to represent a locket to symbolize romantic love and commitment.
Apple’s design previously featured the easter egg UM242 on its key, a reference to locks on Herman Miller office furniture. Facebook’s design once displayed a silver key, its head at the bottom.
This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Locked With Key was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Closed Lock With Key”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A hand held up showing its palm. May be used to mean stop, or as a high-five.

Raised Hand was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A hero which may be displayed as a man,woman or gender-neutral / gender-inclusive depending on the platform. This base emoji does not specify a gender, but is used to create the emojis for Man Superhero and Woman Superhero.
The Supervillain is the nemesis of this emoji.

Superhero was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Firework emoji, showing a explosion of colored light in the night sky, used for any number of celebrations such as New Year's Eve.
Colors vary by platform, and may include pink, purple, yellow, blue, and green.

Fireworks was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Falkland Islands (Malvinas), which may show as the letters FK on some platforms.
The Flag: Falkland Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Falkland Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Kyrgyzstan, which may show as the letters KG on some platforms.
The Flag: Kyrgyzstan emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Kyrgyzstan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person dancing, most commonly displayed as woman with one arm raised wearing a red dress, while dancing the salsa or flamenco. Often used to represent a sense of fun or as a positive affirmation, e.g. "great! 💃"
This emoji did not originally specify a gender, but was canonically deemed a woman when the 🕺 Man Dancing emoji was approved. Google previously displayed this emoji as a man, then a gender-neutral blob character (in keeping with guidelines at the time).
Microsoft previously displayed this emoji as stick figure, and Samsung has displayed this over various releases as a white boy, black boy, and white girl.

Woman Dancing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Dancer”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A gold or yellow bell with a red line through it, which is commonly used on mobile phones as an icon for the silencing of notifications or ringing sounds. A mute, or silent mode.

Bell With Slash was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Bell With Cancellation Stroke”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A thundercloud. Depicted as a yellow lightning bolt flashing from a white cloud.
May be used as a weather icon to represent thunderstorms.
Not to be confused with ⛈️ Cloud With Lightning and Rain, though their applications may overlap.
Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish with two lightning bolts.

Cloud With Lightning was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A squid, an octopus-like sea animal with ten arms. Generally depicted as a pinkish-orange giant squid, facing forward or angled to the left, with a slender, arrow-like body, small eyes, and two, long arms raised up at its sides. Platforms generally depict six arms.
Occasionally used to represent squid as a food item. Not to be confused with 🐙 Octopus, though their applications may overlap.
Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Twitter’s squids are facing forward. Samsung’s squid was previously gray.

Squid was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A supernatural being, which is generally shown to be imprisoned within a bottle or lamp. May be capable of granting wishes when summoned. Variations exist for a female genie or male genie.

Genie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Solomon Islands, which may show as the letters SB on some platforms.
The Flag: Solomon Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Solomon Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A racing car which appears as a formula one vehicle or rally car on most platforms. Generally displayed in red.
Apple's version of this emoji features the Swift (programming language) logo on the side.

Racing Car was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Grenada, which may show as the letters GD on some platforms.
The Flag: Grenada emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Grenada was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Albania, which may show as the letters AL on some platforms.
The Flag: Albania emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Albania was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: Pitcairn Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Pitcairn Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person going for a walk. Taking a slow-medium pace, this person would be a runner if they picked up their speed.
This emoji does not specify a gender, but is shown as a man on most major platforms.

Person Walking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Pedestrian”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Svalbard & Jan Mayen, which may show as the letters SJ on some platforms. This is the same flag as Norway.
The Flag: Svalbard & Jan Mayen emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇯 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter J emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Svalbard & Jan Mayen was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Representation of hot springs with steam rising from a circular tub. This is the common symbol used to represent an onsen on maps in Japan.

Hot Springs was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Prescription glasses, shown with a variety of frames, depending on platform.

Glasses was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Eyeglasses”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A reddish-orange face with furrowed eyebrows, tongue stuck out, and beads of sweat, as if overheated from high temperatures. Number and position of sweat droplets vary by platforms. May also represent physical attractiveness (slang, hot).
Most platforms feature expressions that are variations on 😰 Anxious Face With Sweat or 😥 Sad but Relieved Face.  

Hot Face was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Overheated Face”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-left, or south-west direction.

Down-Left Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “South West Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A school bag Emoji (also called a satchel) used by children attending school to carry books, lunch, and other personal belongings.

Backpack was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “School Satchel”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A steam train, powered by coal or wood. An early type of locomotive, now mostly replaced by electric or diesel trains.
Oddly, this emoji does not show any steam coming from the train.

Locomotive was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Steam Locomotive”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The fruit of a rich red strawberry dotted with seeds and crowned with green leaves. Google previously depicted the fruit in orange.

Strawberry was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man standing in front of a chalkboard (aka blackboard) with the intention of teaching a class.
See also: 👩‍🏫 Female Teacher
The Man Teacher emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🏫 School emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Teacher was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A palm tree, a tree-like plant, as grows by the sea. Depicted as a palm tree with long, green, feather-like leaves and a tall, brown, segmented trunk.
May be used to represent beaches, tropical climates and cultures, summer fun, and vacations (holidays). Vendors implement a similar tree in their 🏝️ Desert Island.
Microsoft’s palm tree bears coconuts, as Samsung’s previously did. Apple’s palm tree previously had more erect palms.

Palm Tree was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A deciduous tree, whose leaves change color before shedding, as 🍂 Fallen Leave, in the fall/autumn. Depicted as a generic tree with a round, lush, leafy top and brown trunk.
May be used to represent various types of trees, forests, temperate climates, nature, and the seasons of spring and summer.

Deciduous Tree was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A bride in traditional western wedding dress with a veil on her head. This veil is white for the Apple emoji, pink in the Google emoji and blue in Microsoft’s emoji.

Bride With Veil was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The face of a princess; a girl or woman wearing a small crown or tiara. Could also be used to represent a Queen or other royalty.

Princess was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A pair of equal-length chopsticks, an eating utensil used throughout East Asia. Design and color vary widely by platform, though often red or wood-colored and with tips angled together. Featured in many platforms' Steaming Bowl of Food and Takeout Box. A counterpart to utensils such as Fork and Knife and Spoon.

Chopsticks was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A keyboard, as used to type on a computer. Generally depicted as a gray device with white or black keys. Used for various content concerning computers, typing, and writing.
Apple’s design resembles the company’s Magic Keyboard. Microsoft's design is blue.
Not to be confused with 🎹 Musical Keyboard.

Keyboard was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A small section of a music keyboard, which differs from a computer keyboard.
Showing white and black keys, this keyboard is played by a pianist to make music. Commonly used as a piano emoji.

Musical Keyboard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A gold or yellow bell, which is commonly used on mobile phones as an icon for notifications or ringing sounds.

Bell was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An old-fashioned key, as opens an antique chest or wardrobe. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a tarnished, silver skeleton key with an ornate, bowed head and two-toothed bit at the bottom left.
Like 🔑 Key, often used figuratively, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial"). May also be applied to antiques.
Microsoft’s design is gold, with the head at the upper left. Samsung and Facebook’s keys were previously gold.

Old Key was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Palau, which may show as the letters PW on some platforms.
The Flag: Palau emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Palau was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Facepalming emoji is a sequence of the 🤦 Face Palm and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Facepalming was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Greece, which may show as the letters GR on some platforms.
The Flag: Greece emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Greece was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Kosovo, which may show as the letters XK on some platforms.
The Flag: Kosovo emoji is a sequence of the 🇽 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter X and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Kosovo was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A dromedary camel, a long-necked mammal with one large hump on its back. Depicted in light or yellowish brown in full profile on all fours facing left.
Not to be confused with 🐫 Two-Hump Camel (Bactrian), though their applications generally overlap.
May be used in association with deserts, the Middle East, and Wednesday (Hump Day).
Samsung’s design features a camel with a shaggy head of hair and slight smile. Google’s design previously featured a blanket on its back, as for transport.

Camel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Dromedary Camel”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Syria, which may show as the letters SY on some platforms.
The Flag: Syria emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Syria was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic camera, shown with its flash going off, as to illuminate a darker scene. Vendors implement the same design as 📷 Camera with a burst of light, often resembling 💥 Collision.
Commonly used for various content concerning photography as well as an icon for a picture, as before an upload, link, or credit.

Camera With Flash was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Women Wrestling emoji is a sequence of the 🤼 Wrestlers and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Women Wrestling was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Canary Islands, which may show as the letters IC on some platforms.
The Flag: Canary Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Canary Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A barrel for transporting bulk liquids, such as oil. Generally depicted as a red or blue metal drum with holes or a stopper on its lid. Commonly used for various content concerning petroleum or hazardous waste.
Google’s design displays a yellow oil drop symbol. Samsung's design previously featured a yellow hazard sign.

Oil Drum was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Martinique, which may show as the letters MQ on some platforms.
The latest versions of iOS and OS X use the historical snake flag of Martinique for this character. This is used instead of the Flag For France, which is the official flag of Martinique.
The Flag: Martinique emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇶 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Q emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

 Flag: Martinique was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A horizontal line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing left and right.

Left-Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Left Right Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with an open mouth wailing and streams of heavy tears flowing from closed eyes. May convey inconsolable grief but also other intense feelings, such as uncontrollable laughter or overwhelming joy.
Not to be confused with 😂 Face With Tears of Joy. Several platforms, including Apple, feature the same mouth as on their 😲 Astonished Face.

Loudly Crying Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Sudan, which may show as the letters SD on some platforms.
The Flag: Sudan emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Sudan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a frowning mouth and eyes and eyebrows scrunched downward in anger. Google’s design features a reddish face and Facebook’s, clenched teeth.
Conveys varying degrees of anger, from grumpiness and irritation to disgust and outrage. May also represent someone acting tough or being mean.
Samsung’s design previously featured a reddish face with clenched teeth and wrinkled chin.

Angry Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A crispy brown leg (drumstick) of chicken, duck, turkey, or other poultry on the bone, as roasted at Thanksgiving or Christmas dinner or fried at fast-food restaurants.

Poultry Leg was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed. Also features a streamlined bullet nose, often used in reference to the Shinkansen in Japan.

Bullet Train was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “High-Speed Train With Bullet Nose”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Artist emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🎨 Artist Palette emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Artist was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A stack of breakfast pancakes, topped with a pad of butter and maple syrup oozing down its golden-brown sides, onto a plate on some platforms. Associated with the Christian observance of Shrove Tuesday, or "Pancake Day."

Pancakes was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A bowl with a silver spoon inside, as used to eat cereal or soup. Bowl color varies across platforms, as do contents. Android depicts breakfast cereal, WhatsApp tomato soup; Apple’s is empty.

Bowl With Spoon was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
This Emoji has two meanings.
One meaning is “request” in Japanese. An alternative meaning is “monkey” in the Chinese zodiac.
It is commonly used in Japan to denote an application form or contact information for inquiries.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Application” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7533”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Man Juggling emoji is a sequence of the 🤹 Juggling and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Juggling was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A top hat, worn in traditional British weddings and other formal occasions. This is also a popular playing piece in the game of Monopoly.

Top Hat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Means “agreement” in Japanese. More literally, it means to unite, or join together.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Passing Grade” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-5408”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with X’s or spirals for eyes and a round, open mouth. Often depicted with raised or furrowed eyebrows. Facebook’s design features a purple forehead.
May convey a heightened or hyperbolic sense of such feelings as shock, surprise, disbelief, awe, and amazement, as if staggered to the point of disorientation (i.e., dizzy). May also represent sickness, nausea, intoxication, and death, e.g., slang I’m dead!
Not to be confused with 😲 Astonished Face, which previously featured X-shaped eyes on several platforms, though their meanings may overlap.


Dizzy Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The crescent moon and star is a symbol often associated with the religion of Islam. This symbol can be found on the flags of many countries, such as Algeria, Azerbaijan, Malaysia, Pakistan and Turkey.

Star and Crescent was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A right hand holding a pen or pencil and writing. Shown with a blue pen on all platforms except Apple which has a black pen.

Writing Hand was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face smiling with open hands, as if giving a hug. Many platforms feature the same expression as their 😊 Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes.
May be used to offer thanks and support, show love and care, or express warm, positive feelings more generally. Due to its hand gesture, often used to represent jazz hands, indicating such feelings as excitement, enthusiasm, or a sense of flourish or accomplishment.
Joins 🤔 Thinking Face, 🤫 Shushing Face, and 🤭 Face With Hand Over Mouth as one of the few smileys featuring hands.

 Hugging Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A helicopter, which can hover in the air. Often seen in emergency circumstances such as transporting patients to a hospital, or for police or fire-fighting activity.

Helicopter was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Lacrosse was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Lacrosse Stick and Ball”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
An orange-colored basketball displayed with a hoop. Many versions of this emoji omit the hoop, and display only the basketball.
This emoji can be sent on Facebook Messenger to unlock a hidden basketball game.

Basketball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Basketball and Hoop”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Two masks often used on maps to indicate a theatre, these originate in Greek Theatre as masks of tragedy and comedy.
One mask frowns, the other smiles.

Performing Arts was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Montenegro, which may show as the letters ME on some platforms
The Flag: Montenegro emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Montenegro was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A drum shown with drumsticks. A percussion instrument which is likely to be displayed as a snare drum.

Drum was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Drum With Drumsticks”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A speaker cone displayed with three sound waves, generally used as an icon to indicate the increasing of volume on a phone or computer.

Speaker High Volume was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Speaker With Three Sound Waves”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An herb, a plant used in cooking or medicine. Depicted as a green sprig, as of basil, sage, or oregano, generally with five or seven leaves.
May be used for various content concerning cooking, herbal medicine, and plant life more generally. Occasionally used as slang for marijuana.
Not to be confused with 🌱 Seedling, though their applications may overlap.

Herb was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A cartoon-styled gust of air. Depicted as a small, gray cloud with motion lines, rushing to the left.
Resembles briffits, a stylized cloud of dust used in comics and animation to indicate someone or something has dashed away (e.g., leaving someone in the dust).
May be used to represent speed, smoking, and various types of wind, blown or broken. May precede other emoji, such as 🏃Runner or 🚗 Automobile, to indicate something is fast or fleeing: 🏃💨, 🚗💨.
Not to be confused 🌬️ Wind Face, though their applications may overlap.

Dashing Away was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Dash Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Judge emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and ⚖ Scales emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Judge was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A large ship, used for transport of people or cargo across the ocean. May be a cruise ship, commonly found around tropical locations.

Ship was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a cow looking straight ahead. Variously depicted as a white, brown, or multicolored cow face with a neutral expression, short horns, and a pink or brown muzzle.
Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied 🐄 Cow.
Facebook’s design once featured a more lifelike, brown cow face.

Cow Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man with red hair. Sometimes described as ginger, orange, copper, or auburn.
The Man: Red Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🦰 Emoji Component Red Hair emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man: Red Hair was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A silver spoon, as used to eat soup, cereal, or ice cream as well as serve food or stir drinks. Positioned at various angles across platforms. May be paired with Fork and Knife, Fork and Knife With Plate, and Bowl With Spoon.

Spoon was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a half-frown and white bandage wrapped around its head, often depicted partially over one eye. May represent physical injury or pain but also emotional hurting, sometimes for ironic effect.
Differs from other smileys conveying illness, such as 🤢 Nauseated Face (appearing as if it’s going to vomit) or 🤒 Face With Thermometer (used especially for colds and flus).

Face With Head-Bandage was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Iran, which may show as the letters IR on some platforms.
The Flag: Iran emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Iran was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A gorilla, the powerful, black-haired great ape. Variously depicted in full profile on all fours facing left or as a friendly, cartoon-styled gorilla face looking straight ahead.
Apple, WhatsApp, Facebook, and Microsoft’s designs feature a full gorilla, as a silverback, with strong shoulders and reddish forehead. Google, Samsung, and Twitter’s designs feature a black and gray gorilla face with a neutral expression and prominent forehead and jaw.
Facebook’s design previously featured only a gorilla face.

Gorilla was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Scotland, a country in the United Kingdom. May show as the letters gbsct.
The Flag: Scotland emoji is a sequence of the 🏴 Waving Black Flag, 󠁧 Tag Latin Small Letter G, 󠁢 Tag Latin Small Letter B, 󠁳 Tag Latin Small Letter S, 󠁣 Tag Latin Small Letter C, 󠁴 Tag Latin Small Letter T and 󠁿 Cancel Tag emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Scotland was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The symbol for a baby, usually used to indicate a room that is suitable to change a baby in. Often located in or near public restrooms.

Baby Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A music note emoji, which can denote song lyrics, or other music related topics.
Displays as two eighth-notes (quavers in British English) connected with a beam in the Apple artwork. A single eight-note (quaver) is used in Microsoft and Google’s emoji font.

Musical Note was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A small pouch, somewhere between the size of a handbag, and a purse.

Clutch Bag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Pouch”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. More common than the horizontal traffic light.

Vertical Traffic Light was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A volleyball emoji, showing the round ball used in the sport. Played as part of the Summer Olympic Games.

Volleyball was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A yellow baby chicken (chick). Variously depicted as a chick in full profile, standing on its legs, or as a chick head. Both designs show the bird facing left, with an orange beak and feet.
Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent various types of baby birds. May also be used to represent chicken foods (e.g., poultry, eggs), spring, Easter, or slang senses of chick.
Not to be confused with 🐣 Hatching Chick or 🐥Front-Facing Baby Chick, though their applications overlap. See also 🐔 Chicken and 🐓 Rooster.
Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs feature a chick head; other major platforms display a full-bodied chick.

Baby Chick was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Vampire emoji is a sequence of the 🧛 Vampire and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Vampire was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a hamster—a small rodent often kept as a pet—looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a brown-and-white faced hamster with whiskers, a pink nose, puffy cheeks, and large, round, pink ears, sometimes with a buck tooth.
Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent a gerbil, guinea pig, chinchilla, or related animals. Does not have a full-bodied hamster emoji counterpart.
Not to be confused with 🐭 Mouse Face.
Microsoft’s hamster was previously gray.

Hamster was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 under the name “Hamster Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol often used in relation to the religion of Judaism. Not to be confused with the Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot emoji.

Star of David was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A Bactrian camel, a long-necked mammal with two large humps on its back. Depicted in light or yellowish brown, sometimes with a shaggy mane and humps, in full profile on all fours facing left.
Not to be confused with 🐪 Camel (dromedary), though their applications generally overlap.
May be used in association with deserts, the Middle East and Central Asia, and Wednesday (Hump Day).
Samsung’s design features a camel with a shaggy head of hair and slight smile. Google’s design previously featured a blanket on its back, as for transport.

 Two-Hump Camel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Bactrian Camel”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A snail, a slow-moving, snail-like mollusk in a spiraling shell. Generally depicted as a brown snail in full profile facing left or right, with a brown, textured shell and tentacle-like eyes.
May be used to represent a slug and various senses of slow.
Twitter’s snail has a purple body and yellow shell. Microsoft’s snail previously had a green body.

Snail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The face of a boy, smiling. Previously differentiated from the man emoji on Android by wearing a cap, and on iOS by the lack of any facial hair.

Boy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic telephone, as a landline home phone. Most platforms depict a red, push-button phone with the handset on the base.
Used for various content concerning literal and figurative phone-calling. Also used as an icon before a phone number.
Google and Samsung’s designs feature rotary dials. See the glossary for the term black in Unicode character names.

Telephone was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Telephone”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Sunglasses that can be worn outside for protection from the sun. Often association with connotations of being "cool", or leisurely in sunny places.
This emoji shows only the sunglasses, which differs from the smiling face with sunglasses emoji.

Sunglasses was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Dark Sunglasses”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 👷 Construction Worker emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Construction Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👷 Construction Worker and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Construction Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The pink flower of a cherry blossom tree. Depicted as a single, light-pink cherry blossom with five, notched petals and red-tipped stamens in a yellow or white center.
A traditional symbol in Japan, where the flower is called sakura and celebrated in annual viewings.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such ideas as love and beauty. Also used as a pink accent color.
Not to be confused with 💮 White Flower and 🌺 Hibiscus, though their applications may overlap.

 Cherry Blossom was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A spider, an eight-legged arachnid that spins a web. Depicted as a common black spider, as a house spider or funnel-web spider, shown from above with its large abdomen oriented at the bottom.
See also 🕸️ Spider Web. Commonly used during Halloween and to represent the superhero Spider-Man.
Google's spider is upside down, suspended from a thread. Facebook’s spider is shown on its eight legs facing left. Microsoft’s spider was previously a black widow, Samsung’s was brown.

Spider was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A laptop personal computer. Depicted as a black or gray device, opened to show a dark or blue screen, keyboard, and touchpad.
Commonly used for various content concerning computer technology, work, and activity.
Previous designs resembled a desktop computer (e.g., iMac) on many platforms, hence its Unicode name of Personal Computer. Apple’s design now resembles a MacBook.

Laptop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Personal Computer”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A pretty dress, suitable for a ball, party or other similar occasion.

Dress was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A speech bubble showing an eye inside. When using text-to-speech on Apple platforms, this emoji is read aloud as: "Eye in speech bubble representing anti-bullying campaign". This emoji was released in conjunction with the Ad Council for the I Am A Witness campaign.
The Eye in Speech Bubble emoji is a sequence of the 👁 Eye and 🗨 Left Speech Bubble emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.


Eye in Speech Bubble was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A curved arrow pointing up.

Right Arrow Curving Up was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002
under the name “Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Upwards”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The unique, feathery ice crystal of a snowflake. Depicted as a bluish-white snowflake with six, intricate, symmetrical branches.
Like 🌨️ Cloud With Snow, may be used as a weather icon to represent a snowstorm or a cold, snowy day. May also be used for various content concerning wintertime, cold climates, and winter activity, such as skiing.

Snowflake was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Qatar, which may show as the letters QA on some platforms.
The Flag: Qatar emoji is a sequence of the 🇶 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Q and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Qatar was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A locked (closed) padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a secure internet connection, private account, or locked device. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle. WhatsApp’s design is silver.
Commonly used for content concerning safety, security, privacy, and protection as well as various senses of lock, e.g., locked in/down.
This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).
See also: 🔏 Locked With Pen and 🔐 Locked With Key.

Locked was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Lock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A diamond symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the diamonds suit.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Diamond Suit was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Diamond Suit”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Pisces astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Fish.

Pisces was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A padded boxing glove, used in the sport of boxing. Usually red.

Boxing Glove was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes, a closed smile, rosy cheeks, and several hearts floating around its head. Expresses a range of happy, affectionate feelings, especially being in love. The number of hearts (three or more) varies by platform.
Apple's design features the same expression as its ☺️ Smiling Face.   

Smiling Face With Hearts was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes and Three Hearts”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A fax machine, as scans and transmits documents over a telephone line. Common in the 1980–90s before the internet. Depicted as a white or black machine with a telephone handset, keypad, display screen, and paper in its tray. Very occasionally used as icon before a fax number or as a pun on facts.
Not to be confused with 🖨️ Printer.

Fax Machine was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person (generally depicted as a woman) wearing a headscarf. While the type of  headscarf is not specified, this is most commonly displayed as a woman wearing a hijab.

Woman With Headscarf was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Person With Headscarf”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman working in the field of health care. This may be used to represent a doctor, nurse, or pharmacist.
See also: 👨‍⚕️ Male Health Worker
The Woman Health Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and ⚕ Staff of Aesculapius emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Health Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with furrowed eyebrows, a small frown, and large, “puppy dog” eyes, as if begging or pleading. May also represent adoration or feeling touched by a loving gesture.

Pleading Face was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Face With Pleading Eyes”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes sneezing or blowing its nose into a white tissue, as if from a cold or allergies. Often depicted with a crumpled-looking mouth.
May also represent someone in an emotional state wiping away tears, as at a wedding.

Sneezing Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🚴 Bicyclist emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Biking emoji is a sequence of the 🚴 Bicyclist and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Biking was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Student emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🎓 Graduation Cap emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Student was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Algeria, which may show as the letters DZ on some platforms.
The Flag: Algeria emoji is a sequence of the 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Algeria was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A Japanese post office, featuring the テ Japanese postal mark on the front of the building (or showing this mark instead of the building in Microsoft’s artwork).

Japanese Post Office was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A fingers crossed emoji which displays the index (first) finger crossed over the middle (second) finger. Commonly used as a gesture indicating luck, or to show desire of a favorable outcome.
This emoji is displayed with an additional finger on Samsung devices.

Crossed Fingers was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Hand With Index and Middle Fingers Crossed”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A loudspeaker used to make announcements in public areas such as schools, or sporting grounds.

Loudspeaker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Public Address Loudspeaker”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 👷 Construction Worker emoji.
The Woman Construction Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👷 Construction Worker and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Construction Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a small, closed mouth, flat or frowning, rolling its large, white eyes upwards. As with the gesture of an eye-roll, commonly conveys moderate disdain, disapproval, frustration, or boredom. Tone varies, including playful, sassy, resentful, and sarcastic, as if saying Yeah, whatever.
Samsung's design previously depicted a face smiling and looking to the side.

Face With Rolling Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
One or more scoops of ice cream in a dessert bowl, variously topped with sprinkles, wafer rolls, or cherry and syrup. Flavors vary from vanilla, chocolate, and/or strawberry across platforms.

Ice Cream was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A white piece of paper with text written on it by a yellow pencil, positioned over the sheet, tip down, at a 45° angle. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, including signing (in sports).
WhatsApp and Facebook’s designs depict an old-fashioned office memorandum on pink paper. Apple’s suggests an informal note with the easter egg of handwritten text from its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign: Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes…
Not to be confused with 📄 Page Facing Up or other emojis featuring sheets of paper.


Memo was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Shrugging emoji is a sequence of the 🤷 Shrug and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Shrugging was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A softball, which is differentiated from a baseball by size (it is larger, though hard to tell in emoji form) and color (yellow, not white).

Softball was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a slight frown. Often conveys a mild degree of concern, disappointment, or sadness, but usually less intensely than ☹️ Frowning Face.
Samsung and Facebook previously included eyebrows.

Slightly Frowning Face was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A honey bee, a busy, flying insect that lives in a hive and makes honey. Depicted as a black-and-yellow bee with clear or white wings and a stinger. Variously facing left in full profile or shown from above.
May be used to represent various types of bees (e.g., bumblebee) and wasps (e.g., hornets, yellow jackets). May also be used to accent black-and-yellow colors or patterns. Popularly used in connection with singer and superstar Beyoncé (nicknamed Queen Bey) or for metaphorical queen bees.

Honeybee was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Armenia, which may show as the letters AM on some platforms.
The Flag: Armenia emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Armenia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😩 Weary Face. Its expression more closely resembles 😱 Face Screaming in Fear. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Weary Cat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Weary Cat Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
An awareness ribbon, worn to show support of a cause or group.

Reminder Ribbon was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description: null

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A necktie commonly worn at work or formal occasions.
Sometimes displayed as a shirt and tie. Colors and patterns vary by platform.

Necktie was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A yellow and green shield symbol, called a Shoshinsha Mark. Must be displayed by drivers in Japan for one year after they receive their drivers licence.
Similar to L-Plates used to identify learner drivers in other countries.

Japanese Symbol for Beginner was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
