category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Chess Pawn was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Chess Pawn”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The snout of a pig. Depicted as a pink oval or slightly pear-shaped nose with two black nostrils.
See also 🐖 Pig and 🐷 Pig Face.
Previously displayed as a cute pig character on Google Gmail.

Pig Nose was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Two-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with closed eyes, furrowed eyebrows, broad frown, and two puffs of steam blowing out of its nose, as if in a huff or fuming. 
May convey various negative emotions, including irritation, anger, and contempt. May also convey feelings of pride, dominance, and empowerment. 
Originally named Face With Look of Triumph, and the steam from its nose may derive from a visual shorthand for frustration or disdain in anime and manga. 
Samsung’s design previously looked like its head was titled back in a more arrogant expression. Earlier designs from Microsoft depicted a big, open mouth without steam and from Facebook, a smiley that resembled 😬 Grimacing Face.

Face With Steam From Nose was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face With Look of Triumph”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Hungary, which may show as the letters HU on some platforms.
The Flag: Hungary emoji is a sequence of the 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Hungary was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face, usually shown with closed eyes and raised eyebrows, with saliva drooling from one corner of its mouth. Often used to show desire for a person (sexy, attractive) or object (e.g., delicious food). May also represent someone is tired or sleeping.
Not to be confused with 😋 Face Savoring Food or 😪 Sleepy Face.
Samsung's design previously featured a startled facial expression.

Drooling Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, closed smile with its tongue sticking out of one corner, as if licking its lips in appetite or contentment. Widely used to convey that a food item is delicious. May also express that a person is attractive.

Face Savoring Food was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face Savouring Delicious Food”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A paddle and ping pong ball used in the sport of table tennis.

Ping Pong was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Table Tennis Paddle and Ball”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An umbrella, opened to provide cover from rain. Generally depicted with purple fabric and a hooked handle with several rain droplets falling on its top.
Commonly used for various content concerning rainy weather.
Not to be confused with ☂️ Umbrella or 🌂 Closed Umbrella, though their applications may overlap.
WhatsApp’s umbrella is green. Google’s umbrella was previously blue, Microsoft and Samsung’s red, and Facebook’s once pink.
In 2016, a Durex poll voted this emoji to (unofficially) represent condoms and safe sex for World AIDS Day.

Umbrella With Rain Drops was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A sandal worn by a woman in summer, spring, or other weather that suits open-toed footwear. Has a heel at the back providing additional height to the wearer.

Woman’s Sandal was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Womans Sandal”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Yee-haw! A yellow smiley wearing a wide-brimmed, brown-leather cowboy hat. Its smile varies across platforms. May convey a sense of exuberance, whimsy, confidence, adventure, or other sentiments.
Several vendors, including Apple, feature the same expression as their 😃 Grinning Face With Big Eyes.

Cowboy Hat Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Face With Cowboy Hat”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with raised or furrowed eyebrows and a thermometer in its mouth. Often depicted with red cheeks, as if feverish. May be used to represent a hospital patient or person with a cold or flu.
Differs from other smileys conveying illness, such as 🤢 Nauseated Face (appearing as if it's going to vomit) or 🤕 Face With Head-Bandage (physical injury).

Face With Thermometer was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A retail bank branch, where people can perform money-related tasks. Also a common location to find an ATM.
This emoji came to also mean "slacking off" or evading responsibility in Japan, due to the BK letters being associated with the slang term bakkureru.

Bank was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A curled loop, which is shown in black on most platforms. Displayed as a blue ribbon on Samsung devices.
Similar to the Double Curly Loop but with only a single loop.

Curly Loop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A construction helmet, which is worn by the construction worker emoji in some emoji sets.
The cross on the helmet (shown in the Apple version of this emoji) is used in Japan as a safety reminder in construction zones. It is also commonly seen on the Met helmet in the game Mega Man.

Rescue Worker’s Helmet was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Helmet With White Cross”
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🚣 Rowboat emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Rowing Boat emoji is a sequence of the 🚣 Rowboat and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Rowing Boat was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes, open frown, and raised eyebrows. Samsung’s design shows upper teeth and tongue. Meaning widely varies, but may convey alarm, confusion, or sadness, as if gasping in shock or concern.
Bears the same eyes and mouth as 😦 Frowning Face With Open Mouth on most platforms, but its eyebrows give it a more surprised expression.

Anguished Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A video game emoji, shown on major platforms as a console gamepad with D-pad, joysticks, and buttons.

Video Game was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing up. Styled similarly to the left and right pointing triangles on iOS, but shown in red on Windows, and orange on Android.

Upwards Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Up-Pointing Small Red Triangle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A stylized globe, with blue meridians (longitudes) and latitude. Depicted with light-blue grid of lines on a white, blue, or empty circle.
May be used as a symbol of the internet or world wide web, global communications, international affairs, connectivity and networks, time zones, coordinates, or the world more generally.
May appear as an icon on Apple devices to change (language) keyboards.
See also 🌎 Globe Showing Americas, 🌍 Globe Showing Europe-Africa, and 🌏 Globe Showing Asia-Australia.

Globe With Meridians was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A synague; a place of worship for followers of Judaism. Displayed with a Star of David on the front.

Synagogue was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable alphabetical input, as opposed to numeric or symbol input.

Input Latin Letters was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Input Symbol for Latin Letters”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A wooden painted horse, found on the carousel at a carnival. Faces to the left-of screen.
A previous version of Windows displayed the carousel horse facing right, which was changed to face left on Windows 10 for cross-platform consistency.

Carousel Horse was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for France, which may show as the letters FR on some platforms.
The Flag: France emoji is a sequence of the 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: France was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Symbol for a sale, or bargain prices in Japan (“cut prices”). Literally translated, this character means to cut or divide.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Discount” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-5272”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Seven O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Seven O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Classical Building was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Generic profile of one person. Often used in interface design to represent a user.

Bust in Silhouette was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Eritrea, which may show as the letters ER on some platforms.
The Flag: Eritrea emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Eritrea was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two mothers, and one son.
The Family: Woman, Woman, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👩 Woman and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Woman, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person with a serious expression, showing mild displeasure with the situation. Could be considered to be reserved or stoic in response, as this person is not visible angry.
Quite different to the Pouting Face Emoji which conveys a more aggressive tone, and is a smiley. Pouting Cat Face is a cat.

Person Pouting was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Person With Pouting Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A glyph that is used for kawaii in Japan, resembling the shape of a flower.

Diamond With a Dot was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Diamond Shape With a Dot Inside”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😍 Smiling Face With Heart-Eyes. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Smiling Cat With Heart-Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smiling Cat Face With Heart-Shaped Eyes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A dog, a faithful, beloved pet canine. Depicted as a light-brown dog, of various breeds, in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long, curled tail held upright and pointed or floppy ears.
Google and Facebook’s dogs resemble a reddish-brown Shiba Inu, a popular Japanese breed featured in the Doge meme.
See also 🐩 Poodle and 🐶 Dog Face, whose applications may overlap. Some vendors implement the same or a similar dog in their 🦮 Guide Dog and 🐕‍🦺 Service Dog.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.



Google and Facebook previously featured puppies with collars, Apple’s dog previously resembled an Akita Inu, another popular Japanese breed.

Dog was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Quack! A duck, a waterbird with webbed feet. Depicted as a male (drake) mallard in full profile facing left, standing on its legs with gray and brown feathers, a yellow bill, and its distinctive green head.
May be consumed in the form of a 🍗 Poultry Leg. Occasionally used as a substitute for the F-word, due to rhyming and Apple's iPhone autocorrect.
Samsung’s design previously featured a yellow rubber ducky.

Duck was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An icy-blue face with gritted teeth usually depicted with icicles clinging to its cheeks or jaw, as if frozen from extreme cold. May also represent unfriendliness (slang, cold) or excellence (slang, cool or chill).
Apple’s design features the same expression as its 😬 Grimacing Face.

Cold Face was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Freezing Face”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A postal horn (post horn). Depicted as a coiled, valveless, brass horn, like a bugle or trumpet, with two red tassels. Sometimes used to mark announcements as well as for various content concerning brass instruments, music, or mail.
In the 18–19th centuries, post horns signaled the arrival of and cleared the way for mail coaches, like a modern-day siren. Used today as a symbol on postboxes (mailboxes) and by many European postal services, as seen featured in 🏤 European Post Office.


Postal Horn was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 💂 Guardsman emoji.
The Woman Guard emoji is a sequence of the 💂 Guardsman and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Guard was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag raised. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.
Indicates in the United States that incoming mail (post) has been delivered. May also indicate that there is outgoing mail for pickup.
Compare 📪 Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, 📭 Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📬 Open Mailbox With Raised Flag.


Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A nazar, an eye-shaped amulet believed to protect against the evil eye, especially in Turkish culture. Depicted as a rich blue, circular bead with a black dot in the center ringed with white and light blue, resembling an eye.
Commonly used to represent eyes, various senses of looking, various senses of charms, envy and jealousy, and Turkey and Turkish culture. Also used for its blue color more generally.
WhatsApp and Facebook's designs include a small hole, as for threading the amulet on a string or chain.

Nazar Amulet was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Scarf was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Liberia, which may show as the letters LR on some platforms.
The Flag: Liberia emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Liberia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Tanzania, which may show as the letters TZ on some platforms.
The Flag: Tanzania emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Tanzania was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A large rotating wheel, often found at a carnival or fair.

Ferris Wheel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Iraq, which may show as the letters IQ on some platforms.
The Flag: Iraq emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇶 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Q emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Iraq was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A single human ear. May be used in the context of listening, or hearing something.

Ear was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Curling Stone was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A hash key, sometimes referred to as a pound key in the United States. Most commonly used online to make a hashtag (or hash flag) on social media sites.
The Keycap Number Sign emoji is a sequence of the # Number Sign and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Number Sign was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Shrugging emoji is a sequence of the 🤷 Shrug and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Shrugging was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
An undressed garden salad in a bowl with leafy-green lettuce and other ingredients such as tomato, red onion, and black olives. Commonly associated with healthy eating and living.
Google previously displayed a hard-boiled egg, removed in 2018 to make the salad vegan-friendly.

Green Salad was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016

and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A common green apple, tarter counterpart to the Red Apple. Displayed with a stem and single, green leaf on major platforms.

Green Apple was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol representing Blood Type B. Displayed as the letter B on a red background.
Sometimes used online to replace the letter C at the start of words in reference to the Bloods street gang's practice of turning words like cool into bool. This has expanded in some instances to starting any word with the letter B, or more specifically, this emoji which makes it more 🅱️lear that a letter has been replaced.

B Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter B”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two fathers, and two daughters.
The Family: Man, Man, Girl, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👨 Man, 👧 Girl and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Man, Girl, Girl was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Dominica, which may show as the letters DM on some platforms.

🇩🇲 Dominican Flag Emoji

The Flag: Dominica emoji is a sequence of the 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Dominica was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The word cool, shown enclosed in a square. This generally displays in a shade of blue, or blue-gray on most platforms. Used as a text decoration.

Cool Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared Cool”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A whole, bright orange carrot, topped with long green leaves, as if freshly plucked from the garden. Some platforms feature a longer, thinner carrot, others a shorter, more bulbous one.

Carrot was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A cube-shaped building located at the centre of the Al-Masjid al-Haram Mosque in Mecca.

Kaaba was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A flower that has wilted, or is dying. Generally depicted as a limp, faded red rose drooping over the to the right on a dried-out, green stem, shedding a petal.
May be used to express such sad sentiments as heartbreak, though sometimes with a sense of irony. Sometimes used to represent a rose or other flower, with positive connotations.
Not to be confused with 🌹 Rose.
WhatsApp's flower suggests a wilted 🌻 Sunflower; Twitter's a 🌷 Tulip, as Microsoft and Samsung's previously did. Facebook's flower was previously orange.


Wilted Flower was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Mage emoji is a sequence of the 🧙 Mage and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Mage was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Bulgaria, which may show as the letters BG on some platforms.
The Flag: Bulgaria emoji is a sequence of the 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Bulgaria was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Anguilla, which may show as the letters AI on some platforms.
The Flag: Anguilla emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Anguilla was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🏌 Golfer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Golfing emoji is a sequence of the 🏌 Golfer and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Golfing was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A large capacity stadium, featuring a large amount of seating for sporting fans, or people attending other shows hosted by the stadium.

Stadium was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
An individual cupcake in a liner topped with a swirl of frosting and sprinkles. The style of cupcake widely varies across platforms. The cake may be sponge or chocolate, the frosting pink or white, and the sprinkles rainbow or red.

Cupcake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Ten-pin bowling emoji, showing a bowling ball and pins.

Bowling was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A snow cloud. Depicted as blue snowflakes falling from a white cloud.
May be used as a weather icon to represent snow showers or a snowy day.
Not to be confused with 🌧️ Cloud With Rain.

Cloud With Snow was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An evergreen tree, which keeps green leaves all year round. Depicted as a tall, dark green, cone-shaped tree with shaggy, layered leaves, as a pine or fir, showing a brown trunk.
May be decorated in the form of a 🎄 Christmas Tree. May also be used to represent various types of trees, forests, northern climates, nature, winter, and the Christmas season.

Evergreen Tree was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
This police officer wears a blue hat, which features a gold badge or shield in the middle.
The gender of this emoji is not specified, but is commonly shown as a man.

Police Officer was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag lowered and its slot empty. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.
Indicates in the United States that outgoing mail has been picked up. May also indicate that no incoming mail has been delivered.
Compare 📫 Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, 📪 Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📬 Open Mailbox With Raised Flag.


Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An abacus, an ancient tool used to count and calculate by moving beads. Depicted as a wooden frame with four or more rows or columns of variously positioned and colored beads.
Used for various content concerning mathematics and science (education) as well as calculations, counting, and numbers more generally.
Designs from Apple, Microsoft, and Facebook resemble a Chinese abacus (suanpan). By one reckoning, Apple’s red-beaded design displays the number 108 and Emojipedia's, 12,031,981.

Abacus was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Woman, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Girl was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The face of a wolf, a howling canine that hunts in packs. Generally depicted as a cartoon-styled face of a gray wolf with pointed ears, white cheeks and muzzle, and black nose.
Its expression is variously neutral, friendly, or slightly menacing, as in Google and Samsung’s designs. Apple’s design features the head of gray wolf, facing left.
Occasionally used to represent metaphorical senses of wolf, e.g., lone wolf, wolf pack.
Apple and SoftBank’s designs previously resembled a reddish-brown canine, resembling a dog or fox.

Wolf was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Wolf Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Malaysia, which may show as the letters MY on some platforms.
The Flag: Malaysia emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Malaysia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A dragon, a mythical creature resembling a giant reptile found in the folklore of many cultures. Depicted as a green, Chinese-styled dragon in full profile facing left. Generally shown with a curling, snake-like body, clawed feet, yellowish scales on its back, horn-like structures on its head, and whisker-like tendrils by its nostrils.
See also 🐲 Dragon Face. One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Commonly used on Chinese New Year and St. George's Day. Also used for various medieval and fantasy content.
Apple's dragon is holding a glowing blue orb, as a 🔮 Crystal Ball. Facebook's dragon is bluish in color. Microsoft's dragon was previously red, Samsung's a more cartoon-styled, baby dragon holding a blue orb.

Dragon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Supervillain emoji is a sequence of the 🦹 Supervillain and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Supervillain was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A mound of shaved ice (snow cone) served in a dessert bowl with a short spoon, flavored with a cherry-red syrup on many platforms. Associated with Hawaiian shave ice or Japanese kakigori.

Shaved Ice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Index finger pointing upward, showing the back of the hand while doing so.

Backhand Index Pointing Up was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “White Up Pointing Backhand Index”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Somalia, which may show as the letters SO on some platforms.
The Flag: Somalia emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Somalia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A trademark symbol, the letters TM displayed after a word that is trademarked.

Trade Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Trade Mark Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Tristan da Cunha, which may show as the letters TA on some platforms. This same flag is used for Ascension Island and St. Helena.
The Flag: Tristan Da Cunha emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Tristan Da Cunha was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A sailboat, otherwise known as a sailing boat or yacht.  Uses wind as the source of propulsion to move around a body of water.
The color of the sails in this emoji vary by platform, with vendors displaying blue sails, orange sails, or a mix of red, yellow, orange, blue or white.

Sailboat was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Ecuador, which may show as the letters EC on some platforms.
The Flag: Ecuador emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Ecuador was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🕵 Sleuth or Spy emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Detective emoji is a sequence of the 🕵 Sleuth or Spy and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Detective was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Twelve-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Twelve-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol often used in relation to the Indian religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism.

Wheel of Dharma was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Used in traditional Japanese music such as Noh or Renga, to indicate the start of a song. More specifically, the part alternation mark is displayed where the singer’s part begins.
This symbol looks sort of like a lopsided capital M; or a rollercoaster track showing a dip, and then a drop off to the right.

Part Alternation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man wearing business attire. This may include items such as a shirt, tie, jacket, or headset.
The Man Office Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 💼 Briefcase emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Office Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Malawi, which may show as the letters MW on some platforms.
The Flag: Malawi emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Malawi was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Afghanistan, which may show as the letters AF on some platforms.
The Flag: Afghanistan emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Afghanistan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A closed, green, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a green accent color.
Apple’s cover features the easter egg Vol. 2 by John Appleseed, Samsung’s reads Green Book.

Green Book was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman with arms crossed forming an ‘X’ to indicate ‘no’ or ‘no good’. This motion is used on the TV game show Deal or No Deal to indicate ‘No Deal’. Intended to be gender-neutral but shown as a woman on most platforms.
The Man Gesturing No emoji is a sequence of the 🙅 Face With No Good Gesture and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

 Man Gesturing No was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Orthodox Cross was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Clipperton Island, which may show as the letters CP on some platforms. Uses the same flag as France.
The Flag: Clipperton Island emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Clipperton Island was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Norfolk Island, which may show as the letters NF on some platforms.
The Flag: Norfolk Island emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Norfolk Island was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Jersey, which may show as the letters JE on some platforms.
The Flag: Jersey emoji is a sequence of the 🇯 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter J and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Jersey was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The see no evil monkey, called Mizaru (Japanese for “see not”), one of the Three Wise Monkeys. Depicted as the brown 🐵 Monkey Face with tan or pinkish hands covering its eyes.
The Three Wise Monkeys represent the proverb see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil, frequently interpreted as a call to discretion or figure for willful ignorance.
Often used as a playful way to convey a laughing, disbelieving, or cringing I can’t believe what I’m seeing! or I can’t bear to look!
See also 🙉 Hear-No-Evil Monkey and 🙊 Speak-No-Evil Monkey.

See-No-Evil Monkey was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A face, usually purple, with two devil horns, frowning mouth and eyes, and eyebrows scrunched downwards in anger. Bears the same expression as 😠 Angry Face and 😡 Pouting Face on most platforms. Google’s design is red and Facebook’s has black horns, green eyes, and clenched teeth.
Its Unicode name, Imp, alludes to a small demon in folklore, though the smiley is commonly used to represent devils and devilish behavior, especially around Halloween. It is also used to convey various sentiments of anger or ideas of evil. More menacing than its counterpart, 😈 Smiling Face With Horns.
Samsung previously depicted a childlike character with red hair and horns, fangs, and black wings. Earlier designs from Google featured an orangish-red character with blue hair and wings.

Angry Face With Horns was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Imp”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, closed smile turning up to rosy cheeks. Often expresses genuine happiness and warm, positive feelings.
An emoji form of the ^^ emoticon.
On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you message that person often but they aren't your #1 Best Friend.

Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😏 Smirking Face. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Cat With Wry Smile was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Cat Face With Wry Smile”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A first quarter moon, the third of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its right half illuminated in gold or silver, its remainder dark.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.
See also 🌛 First Quarter Moon Face. Not to be confused with 🌗 Last Quarter Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a first quarter moon in a night sky with stars.

First Quarter Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “First Quarter Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: Wallis & Futuna emoji is a sequence of the 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Wallis & Futuna was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Western Sahara, which may show as the letters EH on some platforms.
The Flag: Western Sahara emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Western Sahara was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An emoji representing the cinema: a large screen showing the latest movies, available to the public. Displayed by most platforms as a film projector symbol, and previously by Google and Microsoft as a cinema screen with curtains.

Cinema was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🚣 Rowboat emoji.
The Woman Rowing Boat emoji is a sequence of the 🚣 Rowboat and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Rowing Boat was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A classic alien face. The oval, bare head of a gray or green alien with large black eyes and a slight, friendly smile. Samsung depicts nostrils, Facebook a nose.
May represent extraterrestrial life or topics concerning outer space, but commonly conveys a playful sense of weirdness or strangeness, as if someone or something is out there or from another planet.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Apple previously displayed a similar looking alien head in a box as a placeholder for an unknown emoji, but now shows a boxed question mark.

Alien was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Extraterrestrial Alien”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Colored nail polish being applied to finger nails, often used to display an air of nonchalance or indifference.
Shown as red, pink or purple nail polish on most platforms, the color rarely changes the meaning of this emoji. Previously displayed as a single bottle of nail polish on Android and on Windows.

Nail Polish was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A mosque building, a place of worship for followes of Islam. Shown with a domed roof and a minaret.

Mosque was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Niger, which may show as the letters NE on some platforms.
The Flag: Niger emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Niger was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person with blond hair, which tends to appear as yellow. Displayed as a man on all platforms, this emoji keeps blond hair no matter which skin tone is chosen.
Previous releases showed this emoji as a woman on Android, Windows, and Samsung.

Person: Blond Hair was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Person With Blond Hair”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A school building with multiple storeys, and a clock on the front. A place that children, or teenagers attend for their education.
Displays on Windows as a collection of school-related items: an apple, ruler, and pencil.

School was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a pig looking straight ahead. Depicted as a pink face with a neutral expression, pointed or floppy ears, and distinctive pig nose.
Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied 🐖 Pig. Available as an Apple Animoji.
Apple’s face bears a slight grin and previously featured floppy ears.

Pig Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A dart board with dart hitting the center / bullseye region.

Direct Hit was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Black Medium-Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002
under the name “Black Medium Small Square”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Gambia, which may show as the letters GM on some platforms.
The Flag: Gambia emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Gambia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A tall, folded, paper carton, usually white, as used for takeout/takeaway food at Western Chinese restaurants. Most platforms depict chopsticks inside its open lid, labeled with a red, multi-tiered, traditional Chinese building. Also called an oyster pail.

Takeout Box was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
ATM Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Automated Teller Machine”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An angry-red face with a black bar and white grawlixes covering its mouth, indicating it's swearing or being vulgar. Grawlixes are typographical symbols (e.g., @#$%&!) representing swear words or obscenities. Often used to convey an outburst of anger, frustration, or rage.
Most platforms feature the same eyes as on their 😠 Angry Face.

Face With Symbols on Mouth was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Serious Face With Symbols Covering Mouth”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A melon fruit in a light greenish-brown rind. Depicted as a cantaloupe by most platforms, but can resemble a honeydew at a distance.

Melon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
A flag with black and white squares shown in a checkerboard pattern, used to signal the start or end of a motor car race.

Chequered Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A microbe, as a bacterium grown in a 🧫 Petri Dish or observed under a 🔬 Microscope. Generally depicted as a squiggly, single-celled microorganism with prominent cilia. Color, shape, and position vary across platforms.
Commonly used to represent bacteria, viruses, and germs and disease more generally. Also may be used as a green accent color.
Apple, Samsung, and Twitter’s microbes are bright green. Microsoft’s is blue, Facebook’s indigo, and WhatsApp’s purple. Google’s design features five microbes in different, bright colors.

Microbe was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description: null

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A sneaker – a comfortable shoe used in sports such as tennis or golf, or for fashion purposes.

Running Shoe was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Athletic Shoe”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A ribbon and medallion generally awarded to a person in the military for heroic acts.

Military Medal was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A postbox (mailbox, letterbox) with a letter in its slot for collection. Generally depicted in red with a white envelope, styled after public postboxes in Japan. May also evoke postboxes in the United Kingdom.
Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email. Microsoft’s design is blue, after U.S. mail collection boxes.

Postbox was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a mouse, looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a gray or white mouse face with large, round ears, a pink, pointed nose, and whiskers.
Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied 🐁 Mouse. Not to be confused with 🐹 Hamster Face.
Google’s mouse is squinting with a buck tooth, which Facebook’s mouse also has. Microsoft’s design was previously brown.

Mouse Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a crumpled mouth and a cockeyed expression, as if tired and emotional from inebriation or smitten with love. Depicted with raised or furrowed eyebrows and at least one eye half-open. WhatsApp's design features a tongue hanging out. 
Meaning widely varies, but commonly conveys intoxication or infatuation. Its dazed expression may also represent such feelings or states as bewilderment, irritation, disgust, exhaustion, wackiness, or complete satisfaction.

Woozy Face was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Face With Uneven Eyes and Wavy Mouth”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person swimming in a pool, the ocean, or another body of water. Lacked goggles on prior versions of iOS.
Swims facing to the left of screen on all major platforms.

Person Swimming was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Swimmer”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The hear no evil monkey, called Kikazaru (Japanese for “hear not”), one of the Three Wise Monkeys. Depicted as the brown 🐵 Monkey Face with tan or pinkish hands covering its ears.
The Three Wise Monkeys represent the proverb see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil, frequently interpreted as a call to discretion or figure for willful ignorance.
Often used as a playful way to convey I can’t believe what I’m hearing! or, more generally, express astonishment or disbelief.
Google’s design features scrunched, X-shaped eyes.
See also 🙈 See-No-Evil Monkey and 🙊 Speak-No-Evil Monkey.

Hear-No-Evil Monkey was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
2nd Place Medal was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Second Place Medal”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A penguin, a flightless bird adapted to water and ice. Variously depicted as a full, black-bodied penguin with a white belly and orange bill or as a penguin head.
Often used with an affectionate or playful tone or in association with the cold. Occasionally used to represent a puffin.
Apple and WhatsApp’s designs feature a penguin head, with Apple’s bearing a yellow patch on its head, as an emperor penguin. Other major platforms feature a penguin standing in full profile, facing forward or left.

Penguin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Getting Haircut emoji is a sequence of the 💇 Haircut and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Getting Haircut was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A motorcycle, otherwise known as a motorbike used for sport/racing purposes. For a transport-based motorcycle, use a motor scooter.

Motorcycle was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Racing Motorcycle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Merman emoji is a sequence of the 🧜 Merperson and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Merman was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Seychelles, which may show as the letters SC on some platforms.
The Flag: Seychelles emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Seychelles was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Leo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Lion.

Leo was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes and an open frown. Samsung’s design shows upper teeth and tongue. Meaning widely varies, but may convey mild sadness, disappointment, concern, and amazement.

Frowning Face With Open Mouth was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Circular arrows pointing in a clockwise direction. Used in music player applications to loop a track or album continuously.

Repeat Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Deer was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A bar of soap, as used in the shower or bath. (Or to wash out the mouth of 🤬 Face With Symbols on Mouth.) Generally shown with lathered bubbles. Depicted in various colors, often pink, and at different angles.
Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, and cleaning.

Soap was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Bar of Soap”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Woman in Lotus Position emoji is a sequence of the 🧘 Person in Lotus Position and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman in Lotus Position was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A bouquet of brightly colored flowers. Generally depicted as a collection of pink and yellow flowers with green stems tied together. Positioned at various angles across platforms.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May also be more generally used to express such sentiments as love, appreciation, and happiness.
Google’s flowers were previously all yellow, Microsoft’s roses, and Samsung’s pink and white.

Bouquet was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 💆 Face Massage emoji.
The Man Getting Massage emoji is a sequence of the 💆 Face Massage and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Getting Massage was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A closed, orange, hardcover book—similar to the Emojipedia logo 📙😃. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as an orange accent color.
Apple’s cover features the easter egg Vol. 4 by John Appleseed. It was previously purple and the third volume. Samsung’s cover reads Orange Book.

Orange Book was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A volcano, erupting with smoke and lava.

Volcano was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Blue raindrops falling from a white cloud with a lightning bolt flashing.
May be used as a weather icon to represent thundershowers.
Not to be confused with 🌩️ Cloud With Lightning, though their applications may overlap.

Cloud With Lightning and Rain was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Thunder Cloud and Rain”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Northern Mariana Islands, which may show as the letters MP on some platforms.
The Flag: Northern Mariana Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Northern Mariana Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Twelve O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Twelve O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A yellow sun partially covered by a small, white cloud. Position of the cloud varies across platforms.
May be used as a weather icon to represent a mostly sunny day.
Not to be confused with ⛅ Sun Behind Cloud or 🌥️ Sun Behind Large Cloud, though their applications may overlap.
See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

Sun Behind Small Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “White Sun With Small Cloud”
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The long, thin loaf of a baguette, with scoring on its golden-brown crust. A bread commonly associated with France.

Baguette Bread was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A plain t-shirt, that can be worn by men or women. Displayed as a blue polo shirt on iOS, Facebook and Firefox OS. A white t-shirt on Android and Windows, and yellow or green on other platforms.
The Facebook version of this emoji has a capital H on the front.

T-Shirt was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A large department store, selling a range of products to the general public. Shown as a large building with a billboard on most platforms, or as a shopping bag on Windows.

Department Store was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Registered was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Registered Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A raised hand with a part between each finger and the thumb. Held up in a manner that may indicate the number five. Similar to a waving hand, without any motion.
Currently only supported in Windows 10.

Hand With Fingers Splayed was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Raised Hand With Fingers Splayed”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Three O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Three O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Egypt, which may show as the letters EG on some platforms.
The Flag: Egypt emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Egypt was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
No Entry was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
This means to lack, or have none of something.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Free of Charge” Button was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7121”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A dumpling of dough and filling, as folded and pinched closed for steaming or frying. Associated with cuisines around the world, including China (jiaozi), Japan (gyoza or dango), Poland (pierogi), and Spain and Latin America (empanada). Facebook's design resembles a xiaolongbao, a Chinese soup dumpling.

Dumpling was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A can or tin of food, depicted as tomatoes or a generic green vegetable. May be also used to represent sauce or soup.

Canned Food was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A red, triangular flag shown sitting in the hole of a golf course green. Some versions of this emoji also include golf balls.
Android previously displayed this emoji as the head of a putter (golf club) hitting a golf ball.
Not to be confused with the Triangular Flag on Post emoji.

Flag in Hole was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A closed, blue, hardcover book. Commonly used for various content concerning reading, writing, learning, and schooling. May also be used as a blue accent color.
Apple’s cover features the easter egg Vol. 3 by John Appleseed, Samsung’s reads Blue Book. Note that in the U.S., this emoji may be associated with blue book exams and the Kelley Blue Book.

Blue Book was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A speaker cone displayed without any sound waves.

Speaker Low Volume was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Speaker”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🙎 Person With Pouting Face emoji.
The Man Pouting emoji is a sequence of the 🙎 Person With Pouting Face and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Pouting was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with raised eyebrows, a small, closed mouth, wide, white eyes staring straight ahead, and blushing cheeks. Intended to depict such feelings as embarrassment, but meaning very widely varies. Other senses include flattery, surprise, disbelief, admiration, affection, and excitement.
Google's design previously featured a more bashful expression and Samsung, a more ashamed one.

Flushed Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A curved arrow pointing down.

Right Arrow Curving Down was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002
under the name “Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Downwards”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An iteration of the Playboy Bunny known in Japan as a Bunny Girl. Usually depicted as an attractive woman  wearing bunny ears; a bunny girl can also be seen in anime as a hybrid human/animal known as Kemonomimi.
Some versions of this emoji, such as Apple’s, display two girls dancing, each wearing a leotard and bunny ears. Other interpretations show the face of one woman wearing bunny ears.
The two-person version of this emoji is often used as a display of friendship, fun, or "let's party".


People With Bunny Ears was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Woman With Bunny Ears”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A bar graph generally showing three different-colored, vertical rectangles at various heights, as compares values across a category. Commonly used to represent various types of data, information, facts, figures, and charts more generally.
Several platforms, including Apple, depict (left to right) a green, red (lowest), and blue bar (highest). Google’s design includes four bars, with yellow the highest.

Bar Chart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A metal device, dropped out of a boat to prevent it drifting away from the current location.
An anchor also refers to a place on a webpage that may be directly linked to, rather than simply loading a page and requiring a user to scroll to the correct location.

Anchor was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol showing the following glyphs: 〒 (Japanese postal mark), 𝅘𝅥𝅮 (music note), & (ampersand, or sometimes an @ symbol) and % (percentage sign).
Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable symbol input, as opposed to alphabetical or numeric input.

Input Symbols was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Input Symbol for Symbols”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The letters NG, shown enclosed in a square, which are an acronym for the words No Good.
The origin of NG refers to bloopers shown during or after the credits of a live television show in Japan (known as NGs), but can be used in any field as a form of shorthand for no good.

NG Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared NG”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for South Sudan, which may show as the letters SS on some platforms.
