The Flag: South Sudan emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: South Sudan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A rain cloud. (Keep dry with ☔ Umbrella With Rain Drops.) Depicted as blue raindrops falling from a white cloud. Most platforms depict the raindrops falling to the left.
May be used as a weather icon to represent rain showers or a rainy day.
Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish.

Cloud With Rain was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow pointing to the right, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a forward icon in an email application.

Left Arrow Curving Right was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Rightwards Arrow With Hook”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A raised hand, with the fingers separated between the ring finger and the middle finger.

Vulcan Salute was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Raised Hand With Part Between Middle and Ring Fingers”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A small piece of round, hard sugar candy, as handed out on Halloween, wrapped with two twists on its ends. Candy and wrapper color vary widely by platform. Facebook’s design resembles a classic, unwrapped red-and-white peppermint. May also be called sweets or lollies.

Candy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The handset of a traditional telephone, with speaker and microphone. Generally depicted in black at a 45° angle.
Like ☎️ Telephone, used for various content concerning literal and figurative phone-calling. Also used as an icon before a phone number.
Microsoft’s design is red.

Telephone Receiver was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An undercover investigator, wearing a hat, and sometimes using a magnifying glass to closely inspect evidence. This emoji did not originally recommend emoji modifiers, but a proposal was created to address this.

Detective was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Sleuth or Spy”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Turkey, which may show as the letters TR on some platforms.
The Flag: Turkey emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Turkey was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A classic smiley. A yellow face with a modest smile, rosy cheeks, and soft, closed eyes. Many platforms, including Apple, feature relaxed eyebrows. Conveys a wide range of warm, positive feelings, including love, happiness, and gratitude.
Similar to 😊 Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes, which has a broader smile, no eyebrows, and smiling eyes.
This smiley predates Unicode emoji support. In its Unicode name of White Smiling Face, white does not refer to skin tone or ethnicity. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.

Smiling Face was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “White Smiling Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Woman, Girl, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👧 Girl and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Girl, Boy was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two hands performing a handshake gesture, indicating a cordial greeting between friends or associates.

Handshake was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A bald eagle, the majestic bird of prey with brown feathers and distinctive white head. Generally depicted facing left, with its wings outspread and talons out, as if swooping down to seize prey.
Commonly associated with the United States, whose national emblem is the bald eagle. May be used for other eagles and birds of prey (e.g., hawks) more generally.
Google’s eagle has its wings tucked in, as if perched on a branch. Twitter’s design shows only the bust of an eagle. Apple’s 📰 Newspaper features its eagle on its masthead.

Eagle was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Ten O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Ten O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Four-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Four-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A red rose. Depicted as a single, vertical red rose on a green stem.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such sentiments as love and romance. Also used as a symbol of socialism or as a red accent color.
Not to be confused with 🌷 Tulip, though their applications may overlap.
Samsung’s rose was previously pink.

Rose was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed left. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper left.
Associated with detectives and search or zoom icons on computers. Like 🔎 Magnifying Glass Titled Right, commonly used for various senses of searching, looking, inspecting, etc.

Magnifying Glass Tilted Left was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Left-Pointing Magnifying Glass”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Jordan, which may show as the letters JO on some platforms.
The Flag: Jordan emoji is a sequence of the 🇯 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter J and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Jordan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🙍 Person Frowning emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Woman Frowning emoji is a sequence of the 🙍 Person Frowning and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Frowning was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Serbia, which may show as the letters RS on some platforms.
The Flag: Serbia emoji is a sequence of the 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Serbia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A traditional Japanese Castle, usually made from stone and wood.

Japanese Castle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Wales, a country in the United Kingdom. May show as the letters gbwls.
The Flag: Wales emoji is a sequence of the 🏴 Waving Black Flag, 󠁧 Tag Latin Small Letter G, 󠁢 Tag Latin Small Letter B, 󠁷 Tag Latin Small Letter W, 󠁬 Tag Latin Small Letter L, 󠁳 Tag Latin Small Letter S and 󠁿 Cancel Tag emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Wales was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Pakistan, which may show as the letters PK on some platforms.
The Flag: Pakistan emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Pakistan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Nine emoji is a sequence of the 9 Digit Nine and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Nine was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the ⛹ Person With Ball emoji.
The Woman Bouncing Ball emoji is a sequence of the ⛹ Person With Ball and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Bouncing Ball was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Person in Lotus Position was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Singapore, which may show as the letters SG on some platforms.
The Flag: Singapore emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Singapore was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A sign indicating that mobile phones should be turned off. Used in situations such as a cinema or live performance.
Displayed as a mobile phone with the word OFF. Shown with a cross instead of the word OFF on Windows.

Mobile Phone Off was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A suitcase or bag, as used for traveling. Most platforms depict gray or blue rolling luggage with an extended handle. Commonly used for various content concerning traveling or taking trips, whether for business or leisure.
Apple’s design features an old-fashioned, leather, trunk-styled case with graphic luggage labels/stickers, not to be confused with 💼 Briefcase or 👜 Handbag. Google and Facebook also include such stickers.
May be stored in a 🛅 Coin Locker or inspected at 🛃 Customs.

Luggage was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018

and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Man Playing Water Polo emoji is a sequence of the 🤽 Water Polo and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Playing Water Polo was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The head of a classic robot. Commonly depicted as a vintage, tin toy robot with circular eyes, a triangular nose, knobs for ears, a light and/or antennae atop its head, and a grill-like mouth similar to a grimace. Colors vary across platform, but its head is metallic on most platforms. 
May be used of topics concerning robotics, electronics, computer programming, futurism, and science fiction. It also enjoys a range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of weirdness and fun as well as alarm, surprise, and excitement, given its wide-eyed, teeth-gritting expression.
Available as an Apple Animoji.

Robot was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
 under the name “Robot Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A crescent moon, as in its waxing crescent phase. Depicts the moon as a thin, golden crescent, curving to the right and not displaying the remaining outline of the moon.
May be used for the moon more generally and saying good night. May be used in association with ☪️ Star and Crescent, a popular but unofficial symbol of Islam.
As of March 2019, sending this emoji over Facebook Messenger activates dark mode.
See also 🌒 Waxing Crescent Moon.
Google’s moon once resembled a waning crescent moon, Twitter and Facebook's moons were previously silver.

Crescent Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Six emoji is a sequence of the 6 Digit Six and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Six was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
An icon representing a place to leave luggage. Most commonly found at Japanese train stations to signify coin lockers where bags can be stored for a daily fee.
This emoji displays a suitcase with a key above or below it, ususually in blue.

Left Luggage was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The sun, the star at the center of our solar system. Generally depicted as a golden-yellow disc radiating eight triangular rays, representing the sun’s heat and light.
Commonly used to represent sunny, warm, or hot weather, light, heat, energy, life, outer space, astronomy, and various positive and happy (sunny) feelings.
See also 🌞 Sun With Face. Not to be confused with 🔆 Bright Button or 🔅 Dim Button.
Google’s sun was once red, Samsung’s previously gray. See the glossary for the term black in Unicode character names.

Sun was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Sun With Rays”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A cut of uncooked red meat, as a T-bone or rib-eye steak, with the light, white marbling of fat.
May be used for sexual slang.

Cut of Meat was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A fire extinguisher, as used to put out small fires. Depicted as a red tank with a black hose and pressure gauge. Most platforms include an image of a flame on a white label.
Commonly used for various content concerning fire safety, emergencies, and literal and figurative fires.

Fire Extinguisher was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An elderly man gray (grey) hair, and visible wrinkles. Balding in many versions of this artwork, such as Apple and Microsoft designs.

Old Man was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Older Man”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A hockey stick and puck, used in the sport of ice hockey. Not to be confused with the field hockey stick and ball.



Ice Hockey was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Ice Hockey Stick and Puck”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Australia, which may show as the letters AU on some platforms.
The Flag: Australia emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Australia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A six-sided die, used in a range of board and turn-based games. Commonly called dice which refers to the plural of die.
Most other platforms display this emoji as a single game die in white or red. LG shows two game dice in this emoji.

Game Die was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Madagascar, which may show as the letters MG on some platforms
The Flag: Madagascar emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Madagascar was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A waning crescent moon (appearing to become smaller), the last of the phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its left side illuminated in a thin, golden or silver crescent, its remainder dark.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.
See also 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌒 Waxing Crescent Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning crescent moon in a night sky with stars.

Waning Crescent Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Waning Crescent Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🏌 Golfer emoji.
The Woman Golfing emoji is a sequence of the 🏌 Golfer and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Golfing was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Woman Playing Water Polo emoji is a sequence of the 🤽 Water Polo and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Playing Water Polo was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The word "top" with an arrow pointing up above it.

Top Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Top With Upwards Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A strip of film, as used in a movie camera or photography. Generally depicted as several horizontal frames of unexposed film with black trim and perforations.
Commonly used for various content concerning movies, film, video, and photography as well as an icon for a video or picture, as before an upload, link, or credit.
Apple’s design features an S-shaped, sepia-tinged strip.

Film Frames was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A lowercase letter i, enclosed in a rounded square or circle. Implemented in apps or websites to indicate that help or further information is available.
May be used as a logo for tourist information signage in a town or city.

Information was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
under the name “Information Source”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit One emoji is a sequence of the 1 Digit One and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit One was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman with red hair. Sometimes described as ginger, orange, copper, or auburn.
The Woman: Red Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🦰 Emoji Component Red Hair emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman: Red Hair was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Moldova, which may show as the letters MD on some platforms.
The Flag: Moldova emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Moldova was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman standing in front of a chalkboard (aka blackboard) with the intention of teaching a class.
See also: 👨‍🏫 Male Teacher
The Woman Teacher emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🏫 School emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Teacher was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Tooth was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the ⛹ Person With Ball emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Bouncing Ball emoji is a sequence of the ⛹ Person With Ball and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Bouncing Ball was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A claw hammer, as used for driving or removing nails. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.
Commonly used for content concerning tools, building, and construction as well as various senses of breaking or smashing. May also represent hard work or be applied to hammer-related expressions, e.g., nailed it.
Apple and Facebook’s designs previously displayed a gavel, Softbank’s a mallet. Not to be confused with ⛏️ Pick or Axe.

Hammer was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two open hands, representing openness. Sometimes used as a hug, or as a display of jazz hands.

Open Hands was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Open Hands Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A thumbs-up gesture indicating approval.

Thumbs Up was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Thumbs Up Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for French Polynesia, which may show as the letters PF on some platforms.
The Flag: French Polynesia emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: French Polynesia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A tiger, a large cat with an orange coat and black stripes. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long tail, its distinctive stripes, and, on some platforms, white patches.
See also 🐯 Tiger Face. Not to be confused with 🐆 Leopard.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.
Google’s design is noticeably more cartoon-styled, as Facebook’s previously was. Microsoft’s design previously featured a yellow, forward-facing tiger, as if on the prowl.

Tiger was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A hand waving most commonly used to say “hello” or “goodbye”.
This emoji can be used to convey a sense of not being friends any more when used on WeChat in China.

Waving Hand was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Waving Hand Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Niue, which may show as the letters NU on some platforms.
The Flag: Niue emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Niue was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A videotape cassette, as a VHS tape used to watch movies or record TV on VCRs before DVDs , DVRs, and streaming. Generally depicted as a black cassette with a white label between its reels.
Occasionally used for various content concerning film and video (taping) as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit. May also be used to represent audio cassette tapes.
Microsoft’s design previously resembled a voicemail icon.

Videocassette was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A trumpet, a brass instrument played in jazz bands.

Trumpet was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Vietnam, which may show as the letters VN on some platforms.
The Flag: Vietnam emoji is a sequence of the 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Vietnam was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Belgium, which may show as the letters BE on some platforms.
The Flag: Belgium emoji is a sequence of the 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Belgium was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Genie emoji is a sequence of the 🧞 Genie and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Genie was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
SOS is the description for the distress signal in Morse Code. This emoji means SOS or “emergency”.

SOS Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared SOS”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The heart-shaped twist of a hard or soft golden-brown pretzel, seasoned with grains of salt. A snack commonly associated with Germany.

Pretzel was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The face of a dragon, a mythical creature resembling a giant reptile found in the folklore of many cultures. Depicted as a green, Chinese-styled dragon looking straight ahead or facing left. Often shown with huge nostrils, baring large teeth and a red tongue, with antler-like structures on its head, whisker-like tendrils by its nostrils, and a green or yellow mane.
See also 🐉 Dragon. One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Commonly used on Chinese New Year and St. George's Day. Also used for various medieval and fantasy content.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Microsoft's dragon face was previously red and looking straight ahead. Samsung's dragon face previously resembled a red, friendly, cartoon-styled imp with horns.

Dragon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A firecracker, as lit on Chinese New Year, New Year's Eve, or Independence Day. Depicted as a red tube with a burning fuse, sometimes lined with gold rings at its top and base.
Often used with 🎆 Fireworks and 🎇 Sparkler for various celebrations and holidays. Also applied to figurative senses of fire, e.g., slang hot, on fire (“excellent”).
While it may resemble a stick of dynamite on some platforms, several vendor designs, such as Google and Twitter's, suggest the emoji is modeled after traditional Chinese firecrackers, as are strung together and lit on such occasions as Chinese New Year.

Firecracker was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The man version of the 🙋 Happy Person Raising One Hand emoji.
The Man Raising Hand emoji is a sequence of the 🙋 Happy Person Raising One Hand and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Raising Hand was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Ornamental Japanese Emperor and Empress dolls, as displayed in celebration of Hinamatsuri on March 3 in Japan (Girls’ or Dolls’ Day).
Generally depicted as a Japanese Emperor (left, in blue, holding a scepter) and Empress (right, in red, holding a fan) in ceremonial court dress and seated on a tatami.
When not applied to Hinamatsuri, sometimes used to represent Japan, dolls, a pair of people (as a couple or two friends), and for various idiosyncratic purposes.

Japanese Dolls was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A fishing rod (pole) with a fish caught on the end.

Fishing Pole was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Fishing Pole and Fish”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for South Africa, which may show as the letters ZA on some platforms.
The Flag: South Africa emoji is a sequence of the 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: South Africa was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Fairy emoji is a sequence of the 🧚 Fairy and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Fairy was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two hands raised in the air, celebrating success or another joyous event.

Raising Hands was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Person Raising Both Hands in Celebration”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A snake, a slithering reptile without limbs. Generally depicted as a yellowish-green snake facing left, with a long, coiled body and flicking a red, forked tongue.
May be used for various metaphorical senses of snake.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. May also be used in association with ⛎ Ophiuchus, the Serpent-Bearer, sometimes considered a 13th sign of the Western zodiac.
Samsung’s snake was previously facing forward.

Snake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Fiji, which may show as the letters FJ on some platforms.
The Flag: Fiji emoji is a sequence of the 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F and 🇯 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter J emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Fiji was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Atom Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An information desk person, iconically represented in the Apple emoji artwork as a woman holding out her hand as if she were a waitress carrying an invisible tray of drinks.
Can be used for a variety of interpretations, such as sassiness or sarcasm. No gender is specified for this emoji, though the most common representation is as a woman.

Person Tipping Hand was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Information Desk Person”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Artist emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🎨 Artist Palette emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Artist was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Seven emoji is a sequence of the 7 Digit Seven and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Seven was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A flying saucer, sometimes referred to as an Unidentified Flying Object (UFO). Shown on some platforms with an alien at the controls and/or a beam of light emitting from the base.

Flying Saucer was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle lowercase letter input.

Input Latin Lowercase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Input Symbol for Latin Small Letters”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Zero emoji is a sequence of the 0 Digit Zero and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Zero was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🏊 Swimmer emoji.
The Woman Swimming emoji is a sequence of the 🏊 Swimmer and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Swimming was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Mozambique, which may show as the letters MZ on some platforms.
The Flag: Mozambique emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Mozambique was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A tornado, a destructive column of air. Depicted as a gray, funnel-shaped cloud, rotating in contact with the ground.
May be used as a weather icon to represent a tornado. May also be used to represent a metaphorical tornado (e.g., a powerful force or violent outburst).
Google’s tornado was previously blue and white. Microsoft and Samsung’s designs previously depicted tornadoes defending from a cumulus cloud.

Tornado was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
 under the name “Cloud With Tornado”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for  Heard & McDonald Islands, which may show as the letters HM on some platforms. This is the same flag as Australia.
The Flag: Heard & McDonald Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Heard & McDonald Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Saxophone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A mobile phone held up to take a selfie (photo of the person holding the phone or camera). Generally represented as a disembodied arm holding a mobile phone.

Selfie was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A red face with an angry expression: frowning mouth with eyes and eyebrows scrunched downward. Bears the same expression as 😠 Angry Face on most platforms and may convey more intense degrees of anger, e.g., hate or rage.
Samsung’s design previously featured a yellow face with the anger symbol on its forehead. Microsoft’s design previously featured a yellow face with a more hurt expression.
Not to be confused with 🙎 Person With Pouting Face. This emoji also has a cat variant, 😾 Pouting Cat Face.


Pouting Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😂 Face With Tears of Joy. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Cat With Tears of Joy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Cat Face With Tears of Joy”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Antarctica, which may show as the letters AQ on some platforms.
The Flag: Antarctica emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇶 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Q emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Antarctica was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A gambling machine generally found in casinos. Shows three wheels with a lever to the side. Most platforms display three 7 digits on this emoji.

Slot Machine was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A human nose. May be used to indicate smelling, or something that smells.

Nose was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A pole spiraled with red, white, and blue stripes, as spins out front of a barbershop. Commonly used for various content concerning haircutting and hairstyling.
May also be associated with brothels in parts of Asia.

Barber Pole was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Romania, which may show as the letters RO on some platforms.
The Flag: Romania emoji is a sequence of the 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Romania was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A bottle of milk or formula, as or fed to a baby, with a bluish cap and rubber nipple or teat. Positioned upright or at a 45° angle, and filled to various levels, sometimes showing fill lines. Often used for newborns and childrearing. See also Breast-Feeding.

Baby Bottle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A generic bird. Variously depicted as a blue or red bird, as a bluebird or cardinal, shown standing in full profile, or as a bird head. Both designs show the bird facing left.
May be used for a variety of wild and pet birds as well as for metaphorical senses of bird (e.g., birdie in golf).
Apple and WhatsApp’s designs feature a grayish bird head. Google, Samsung, and Facebook’s designs suggest a bluebird, Microsoft and Twitter’s a cardinal. Google’s bird previously resembled a canary, Samsung’s was previously green, and Microsoft and Twitter’s birds were once blue.


Bird was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A silver shower head, streaming water to the left. Pressure level varies across platforms. 🧼 Soap not provided.
Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and water. Shower heads are also featured in 🛁 Bathtub and 🛀 Person Taking a Bath.

Shower was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Lithuania, which may show as the letters LT on some platforms.
The Flag: Lithuania emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Lithuania was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Supervillain emoji is a sequence of the 🦹 Supervillain and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Supervillain was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A train and railway in the mountains. Displayed as a funicular in Microsoft’s artwork, or a regular train on other platforms.
Android displays this train front-facing, leaving a tunnel, which appears similarly to the metro emoji at small sizes.

Mountain Railway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two curly loops, which represent a reel-to-reel tape recorder. Used as a symbol for voicemail on many phones.
A variation of this logo is used by Free Dial, a toll-free telephone number by NTT in Japan.

Double Curly Loop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a monkey, looking straight ahead. Depicted as a brown-haired monkey with a tan or pinkish face, round ears, nostrils, and open-mouthed smile.
As with the full-bodied 🐒 Monkey, often used with a playful tone or for metaphorical senses of monkey.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Available as an Apple Animoji.
Vendors implement the same or similar monkey face in their Three Wise Monkeys emojis: 🙈 See-No-Evil Monkey, 🙉 Hear-No-Evil Monkey, and 🙊 Speak-No-Evil Monkey.
Facebook’s monkey previously resembled 🐻 Bear Face.

Monkey Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 👱 Person With Blond Hair emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji
The Man: Blond Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👱 Person With Blond Hair and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man: Blond Hair was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Yin Yang was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Similar to a train, but running on a single track. Monorails are often found at theme parks, or other tourist destinations.

Monorail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Man, Girl, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👧 Girl and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Girl, Boy was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A microphone, as used for radio broadcasting or studio recording. Most platforms depict a vintage, silver microphone, like the Shure Unidyne 55.
Commonly used for various content concerning radio, broadcasting, music, recording, and podcasts.
Not to be confused with the handheld 🎤 Microphone, associated with live singing.

Studio Microphone was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A full moon, the fifth phase of the eight phases of the moon, when it is completely lit. Depicts the moon as a full, gold or silver, cratered disc, completely illuminated by the sun.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. Commonly used during Halloween, associated with werewolves and Friday the 13th.
See also 🌝 Full Moon Face. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a full moon in a night sky with stars.

Full Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Full Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Heavy Exclamation Mark Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Delivery Truck was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for US Virgin Islands, which may show as the letters VI on some platforms.
The Flag: U.S. Virgin Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: U.S. Virgin Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
The Milky Way – a galaxy of billions of stars that includes our own solar system and planet earth.
Shown by many platforms as a night sky, with silhouettes of mountains or hills in the foreground.

Milky Way was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Virgo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Maiden.

Virgo was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A mosquito, a type of bloodsucking fly. Depicted as a brown or black mosquito on its six, long legs, with wings, long abdomen, and needle-like mouth. Variously shown from above or facing left.
May be used to represent various insects, other bugs and bug bites, and insect-borne diseases (e.g., malaria). May also be used for metaphorical pests.
Microsoft and Facebook’s mosquitoes have red abdomens, as filled with blood.

Mosquito was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: Antigua & Barbuda emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Antigua & Barbuda was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A Tanabata tree, a type of wish tree on which people hang wishes written on paper and other decorations during Tanabata, a Japanese festival celebrating two heavenly lovers. Depicted as one or two stalks of green bamboo, on which hangs one or more slips of paper, generally red.
Often used to represent various plants or as a green accent color.
Apple’s design includes a yellow star decoration. Microsoft’s design previously displayed a green branch with three, variously colored pieces of paper.

Tanabata Tree was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a lion—the large cat and king of the jungle—looking straight ahead. Depicted as a golden-yellow lion face with a light- or dark-brown mane, white muzzle, and neutral expression.
Often used with an affectionate tone. Does not have a full-bodied lion emoji counterpart. A lion is represented as ♌ Leo in the Western zodiac.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Apple's lion previously featured a timid-looking expression.

Lion was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Lion Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a flat, closed mouth. Intended to depict a neutral sentiment but often used to convey mild irritation and concern or a deadpan sense of humor.

Neutral Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A ballot box, as used to cast votes in an election. Depicted as a box, generally blue or gray, with a slot on top through which a paper ballot is being inserted. Many platforms display a cross mark or check mark on the ballot to indicate a vote, though Apple and Facebook leave theirs blank.
Commonly used for various content concerning voting and elections, especially in politics and government.

Ballot Box With Ballot was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A fist pointing right, which may be used in conjunction with the left-facing fist to complete a fist-bump gesture.

Right-Facing Fist was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A traditional broom, as used for sweeping—or ridden by a witch. Shown at a 45° angle, with a wooden handle and yellow bristles at the lower left.
Commonly used for various content concerning cleaning, brushing, and figurative sweeps (e.g., in sports or awards). Not to be confused with 🖌️ Paintbrush.

Broom was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A human foot shown with five toes and may include part or all of the ankle. Shown on Apple platforms as the sole of a foot.

Foot was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys.
Trams tend to be similar to light rail, with the difference being that they don’t tend to have their own dedicated tracks.
This emoji is generally shown as the front of the tram, on tracks. The intended usage of this emoji, instead of the tram car emoji is not clear.

Tram was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A turtle, a slow-moving reptile with a shell. Depicted as a light-green turtle in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long neck and green, textured shell.
May be used to represent a tortoise and various senses of slow.
WhatsApp’s turtle has light-brown skin, Microsoft and Facebook’s a yellow-rimmed shell.

Turtle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Five emoji is a sequence of the 5 Digit Five and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Five was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Guernsey, which may show as the letters GG on some platforms.
The Flag: Guernsey emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Guernsey was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Eight O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Eight O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two pink love hearts. One larger than the other. Can be used to display that “love is in the air”.
On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you have been #1 BFs with each other for two consecutive months. A bug in October 2019 has a yellow heart emoji showing instead of 💕 for some Snapchat users.

Two Hearts was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Tuvalu, which may show as the letters TV on some platforms.
The Flag: Tuvalu emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Tuvalu was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A petri dish, as used to culture microbes. Depicted as a clear, shallow cylinder with a red, blue, or green growth medium, such as agar, with splotches of variously colored cells, like bacteria.
May be used for various content concerning biology and science more generally. May also be used to represent germs and other microorganisms.
Google’s design features a dropper, Samsung’s a lid.

Petri Dish was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A gold medal, given to a person who has won a sporting event, such as a race. Not to be confused with the military medal emoji.

Sports Medal was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A pregnant woman, intended to complete the family emoji set. Sometimes used in jest to represent feeling full after over-eating; aka "food baby".

Pregnant Woman was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Index finger pointing to the right.

Backhand Index Pointing Right was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “White Right Pointing Backhand Index”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Leaves, as fluttering in a spring or summer breeze. Depicted as one or two green, almond-shaped leaves, with gray or blue motion lines, as if swirling in the air or as the wind blowing through the trees.
May be used to represent the season of fall/autumn, trees, and nature more generally.
Not to be confused with 🍂 Fallen Leaf, though their applications may overlap.

Leaf Fluttering in Wind was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person with its hand in the air, as if it wants to ask or answer a question.
Generally displayed as a woman, but is not defined as one particular gender. Previously showed a blob-like gender-inclusive character in the Google artwork.

Person Raising Hand was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Happy Person Raising One Hand”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A white piece of paper secured by a silver clip on a brown clipboard, as used as a writing surface when standing. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, especially in sports.
Many platforms indicate text with dark lines. WhatsApp’s design shows lined paper. Facebook’s features the easter egg of a table with first names and numbers, perhaps as birthdates:
Matt 3/28

Louie 4/30

Alexa 6/17

Brian 8/06
Apple’s design also features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie and signed Take care from John Appleseed with the text of its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:
Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.

Clipboard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Man, Girl, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👧 Girl and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Girl, Girl was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Man in Lotus Position emoji is a sequence of the 🧘 Person in Lotus Position and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man in Lotus Position was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A classic snowman, as Frosty the Snowman. Depicted as a snowman, facing forward, made from two or three large snowballs and stick arms, dressed with a top hat, a carrot nose, coal eyes, and two or three buttons on its torso. Sometimes shown with a smile and a red scarf.
Often used for various content concerning winter fun and Christmastime.
Vendors implement the same figure for their ☃️ Snowman, but which has snowflakes falling on it.
Google’s snowman is wearing green gloves, though its snowman previously lacked any attire. Samsung's previously lacked a hat.

Snowman Without Snow was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Man, Woman, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👩 Woman and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Woman, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Curaçao, which may show as the letters CW on some platforms.
The Flag: Curaçao emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Curaçao was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A star with six points, and a dot in the center. Similar to the Star of David emoji.

Dotted Six-Pointed Star was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A seat, which could refer to any form of place to sit, with the distinction that a seat is generally fixed, and is not a chair which can be moved.
This emoji is intended to be a seat on some form of mass-transit, such as on an airplane, train or bus. Google previously displayed this as an orange wooden chair.

Seat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A red brick or bricks. Depicted in a loose stack, a single object with holes, or as built into wall, as of a house, school, or other structure.
Commonly used for various content concerning building and construction. May also be used for figurative bricks, e.g., slang brick, “extremely cold (weather).”

Brick was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page torn off from a daily desk calendar, displaying month (usually abbreviated and in a red or blue header) and day on a white, square page.
Like 📆 Tear-Off Calendar and 🗓️ Spiral Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally.
Apple, Google, Samsung, and JoyPixels's dates show July 17. Apple first featured this date in reference to its calendar app on July 17, 2002; originally known as iCal, the app's icon also displays July 17. Emojipedia so chose July 17 as the date for World Emoji Day, first celebrated in 2014. Several major platforms, including Google and Samsung, have since featured July 17 in honor of the occasion. Other vendors feature easter egg dates marking company founding or other milestones:

📅 Apple: July 17 (Mac iCal announcement in 2002, later World Emoji Day)
📅 Google: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a generic monthly calendar)
📅 Microsoft: 21st of a generic month
📅 Samsung: July 17 (World Emoji Day; previously a monthly calendar turned to May)
📅 WhatsApp: Feb 24 (incorporation of WhatsApp in 2009)
📅 Twitter: March 21 (founding of Twitter in 2006; changed from July 15, when launched)
📅 Facebook: May 14 (birthday of founder Mark Zuckerberg; previously a generic 3rd)
📅 JoyPixels: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
📅 emojidex: Tuesday, Jan 12 (unknown)

Discontinued:

📅 Messenger: August (first release of Messenger apps in 2011)
📅 LG: Mar 27 (unknown)
📅 HTC: generic
📅 Mozilla: July 17 (World Emoji Day)
📅 Softbank: generic
📅 Docomo: 12 (suggesting the number of months in a year)  
📅 au by KDDI: 12


Calendar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A silver paper clip, as used to hold together sheets of paper—or remove a SIM card from a mobile phone. Shown positioned at various angles.
Occasionally used to represent school/office supplies. Also sometimes used as an icon before a hyperlink.
Not to be confused with 🔗 Link, 🖇️ Linked Paperclips, ⛓️ Chains, 🧷 Safety Pin—or Microsoft’s Clippy.

Paperclip was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Creatures with pointed ears and human-like faces. Female and male elves are available.

Elf was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Used either as a literal airplane, or sometimes to represent an overseas vacation, or airplane mode on a phone or tablet.
As of July 2018 the airplane emoji has been made available as a new Facebook reaction for users in some markets. This is available in addition to existing emoji reactions such as the thumbs up, heart, or laughing face and appears to be the unintentially result of a internal testing reaction being made public.

Airplane was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A magnetic compass, as used for navigation. Generally depicted in a silver or gold case with a compass rose and a red-tipped needle. Commonly used for various content concerning traveling and exploring as well as metaphorical compasses (e.g., moral compass).
Google and Facebook’s markings include the initials of the four cardinal directions, north, south, east, and west. Not to be confused with various clock or timepiece emojis.

Compass was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A burning candle, as lit when taking a bath or the power is out. Depicted as a white, pillar-shaped candle with a flame and wax dripping down its sides.
Used for a wide array of content, such as various senses of light, birthdays, remembrance, relaxation, and topics concerning religion and Halloween. Notably featured in the Summoning Circle meme on Twitter.
Apple and Google’s candles are in silver holders. Samsung’s candle was previously pink, perhaps as in a birthday cake.

Candle was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014

and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A paper tray with a down arrow on top, as a symbol for an email inbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden try with a red or green arrow.
May be used for various digital activity, including downloading, messaging, and emailing.
Google’s design feature a blue arrow and contains paper, as does Facebook's.
See also 📤 Outbox Tray.

Inbox Tray was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The reddish-brown, acorn-shaped chestnut, tapering to a sharp tip from its light brown base on most platforms. A popular roasted snack associated with autumn and Christmas. 
May be used for other edible nuts (e.g., walnuts) or sexual slang.

Chestnut was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A banded stack of yen banknotes, the paper currency of Japan. Color and detail vary across platforms, but usually shown in green, yellow, or pink with the yen symbol, ¥. Commonly used for various content concerning money and wealth, not restricted to Japan.
Apple and WhatsApp’s designs depict the ¥1,000 banknote, Facebook’s features a Japanese character for yen (円) and a cherry blossom.

Yen Banknote was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Banknote With Yen Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two mothers, and one daughter.
The Family: Woman, Woman, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👩 Woman and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Woman, Girl was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A party popper, as explodes in a shower of confetti and streamers at a celebration. Generally depicted as a gold party hat, striped on some platforms, at a 45° angle, with multicolored confetti and streamers coming from its opening at the upper right. Twitter’s cone is red.
Like 🎊 Confetti Ball, commonly used to convey congratulations and celebration, as on New Year’s Eve, birthdays, wedding days, graduations, and other special occasions or good times more generally.

Party Popper was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Man Playing Handball emoji is a sequence of the 🤾 Handball and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Playing Handball was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A handbag, used predominantly by women to carry personal items and/or as a fashion accessory.
The style of this emoji varies greatly by platform, with leather-related colors such as brown or orange the most commonly displayed. Samsung shows a pink handbag, and Twitter a purple handbag.
Not to be confused with the smaller and handle-less pouch emoji.

Handbag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A hazard symbol for radiation or radioactivity. May appear similar to a three-pronged fan at small sizes.
Generally displayed on an orange or yellow background.

Radioactive was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Radioactive Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A clear glass shaker of salt with a silver cap, as paired with pepper to season food when eating at a restaurant.

Salt was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Salt Shaker”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol showing a person putting litter (rubbish) in the trash (rubbish bin). A more positive version of the Do Not Litter Symbol.

Litter in Bin Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Put Litter in Its Place Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
