emoji_description:
A classic smiley, turned upside down. Implemented as a flipped version of 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face on most platforms.
Commonly used to convey irony, sarcasm, joking, or a sense of goofiness or silliness. Its intent can be similar to the bemused Oh well! of 🤷 Person Shrugging or the shruggie emoticon, ¯\_(ツ)_/¯.
Microsoft's design previously featured a full-toothed grin.

Upside-Down Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth on most platforms, with stars for eyes, as if seeing a beloved celebrity. Color of stars widely varies by platform, though commonly gold or red. May express that someone or something is amazing, fascinating, impressive, or exciting.

Star-Struck was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Grinning Face With Star Eyes”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A stylized representation of a shooting star, a small, fast meteor that burns up in the atmosphere. Generally depicted as a gold, five-point star trailing yellow motion lines against a night sky, as if moving down to the left.
May be used for astronomical stars and other content concerning space. Also may be used for flair or flourish. Sometimes used as a visual reference to NBC’s More You Know public service announcement, popular in the 1990s and featuring a shooting star logo.
Not to be confused with 💫 Dizzy, ⭐ Star, 🌟 Glowing Star, or ✨ Sparkles, though their applications may overlap.
Google’s star is trailed, without backdrop, by yellow lines, though they were previously blue. Microsoft’s star is trailed, without backdrop, by blue lines, though they were previously yellow.

Shooting Star was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two women standing next to each other, smiling, with a pink love heart floating in the air between them.
The Couple With Heart: Woman, Woman emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, ❤ Heavy Black Heart and 👩 Woman emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Couple With Heart: Woman, Woman was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A crocodile, a stealthy reptile with massive jaws. Generally depicted as a light-green crocodile on all fours, with its long tail curving down to its toothed jaws, facing left.
May resemble and be used for an alligator.
Facebook's crocodile is opening its jaws. Samsung’s design previously resembled a kind of cartoon dinosaur.

Crocodile was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Mayotte, which may show as the letters YT on some platforms.
The Flag: Mayotte emoji is a sequence of the 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Mayotte was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for El Salvador, which may show as the letters SV on some platforms.
The Flag: El Salvador emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: El Salvador was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A bug, or insect, generally depicted as a caterpillar, which becomes a 🦋 Butterfly. Shown in full profile facing left, inching up on the back of its green, segmented, and textured body. Often featuring black stripes or yellow dots and tentacles on its head.
May be used to represent various insects, worms, and related animals. May also be used for metaphorical senses of bug.
Twitter’s bug is purple. Apple’s bug is hairy with a red head and legs and black stripes on its body. Microsoft’s bug also has a red head, Facebook’s is yellowish-orange. Google and Microsoft’s bugs previously resembled an orange centipede or millipede, and Samsung’s had a cartoon-styled face with a purple nose.


Bug was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A child with no gender specified. This may be used as a gender-inclusive alternative to the boy or girl emoji.

Child was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A lit, filtered cigarette, shown burning at different directions. Commonly used to represent various forms of smoking (e.g., tobacco, marijuana, vaping) as well as metaphorical senses of smoking.
Originally intended as a sign for a designated smoking area, as contrasted to 🚭 No Smoking Symbol. This is illustrated in Samsung’s previous design of a stylized, white cigarette on a blue background.

Cigarette was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smoking Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Eleven-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Eleven-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Hong Kong, which may show as the letters HK on some platforms.
The Flag: Hong Kong SAR China emoji is a sequence of the 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Hong Kong SAR China was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A bowl of steaming-hot food. Depicted as Japanese ramen (noodles in broth) with chopsticks on most platforms, though it can represent a warm meal more generally. Samsung’s design resembles Pot of Food.

Steaming Bowl was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A thumbs-down gesture indicating disapproval.

Thumbs Down was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Thumbs Down Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A love hotel is a hotel that can be hired by the hour instead of as accommodation for the evening.
Sometimes mistaken for a get well soon emoji due to the similarity in appearance to the hospital. The Microsoft version of this emoji previously displaying a bed with a heart above it.

Love Hotel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Papua New Guinea, which may show as the letters PG on some platforms.
The Flag: Papua New Guinea emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Papua New Guinea was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A spiral-bound calendar. Generally depicted as a monthly calendar, with a red or blue header. Apple and Samsung’s pages are curled up at the bottom right, as to flip for a new month.
Like 📅 Calendar and 📆 Tear-Off Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally.
Twitter and Facebook’s design feature a generic month, Microsoft’s a generic 31 (as the number of days in most months). WhatsApp's design shows in a green header February, when it was incorporated in 2009. Apple, Samsung, and JoyPixels’s designs show the month of July, when World Emoji Day falls on the 17th, a date Google specifically displays.

Spiral Calendar was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Spiral Calendar Pad”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a hand covering its mouth. Apple and Facebook feature simple, open eyes, suggesting someone gasping Oh my! in serious surprise, shock, concern, or apology. Other platforms depict a face with smiling eyes and/or blushing cheeks, suggesting coy laughter or embarrassment, as if cheekily saying Oops! 
May be used to similar effect as 🙊 Speak-No-Evil Monkey. See also 🤐 Zipper-Mouth Face. Joins 🤗 Hugging Face, 🤔 Thinking Face, and 🤫 Shushing Face as one of the few smileys featuring hands.
Facebook's design previously featured smiling eyes and mouth.

Face With Hand Over Mouth was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes and Hand Covering Mouth”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Mountain Cableway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A bed, made up for sleeping in a house, hotel, or other sleeping accommodation. Shown with a headboard at the left, footboard, mattress, pillow, and sheet. Most platforms suggest a wooden frame and feature blue or red sheets.
Commonly used for various content concerning beds, furniture, and housing as well as sleeping, relaxing, and other bedroom activities.
Vendors implement the same style of bed for 🛌 Person in Bed, but without a sleeper under the covers.

Bed was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two men holding hands, most likely due to being in a relationship.

Men Holding Hands was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Two Men Holding Hands”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A swirl of brown poop, shaped like soft-serve ice cream with large, excited eyes and a big, friendly smile.
May be used to represent feces and other bathroom topics as well as stand in for their many related slang terms. It also enjoys a wide range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of whimsy or silliness, given its fun, happy expression.
Microsoft and Google previously depicted a literal pile of feces, Google’s design featuring stink lines and flies hovering above it.
Available as an Apple Animoji.

Pile of Poo was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for United Arab Emirates, which may show as the letters AE on some platforms.
The Flag: United Arab Emirates emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: United Arab Emirates was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A cow, a bovine farmed for its meat or milk. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left with a black-and-white patched coat (as a Holstein Friesian) and, on many platforms, a pink udder and horns.
May be used to represent the animal, its food products, or black-and-white coloring. See also 🐮 Cow Face.
Microsoft's cow was previously brown, as was Facebook's, which had a bell around its neck.

Cow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A tall glass of white milk, as from a cow but also other mammals, nuts, or plants. Most platforms depict a glass filled near to the brim, but some show a glass half-full—or half-empty.

Glass of Milk was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A rocket being propelled into space.

Rocket was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Railway Track was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for North Macedonia (until 2019: Macedonia), which may show as the letters MK on some platforms.
Displays a stylized yellow sun on a red background, with eight rays extending from the center to each edge.
The Flag: North Macedonia emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.


Flag: North Macedonia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A poodle, a popular dog breed with curly hair, often groomed in an ornamental pattern.
Generally depicted as a grayish-white poodle in full profile on all fours facing left, with a shaved torso, legs, and face with fuller, pom-pom-like hair on its head, ears, chest, feet, and tip of tail (as the Continental Clip).
Like 🐕 Dog, may be used to represent a variety of dog breeds (often fluffy or long-haired). See also 🐶 Dog Face.
With an upturned snout, Google’s poodle bears an endearingly haughty expression.
Google, Samsung, and Facebook’s design previously featured pink poodles.

Poodle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
An ear of corn, or maize, partially husked to show its buttery-yellow kernels.

Ear of Corn was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Ear of Maize”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with raised eyebrows, dollar signs for eyes, and an open smile sticking out a tongue styled after a green, dollar banknote. Some platforms depict the dollar-sign eyes in green circles.
Used for a wide range of content dealing with money, including: making money, loving wealth, being or feeling rich, and concepts of success and excellence (e.g., on the money).

Money-Mouth Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
This 空 character means empty and available in Japanese. This is used in the context of an empty parking space or a vacant hotel room.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Vacancy” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7a7a”
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A form of public transport similar to a tram, but running on a track or network separated from cars and other types of traffic.
Difficult to discern from a train at small sizes.

Light Rail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A Japanese kadomatsu, composed of pine leaves and bamboo shoots. Traditionally placed outside homes in Japan around the New Year to welcome spirits for a plentiful, happy year ahead.
Depicted as three shoots of bamboo, arranged vertically at different heights in a wooden container, arrayed with pine leaves.
Often used to represent various plants or as a green accent color.
WhatsApp’s kadomatsu is adorned with red berries, as is Facebook’s, which also includes pink cherry blossoms.

Pine Decoration was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description: null

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A silver safety pin or clip, as used to fasten fabric. Generally shown clasped at a 45° angle, with its spring at the lower left.
May be used for various content concerning arts, crafts, and sewing. Not to be confused with 📎 Paperclip.

Safety Pin was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A construction site generally depicted as a tower crane shown lifting steel or other building materials.

Building Construction was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Libya, which may show as the letters LY on some platforms.
The Flag: Libya emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Libya was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A common fish, as swims in the water. Depicted as a generic, light-blue fish, often with a white underside, in full profile facing left, with fins and prominent gill cover.
May be used to represent a variety of other fish (freshwater or saltwater), fishing, metaphorical senses of fish, and fish as food, as consumed in the form of 🍣 Sushi. May be used to represent ♓ Pisces, the Fish, in the Western zodiac.
Not to be confused with 🐠 Tropical Fish or 🐡 Blowfish, though their applications may overlap. Vendors implement a similar design to the fish caught on the 🎣 Fishing Pole.
Microsoft’s fish was previously yellow.

Fish was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person doing a cartwheel, representing the sport of gymnastics.

Person Cartwheeling was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Person Doing Cartwheel”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A pair of scissors, as used to cut paper or hair. Generally shown open, blades down, with red handles. Commonly used for content concerning haircuts, fashion design, arts and crafts, and various senses of cutting.
WhatsApp’s design features green handles with blades pointed up.
See the glossary for the term black in Unicode character names.

Scissors was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Scissors”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: Palestinian Territories emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Palestinian Territories was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A golden-brown, crescent-shaped, vanilla-flavored fortune cookie. Usually depicted with a strip of paper—on which a wise saying, lucky numbers, or Chinese vocabulary is written—peaking out of its hollow shell. Given at the end of meals at Chinese restaurants in the West.

Fortune Cookie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Taurus astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Bull.

Taurus was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A restroom symbol, depicting a iconography of a man and woman. Used to indicate the location of public bathrooms / toilets / restrooms.
Used as an alternative to the water closet symbol.

Restroom was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A pear-shaped avocado, sliced in half to show its yellow-green flesh and large brown pit. Ready for toast, guacamole, or millennial jokes.

Avocado was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Woman Juggling emoji is a sequence of the 🤹 Juggling and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Juggling was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol showing the numbers 1, 2, 3 and 4. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable symbol input, as opposed to alphabetical or symbol input.

Input Numbers was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Input Symbol for Numbers”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a big grin and scrunched, X-shaped eyes, tilted on its side as if rolling on the floor laughing (the internet acronym ROFL). Sheds two tears and tilts right on most platforms. Often conveys hysterical laughter more intense than 😂 Face With Tears of Joy.
Microsoft's design previously featured a smiley with hands and feet. 

Rolling on the Floor Laughing was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A light bulb, as screwed into a lamp to light a room. Depicted as an incandescent bulb with a silver base, often shown with filament and a soft, yellow-white glow.
Commonly used to represent ideas (as over a head in a cartoon), thinking, and learning, often as paired with 🤔 Thinking Face or 💭 Thought Balloon. May also represent various senses of light and brightness.

Light Bulb was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Electric Light Bulb”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The tropical fruit of a pineapple, shown in spiky, golden-brown skin and with a pointed, green crown. Positioned upright or at a 45° angle.

Pineapple was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with an open smile, sometimes showing teeth, and red, cartoon-styled hearts for eyes. Often conveys enthusiastic feelings of love, infatuation, and adoration, e.g., I love/am in love with this person or thing.
This emoji has a cat variant, 😻 Smiling Cat Face With Heart-Eyes.

Smiling Face With Heart-Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smiling Face With Heart-Shaped Eyes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Cook emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🍳 Cooking emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Cook was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A stemmed glass with a cone-shaped bowl, used for serving cocktails. Depicted as a martini garnished with an olive. Might be gin or vodka, shaken or stirred. See also Tropical Drink.

Cocktail Glass was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for French Guiana, which may show as the letters GF on some platforms.
The Flag: French Guiana emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: French Guiana was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A trident is a three-pronged spear, that appears similar to a pitchfork. Often held by Greek or Roman Gods in statues.

Trident Emblem was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Denotes a “good bargain” in Japanese.

Japanese “Bargain” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Circled Ideograph Advantage”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A symbol for high voltage, as warns against injury from electricity. Depicted as a jagged yellow bolt.
Commonly used to represent lightning, electricity, and various flashes. Also used to represent metaphorical energy and signal attention online.
Samsung’s bolt was previously white on a blue square, as an icon for high voltage.

High Voltage was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
under the name “High Voltage Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man in Steamy Room emoji is a sequence of the 🧖 Person in Steamy Room and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man in Steamy Room was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A framed picture of a painting or photograph, as displayed in a gallery or on a household wall. Vendors feature various scenes, though generally a lush, sunny landscape of hills and mountains, in a gold frame.
Commonly used for various content concerning art, museums, and interior design and decor. May also be used as an icon for a picture, as before an upload, link, or credit.
Microsoft’s design shows Ninja Cat, though it previously featured the Mona Lisa, as did Samsung. Google's design displays the scene depicted in its 🏞️ National Park.

Framed Picture was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Frame With Picture”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Azerbaijan, which may show as the letters AZ on some platforms.
The Flag: Azerbaijan emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Azerbaijan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A white paper receipt, as proof of payment, and shown flat or curled. May be used for other financial documents (e.g., invoice, tax form). May also be used for the slang receipts, or "evidence” or “confirmation” of some feat or controversy.
Some vendors feature easter eggs. Apple’s design, for instance, displays the date of July 17 (World Emoji Day); items referencing its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign (misfits, square pegs, round holes); and a balance $0.00.

Receipt was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A fuel pump, used to fill up a vehicle with gas / petrol.
Shown as red or orange on most platforms. Apple's artwork shows a droplet icon and the numbers 00322 but previously displayed the letter G on the front.

Fuel Pump was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A bat, the flying mammal of the night. Variously depicted as a brown, black, or gray bat, with wings outspread and pointy ears, facing forward or left.
Often used in association with Halloween, vampires, and Batman.
Google’s bat is purplish in color, bearing two fangs. Samsung’s bat was previously brown, Facebook’s gray.

Bat was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A male astronaut or cosmonaut shown wearing a space suit and helmet.
The Man Astronaut emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🚀 Rocket emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Astronaut was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Tokelau, which may show as the letters TK on some platforms.
The Flag: Tokelau emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Tokelau was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A flying disc, more commonly known as a frisbee. Used in the sport of Ultimate or disc golf.

Flying Disc was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Greenland, which may show as the letters GL on some platforms.
The Flag: Greenland emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Greenland was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The red dragon tile in the game of Japanese Mahjong. White, with red 中 character printed on it.

Mahjong Red Dragon was approved as part of Unicode 5.1 in 2008
under the name “Mahjong Tile Red Dragon”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A Japanese bento, a lunch box divided into portions of rice, vegetables, and meat or seafood, such as sushi or fried shrimp.

Bento Box was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A customs officer inspecting luggage. May be shown on signage at airports or other border crossings.
Not to be confused with the passport control emoji.

Customs was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Two colorful shopping bags, as contain consumer items bought at a department store. Depicted as gift bags in various bright colors, patterns, sizes, and positions across platforms. Apple's design, for instance, features a pink bag with light-pink dots in front of a gold bag with yellow stripes.
Commonly used for various content concerning retail shopping, stores, goods, and gifts or presents. May also convey a sense of indulgence or self-care, à la retail therapy.
Microsoft’s design previously featured a bag of groceries and now includes tissue paper.

Shopping Bags was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Red Triangle Pointed Up was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Up-Pointing Red Triangle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A giraffe, the tallest animal on Earth, with spots and a long neck. Generally depicted in yellow or tan in full profile on all fours facing left, with distinctive brown spots and small, horn-like structures.
Microsoft and Samsung’s designs feature a giraffe face looking straight ahead. Facebook’s design previously featured only a giraffe face.

Giraffe was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Giraffe Face”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The word new, shown enclosed in a square.

New Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared New”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Mount Fuji (called Fuji-san in Japan) is the largest mountain in Japan. Often seen with snow on the peak in colder months of the year.
It is considered lucky in Japan to dream of Mt Fuji in the first dream of the new year.

Mount Fuji was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Mali, which may show as the letters ML on some platforms.
The Flag: Mali emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Mali was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A hunk of unspecified meat on a white bone, as associated with cartoon cavepersons or food in anime and manga (Japanese ano niku, “that meat”).
This emoji was shown as a steak in Android 4.4.

Meat on Bone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a slight smile shown winking, usually its left eye. May signal a joke, flirtation, hidden meaning, or general positivity. Tone varies, including playful, affectionate, suggestive, or ironic.
Not to be confused with the more mischievous or sexual 😏 Smirking Face. An emoji form of the ;) emoticon.

Winking Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Zombie emoji is a sequence of the 🧟 Zombie and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Zombie was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A fist pointing left, which may be used in conjunction with the right-facing fist to complete a fist-bump gesture.

Left-Facing Fist was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Exclamation Question Mark was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The number eighteen with a red stroke through it, indicating a location where a person must be aged 18 or above to enter.
The Samsung version of this emoji displays the number 19 instead of 18. This may be due to the practice of counting the first year of life as one (not zero) in parts of East Asia such as South Korea (the location of the Samsung Headquarters).

No One Under Eighteen was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 under the name “No One Under Eighteen Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A making a kissing gesture, with a pink love heart floating in the air between them. Previously shown as with the same appearance as 👩‍❤️‍💋‍👨 Kiss: Woman, Man on most platforms, but now displays two people with an ambiguous gender appearance.

Kiss was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Angola, which may show as the letters A and O on some platforms.
The Flag: Angola emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Angola was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Bangladesh, which may show as the letters BD on some platforms.
The Flag: Bangladesh emoji is a sequence of the 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Bangladesh was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow, pointing down.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Down Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
under the name “Downwards Black Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Monaco, which may show as the letters MC on some platforms.
The Flag: Monaco emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Monaco was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The word up with an exclamation point after it, shown enclosed in a square. Originally intended to denote leveling up in a game.

Up! Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared Up With Exclamation Mark”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Indonesia, which may show as the letters ID on some platforms.
The Flag: Indonesia emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Indonesia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic yellow pencil. Depicted as a graphite pencil, like a U.S. #2 or European HB, with a sharpened tip and pink eraser. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and schooling.
Samsung’s pencil was previously red, Google’s green.

Pencil was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A friendly-looking, tentacled space creature with two eyes. Most major platforms style their design after aliens in classic arcade games like Space Invaders, rendering it purple and pixellated, as if in 8-bit graphics.
Samsung’s design resembles an octopus and previously featured a big-brained alien, à la Star Trek. Earlier designs from Google and Microsoft depicted more cartoon-like alien monsters.
May be used of topics concerning extraterrestrial life, outer space, gaming, and computing, but also enjoys a range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of weirdness, wackiness, or excitement, given that the emoji looks like it is raising its arms shouting Yay! on many platforms.

Alien Monster was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A classic red apple, shown with a stem and single, green leaf on major platforms. Commonly associated with doctors, teachers, and New York.

Red Apple was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a party hat blowing a party horn as confetti floats around its head. Used for celebrating joyous occasions (such as New Year's Eve or World Emoji Day) and enjoying good times more generally.
Apple’s design features the same expression as its 😚 Kissing Face With Closed Eyes.

Partying Face was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Face With Party Horn and Party Hat”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Woman Cartwheeling emoji is a sequence of the 🤸 Person Doing Cartwheel and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Cartwheeling was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A water closet is a name used for public toilet, bathroom or restroom used in some countries. Typically abbreviated to the letters WC, this may be found on signage in public buildings, as an alternative to the restroom symbol.

Water Closet was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Cash money! A banded stack of U.S. dollar banknotes, the paper currency of the United States of America. Green hue and detail vary across platforms, but shown with the dollar sign, $. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.S.
Apple’s design depicts $1 bills with Cupertino and John Appleseed in the treasury signature sections. WhatsApp’s design depicts $10 bills, Facebook’s displays a Statue of Liberty torch.

Dollar Banknote was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Banknote With Dollar Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A stylized white flower. Generally depicted as a rosette-shaped cherry blossom in pink or red outline, often with a white fill.
Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook's designs feature Japanese characters roughly translating to very well done, used by teachers as a stamp for students who did exceptional work, often accompanied by a score in red.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such ideas as love, happiness, and beauty. Also used as a pink, white, or red accent color.
Not to be confused with 🌸 Cherry Blossom and 🌺 Hibiscus, though their applications may overlap.
Apple's flower previously featured a red-outlined design, Google's an orange outline. Microsoft's flower was previously black and white, Samsung and Facebook's pink and white.

White Flower was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
White Medium-Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002
under the name “White Medium Small Square”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A cartoon-style balloon used to represent spoken word in comics. Sometimes  used in communication apps to indicate that another person is typing a message.

Speech Balloon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two triangles pointing down. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° counter-clockwise.

Fast Down Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Black Down-Pointing Double Triangle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A pair of eyes, glancing slightly to the left on most platforms. The Google version of this emoji previously showed only a single eye, despite the name of this character being eyes (plural).
Sometimes used to indicate ‘pervy eyes’ to indicate approval of an attractive photo posted online; or ‘shifty eyes’ to convey a deceitful act.

Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An electric battery, as used to power such devices as a flashlight. Generally depicted as an upright, green cylinder, as a AA or D cell, with white indicators for its positive (facing up) and negative terminals.
Commonly used for various content concerning electricity, charging, energy, and power, especially in figurative senses. Its green color also suggests the icon for battery power on a cell/mobile phone.
Apple’s design includes a voltage symbol; WhatsApp’s battery is blue.

Battery was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010

and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man working in the field of health care. This may be used to represent a doctor, nurse, or pharmacist.
See also: 👩‍⚕️ Female Health Worker
The Man Health Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and ⚕ Staff of Aesculapius emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Health Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Fog, as obscures visibility. Generally depicted as a square of a gray, hazy, cloud-like mass.
May be used as a weather icon to represent foggy conditions. May also be used to represent metaphorical fog (e.g., a daze).
Not to be confused with 🌁 Foggy, though their applications may overlap.
Microsoft’s design is a stylized depiction of fog, featuring three, wavy lines, as Google’s previously did. Samsung’s fog previously resembled three clouds. Twitter’s design previously resembled its 🌁 Foggy emoji, showing fog obscuring the Golden Gate Bridge.

Fog was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: São Tomé & Príncipe emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: São Tomé & Príncipe was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Cape Verde, which may show as the letters CV on some platforms.
The Flag: Cape Verde emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Cape Verde was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Japanese koinobori, decorative, carp-shaped windsocks flown in celebration of Children’s Day on May 5 in Japan. Generally depicted as a blue and red stylized carp fish on a golden pole.
When not applied to Children’s Day, used for various idiosyncratic purposes. SoftBank’s design resembles more traditional koinobori.

Carp Streamer was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A horseshoe magnet, as used to pick up iron. Depicted at various angles in red with silver-tipped poles.
Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative magnetism and attraction. May also be used in various science-related contexts more generally.
Twitter’s design features two electric bolts coming from its poles. WhatsApp’s horseshoe is half blue, denoting an opposite magnetic pole.

Magnet was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes, closed smile, and halo, usually blue, overhead. Often represents angels, prayers, and blessings. May also convey angelic behavior, e.g., doing good deeds. See also 👼 Baby Angel.
Several platforms, including Apple, feature an expression similar to their 😊 Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes.

Smiling Face With Halo was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A red fire truck, an essential part of emergency services along with a police car or ambulance.
May be on the way to put out a fire.

Fire Engine was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Saudi Arabia, which may show as the letters SA on some platforms.
The Flag: Saudi Arabia emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Saudi Arabia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with slightly raised eyebrows, a frown, and eyes looking to the side. May convey a variety of negative emotions, including irritation, displeasure, grumpiness, and skepticism, as if giving the side-eye.
Not to be confused with 😏 Smirking Face, which features similar eyes but a wry smile.

Unamused Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A round, black and white ball used in the game of soccer, which is known as football in much of the world. See also: emojis for the World Cup.

Soccer Ball was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
Two Japanese Flags, crossed at the base. Except on some Samsung devices, which have previously displayed two South Korean flags.

Crossed Flags was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Kiribati, which may show as the letters KI on some platforms.
The Flag: Kiribati emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Kiribati was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A stop icon, displayed as a square.

Stop Button was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Black Square for Stop”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A joystick, as used in playing classic arcade, computer, or video games. Generally depicted with a black base, red-knobbed control stick, and one or more red buttons.
Commonly used for content concerning various types of gaming; occasionaly applied to aviation and aircraft.
Google's base is blue. Microsoft previously featured a more modern design.

Joystick was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A place to store notes and other office materials. Primarily used by older people.
Generally shown as a brown case with a handle on top, and a silver or gold colored clasp on the front. Facebook shows two leather straps on the front.

Briefcase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a slight frown, furrowed eyebrows, and scrunched, X-shaped eyes, as if holding back tears or exerting great effort. May convey various degrees and tones of frustration, sadness, helplessness, and struggle. Facebook’s design features a light-purple forehead.

Persevering Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
P Button was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter P”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The speak no evil monkey, called Iwazaru (Japanese for “say not”), one of the Three Wise Monkeys. Depicted as the brown 🐵 Monkey Face with its tan or pinkish hands covering its mouth.
The Three Wise Monkeys represent the proverb see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil, frequently interpreted as a call to discretion or figure for willful ignorance.
Often used as a playful way to convey I can’t believe what I just said!, express a mischievous Oops!, or communicate a secret-keeping I won’t say a word. May be used to similar effect as 🤭 Face With Hand Over Mouth or 🤐 Zipper Mouth.
See also 🙈 See-No-Evil Monkey and 🙉 Hear-No-Evil Monkey.

Speak-No-Evil Monkey was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A peacock, the male bird that displays a large, fan-like, iridescent tale. Depicted facing forward standing on its legs, with a blue body and green tail feathers outspread.
Sometimes used to suggest something is beautiful or proud. Also sometimes used to accent a peacock-like color or pattern.

Peacock was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic portable radio, as used to listen to music, news, or sports. Depicted in various colors and styles with a speaker, antenna, dial, and knobs.
Commonly used for various content concerning radio, broadcasting, and music.

Radio was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A house, otherwise known as a home when someone is living in it. Suitable for a couple or larger family, other perhaps housemates.
Distinct from an apartment building due to its detached form, this house is likely in the suburbs of a city or a rural area.

House was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “House Building”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A single ice skate used for ice skating. Shown in white and facing left on most platforms.
In the sport of figure skating, a white ice skate is traditionally worn by women, and a black ice skate worn by men. This emoji doesn't define the color to be used, but no major vendor currently displays this as black.

Ice Skate was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Laos, which may show as the letters LA on some platforms.
The Flag: Laos emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Laos was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A shrimp (prawn), a small crustacean with a long tail. Generally depicted as a reddish-orange shrimp (as cooked) in full profile facing left, with tiny eyes, many limbs, and its long antennae curling back as its long tail curls in.
May be consumed in the form of 🍤 Fried Shrimp or 🥘 Shallow Pan of Food. Often used to represent seafood.
The antennae of Apple’s shrimp curls under its body. The body of Facebook’s shrimp is straight. Google and Samsung’s shrimp previously faced right.

Shrimp was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic teddy bear, as snuggled by a child when going to sleep.
Depicted as a brown, stuffed toy bear, shown seated with its arms to the sides, hind paw pads facing forward, and a friendly smile on its face. WhatsApp, Twitter, and Facebook’s design include a ribbon around the neck.
Commonly used to convey something or someone is cute or cuddly (e.g., teddy bear as a term of endearment) as well as other warm, loving sentiments (e.g., get well soon). May also be used for various content concerning toys and children more generally.
Not to be confused with 🐻 Bear Face, though their applications may overlap.

Teddy Bear was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The fleshy, pinkish-orange fruit of the fuzzy peach, shown with green leaves and sometimes a stem.
Thanks to its distinctive cleft, the emoji is commonly used for “buttocks.”

Peach was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A ewe, or female sheep raised for its wool, meat, and milk and without the spiraling horns of a ram. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left with a thick, white fleece and black, gray, or white skin.
Not to be confused with 🐏 Ram, though their applications may overlap.
Often considered (in lieu of 🐐 Goat) one of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.
Apple and Google’s designs previously depicted a ram. Samsung and Facebook’s designs previously featured only a ewe face.

Ewe was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 under the name “Sheep”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A chicken, a bird used for its meat and eggs. Generally depicted as the white head of a chicken (hen or rooster) looking left, with a yellow beak, red comb on its head, and red wattle on its neck.
May be consumed in the form of 🍗 Poultry Leg. Not to be confused with the full-bodied 🐓 Rooster, though their applications overlap. Also may be used for metaphorical senses of chicken (e.g., “coward”).
See also 🐣 Hatching Chick, 🐤 Baby Chick, and 🐥 Front-Facing Baby Chick.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Google’s design features a full chicken, Twitter’s chicken head is looking straight ahead. Microsoft’s chicken was previously yellow, Samsung’s facing forward; Facebook’s design once featured a full, brown bird.

Chicken was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman behind a computer screen, working in the field of technology.
See also: 👨‍💻 Male Technologist
The Woman Technologist emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 💻 Personal Computer emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Technologist was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Philippines, which may show as the letters PH on some platforms.
The Flag: Philippines emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Philippines was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a frown and closed, downcast eyes, as if aching with sorrow or pain. May convey a variety of unhappy emotions, including disappointment, grief, stress, regret, and remorse.
Similar to 😔 Pensive Face, but with a sadder, more hurt expression. Samsung’s design previously featured an expression closer to 😕 Confused Face.

Disappointed Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A beach showing sand, and an umbrella for protection from the sun.

Beach With Umbrella was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.
Means “moon” or “month” in Chinese.

Japanese “Monthly Amount” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6708”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for the United Kingdom of Great Britain, which may show as the letters GB on some platforms.
England, Scotland and Wales have their own emoji flags as part of Emoji 5.0.
The Flag: United Kingdom emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: United Kingdom was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Desert Island was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Tonga, which may show as the letters TO on some platforms.
The Flag: Tonga emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Tonga was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A rat, a large rodent with a long tail, known to frequent big cities. Depicted in gray in full profile on all fours facing left, with pink ears, feet, and tail.
May be use for various metaphorical senses of rat. Not to be confused with 🐁 Mouse, which has white hair.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.
Google’s design is noticeably more cartoon-styled, standing on its hind legs and facing forward with a buck tooth.

Rat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Isle of Man, which may show as the letters IM on some platforms.
The Flag: Isle of Man emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Isle of Man was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Quids in! A banded stack of pound banknotes, the paper currency of the United Kingdom (England, Wales, Northern Ireland, and Scotland). Color and detail vary across platforms, but widely depicted as purple £20 notes with the pound sign, £.
Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.K. 
Samsung's design displays £10 notes.

Pound Banknote was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Banknote With Pound Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for United Nations. May show as the letters UN. This two letter regional indicator pair is an exceptional reservation as part of ISO 3166.
The Flag: United Nations emoji is a sequence of the 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: United Nations was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Cuba, which may show as the letters CU on some platforms.
The Flag: Cuba emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Cuba was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A ram, a male sheep with large, spiraling horns. Generally depicted in full profile on all fours facing left with a thick, white fleece and light-brown horns.
Occasionally used to represent antelopes and related animals. Not to be confused with 🐑 Ewe, though their applications may overlap.
Often considered (in lieu of 🐐 Goat) one of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Also often used to represent ♈ Aries (the Ram) in the Western zodiac.
WhatsApp and Facebook’s designs resemble a bighorn sheep, as did Apple’s once did.

Ram was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A construction worker wearing a hard-hat (safety helmet). Has a high visibility vest or hammer in some variations.
Some platforms display a green cross on the helmet which is used in Japan as a safety reminder in construction zones. It is also commonly seen on the Met helmet in the game Mega Man.

Construction Worker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A police car, shown with an emergency light on the top.
This emoji is displayed from the front, as opposed to the police car emoji, which is shown from the side.

Oncoming Police Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 👮 Police Officer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Police Officer emoji is a sequence of the 👮 Police Officer and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Police Officer was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A pensive, remorseful face. Saddened by life. Quietly considering where things all went wrong. Depicted as a yellow face with sad, closed eyes, furrowed eyebrows, and a slight, flat mouth.
May convey a variety of sad emotions, including feeling disappointed, hurt, or lonely. Less intense than other sad emojis like 😭 Loudly Crying Face and more introspective.
Microsoft's design previously featured a more neutral, bored expression. Samsung’s design previously looked more guilty or worried. Not to be confused with 😌 Relieved Face, which has similarly shaped eyes but in a happier expression.

 Pensive Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes, a slight frown, and furrowed eyebrows, from which a single bead of sweat drips, as if from concern or anxiety. Also known as Disappointed but Relieved Face, suggesting the smiley is upset but is grateful things didn’t turn out worse.
Commonly conveys mild degrees of frustration and sadness. Not to be confused with 😢 Crying Face, 😪 Sleepy Face, or other emojis with tear or sweat droplets.

Sad but Relieved Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Disappointed but Relieved Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with eyes closed and mouth letting out three, cartoon-styled Zzz’s overhead to indicate it's sound asleep. The Zzz’s appear blue or purple across most platforms. May also represent boredom (slang, snooze).
Generally used instead of 😪 Sleepy Face to convey sleep or sleepiness.

Sleeping Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Luxembourg, which may show as the letters LU on some platforms
The Flag: Luxembourg emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Luxembourg was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Yemen, which may show as the letters YE on some platforms.
The Flag: Yemen emoji is a sequence of the 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Yemen was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A pair of paw prints, as left by a pet 🐈 cat or 🐕 dog. Generally depicted as two, staggered, dark-colored paw prints, each showing four toes and a pad.
Commonly used for various content concerning pet cats and dogs. Occasionally applied to other quadruped mammals. See also 👣 Footprints.
Google and Twitter’s prints are red and Microsoft’s orange, as if a pet walked through paint. Apple and Facebook’s prints were previously red, Google’s blue, and Microsoft’s gray. Facebook's design originally displayed human footprints.


Paw Prints was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🙇 Person Bowing Deeply emoji.
The Woman Bowing emoji is a sequence of the 🙇 Person Bowing Deeply and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Bowing was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for a file on a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left.
Commonly used for various content concerning filing, organization, and work, especially at an office.
Apple’s folder is gray, Twitter’s is blue. Google’s design features multiple tabs, Microsoft’s a blue tab.
Nearly identical in appearance and use to 📂 Open File Folder, which is slightly open.

File Folder was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Guadeloupe, which may show as the letters GP on some platforms.
