The latest versions of iOS and OS X use the local unofficial flag, based on the coat of arms of Guadeloupe’s capital Basse-Terre. This is used instead of the Flag For France, which is the official flag of Guadeloupe.
The Flag: Guadeloupe emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.


Flag: Guadeloupe was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A fluffy, white cloud, as a cumulus. May be used as a weather icon to represent a cloudy or overcast day.
Google’s cloud is bluish, Twitter’s design features two clouds.

Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A Mexican or Tex-Mex taco on a hard or soft corn tortilla, filled with such ingredients as beef, lettuce, tomato, cheese, and onion. Apple’s design resembles a carne asada taco, with cilantro and white onion.

Taco was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A rosette, a stylized, flower-shaped decoration often presented as an award with a ribbon or (military) medal. Appears as a motif in ancient culptures. Generally depicted as a circular, yellow-and-orange flower.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such ideas as love, happiness, and beauty. Also used as a yellow accent color.
Not to be confused with 🌼 Blossom, though their applications may overlap.
WhatsApp's rosette is orange, white, and purple; Twitter's is purple and blue. Samsung's was previously pink.

Rosette was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A dark-colored, hardcover notebook, as used to write or take notes in school. Commonly used for various content concerning writing and schooling.
Several platforms, including Apple, feature a cover with black-and-white marbling, evoking a classic composition book used in the U.S. Apple's design displays Notes on its cover. Google, Microsoft, and Samsung’s covers were previously yellow or brown.

Notebook was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Foggy weather displayed as fog covering a bridge or cityscape, depending on the platform. For platforms that show a bridge, the red Golden Gate Bridge is generally displayed.

Foggy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A traditional Japanese robe that can be worn by women or men.

Kimono was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Colombia, which may show as the letters CO on some platforms.
The Flag: Colombia emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Colombia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol showing the capital letters A, B, C and D. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle capital letter input.

Input Latin Uppercase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Input Symbol for Latin Capital Letters”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An adult with no gender specified. This may be used as a gender-inclusive alternative to the man or woman emoji.

Person was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Adult”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Four emoji is a sequence of the 4 Digit Four and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Four was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An infinity emoji, displayed as the symbol for infinity enclosed within a circle or square.

Infinity was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
under the name “Permanent Paper Sign”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A larger version of the small orange diamond emoji.

Large Orange Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A classic Christmas tree, an evergreen tree decorated with lights and ornaments to celebrate Christmas.  Depicted with round, variously colored ornaments and topped with a yellow star.
Used for various content concerning the Christmas holiday and season as well as for wintertime more generally.
Not to be confused with 🌲 Evergreen Tree, though their applications may overlap.
Google and Samsung's trees were previously adorned with tinsel, Microsoft's previously lacked ornaments.

 Christmas Tree was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A lizard, a scaly reptile with a long tail. Depicted as a light-green lizard on all fours from above, generally looking left with large eyes, a lightly textured or colored back, and toes outspread, as a gecko.
May be used for a variety of wild and pet lizards.
Google’s lizard was previously brown.

Lizard was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A cartoon-styled representation of a collision. Depicted as a star-like, orange-and-yellow fiery burst, generally with one point extending to the bottom right, as if from the source of the collision.
May be used to represent various types of bangs, explosions, or crashes. Like 🔥 Fire and 💯 Hundred Points, commonly used to represent something is excellent or exciting in some way.
Apple implements a version of 💥 Collision in its 🧨 Firecracker and 📸 Camera With Flash.

Collision was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Collision Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple open eyes showing clenched teeth. May represent a range of negative or tense emotions, especially nervousness, embarrassment, or awkwardness (e.g., Eek!).
Resembled 😁 Beaming Face With Smiling Eyes on Apple iOS prior to 2017. Apple’s design for 🥶 Cold Face features the same mouth. Samsung's design previously featured more puckered-looking lips. 
On Snapchat, this emoji next to a contact denotes that you send the most snaps to the same person that they do., i.e., you share a #1 Best Friend.


Grimacing Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Megaphone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Cheering Megaphone”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A hedgehog, a small, spiny mammal sometimes kept as a pat. Generally depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a round, brown body covered with spines and a light-brown face and underside.
Sometimes used to represent a porcupine or echidna.
Google and Twitter’s designs show a hedgehog facing forward. Apple and WhatsApp’s design suggest a slight smile. Facebook’s design previously featured a hedgehog on its back, rolled up in a ball.

Hedgehog was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An icon of a outlined sun, used when decreasing the brightness of a screen. Appears smaller than the High Brightness Symbol.

Dim Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Low Brightness Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Equatorial Guinea, which may show as the letters GQ on some platforms.
The Flag: Equatorial Guinea emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇶 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Q emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Equatorial Guinea was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A string of beads, as used in prayer or meditation in many religious traditions. Generally depicted as red, wooden beads with a gold, decorative center bead and tassel.
Commonly used to represent various religious sentiments, jewelry, and magic.
Samsung previously featured a Latin cross, suggesting a Christian rosary, though now joins other vendor designs in resembling an Islamic misbaha or Buddhist mala.

Prayer Beads was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A man wearing a suit, hovering above the ground with a shadow displayed beneath him. Generally shown wearing a fedora or similar style of hat.
This character was originally introduced into the Webdings font as an “exclamation mark in the style of the rude boy logo found on records by The Specials". The levitating man is known as Walt Jabsco.
Support for skin tone modification of this emoji was added in 2016.


Man in Suit Levitating was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Man in Business Suit Levitating”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A large, open umbrella, as provides shade at a beach or patio. Generally depicted as a striped umbrella inserted into a patch of sand and tilted to the right.
Commonly used for various content concerning the beach, summer vacations (holidays), sunny weather, and relaxing outdoors.
The color of the stripes varies across platforms; Apple (no sand) and Samsung’s are red and yellow, Twitter and Facebook’s red and white, Google’s blue and white, and WhatsApp’s rainbow-colored.
Not to be confused with other umbrella-related emoji, such as 🏖️ Beach With Umbrella, though their applications may overlap.


Umbrella on Ground was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth and tongue on some platforms. Often conveys general happiness and good-natured amusement.
Similar to 😀 Grinning Face and 😃 Grinning Face With Big Eyes, but with warmer, less excited eyes.
This emoji has a cat variant, 😸 Grinning Cat Face With Smiling Eyes.

Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smiling Face With Open Mouth and Smiling Eyes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A thin, artist's paintbrush, as used to paint a picture. Often depicted with reddish paint on its pointed bristles. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left.
Commonly used for various content concerning the art of painting or fine art more generally. Often paired with 🎨 Artist Palette.

Paintbrush was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Lower Left Paintbrush”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person swinging a golf club, attempting to hit a golf ball toward the flag on the green.

Person Golfing was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Golfer”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A motorized speedboat used for recreation on lakes, or other bodies of water.

Speedboat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Translates as meaning complimentary, or free of charge. For example, a drink that is given "on the house" to a regular customer.

Japanese “Service Charge” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared Katakana Sa”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A tongue, sticking out. May be used as a childish sign of defiance.

Tongue was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Man, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Girl was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two mothers, and two sons.
The Family: Woman, Woman, Boy, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👩 Woman, 👦 Boy and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Woman, Boy, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A paper tray with an up arrow on top, as a symbol for an email outbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden tray with a red arrow.
May be used for various digital activity, including uploading, messaging, emailing, ordering, and sharing.
Google’s design features a blue arrow and contains paper, as does Facebook’s. Samsung’s arrow was previously green.
Compare 📥 Inbox Tray.

Outbox Tray was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A closed, hardcover notebook, as used for journaling or sketching. Appearance varies across platforms, with most designs featuring relatively plain covers. Commonly used for content concerning writing and schooling.
Apple's cover is tan and labelled Notes, Google’s is gray and features different-colored tabs, and Samsung's displays the easter egg initials SJST. Facebook’s design is most decorative, pink with a flower pattern.

Notebook With Decorative Cover was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: St. Lucia emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: St. Lucia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An analog, handheld timepiece used to measure elapsed time, as for athletic sprints. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted with two or more control buttons on its top.
Used for various content concerning time. Not to be confused with ⏰ Alarm Clock or other clock emojis.

Stopwatch was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A white uniform used in marital arts such as judo or karate. Held together using a material belt. Known as keikogi in Japanese.

Martial Arts Uniform was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for England, a country in the United Kingdom. May show as the letters gbeng.
The Flag: England emoji is a sequence of the 🏴 Waving Black Flag, 󠁧 Tag Latin Small Letter G, 󠁢 Tag Latin Small Letter B, 󠁥 Tag Latin Small Letter E, 󠁮 Tag Latin Small Letter N, 󠁧 Tag Latin Small Letter G and 󠁿 Cancel Tag emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: England was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: Turks & Caicos Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Turks & Caicos Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A flower that has blossomed. Depicted as a flower with white or yellow petals, as a daisy, with a golden center.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to convey such ideas as love, appreciation, and happiness. Also used as a yellow or white accent color.
Not to be confused with 🌻 Sunflower or 🌸 Cherry Blossom, though their applications may overlap.
Google's flower was once pink. Microsoft's was previously yellow, Samsung's white.

Blossom was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Djibouti, which may show as the letters DJ on some platforms.
The Flag: Djibouti emoji is a sequence of the 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D and 🇯 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter J emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Djibouti was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Biohazard was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Biohazard Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A pot, as a casserole dish, filled with a warm and hearty beef or vegetable stew on most platforms. Samsung’s design resembles a bowl of ramen or other noodle dish, with chopsticks. Generally used for eating and cooking (“a meal”), and commonly associated with soup or Japanese nabe.

Pot of Food was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A white piece of paper, curled up at the bottom to the left or right, with text printed on it, as a business letter. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.
Most platforms indicate text with dark lines. Apple’s design features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie with text from its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:
Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They're not fond of rules. And they have no respect for the status quo. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can't do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward…
Samsung’s design is addressed Dear Samsung. Early designs from au by KDDI resemble 📄 Page Facing Up, suggesting this emoji may have been originally intended to represent documents on a computer.
Not to be confused with 📄 Page Facing Up or other emojis featuring sheets of paper.

Page With Curl was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A water tap with a red stroke through it, indicating that water is not safe for drinking (non-potable).
May be used at a camp site or other area that has water suitable for cleaning or other non-drinking purposes.

Non-Potable Water was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Non-Potable Water Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 💁 Information Desk Person emoji.
The Man Tipping Hand emoji is a sequence of the 💁 Information Desk Person and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Tipping Hand was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A face blowing the wind, as a personification of nature (e.g., Mother Nature, the North Wind) who creates the wind by blowing air from its mouth. Depicted as a gray, profile of a human face, generally with a feminine appearance, blowing swirls from her mouth to the right.
May be used to represent windy weather. Occasionally used to represent clouds, fog, smoke, and smoking. Not to be confused with Dashing Away, though their applications may overlap.
Microsoft’s design is blue, as is Facebook’s, whose design most clearly suggests a woman’s face. WhatsApp’s design depicts a cloud with a face, as Samsung’s previously did.

Wind Face was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Wind Blowing Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A pair of skis which are shown on some platforms alongside ski poles and/or ski boots. The color and design of the skis varies by platform, with some versions also showing the skis moving at speed.
Distinct from the skier emoji which features a person skiing.

Skis was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Ski and Ski Boot”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A golden-yellow pot of honey, as made by bees and desired by bears. Shown with the sweet substance oozing down its sides, often with a honey dipper inside the small vessel. 
May be used figuratively, as the term of endearment “honey.”

Honey Pot was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A cup of a steaming-hot beverage, usually taken as coffee or tea. Sometimes shown on a saucer. Samsung features a foamy-white tulip latte art design.
May be paired with the Frog Face to represent the snarky But That's None of My Business meme. 

Hot Beverage was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Sweden, which may show as the letters SE on some platforms.
The Flag: Sweden emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Sweden was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An arm flexing to show its biceps muscle. Represents strength, or working out.

Flexed Biceps was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A ring with displaying a gem stone of some kind on the top, most likely a diamond. This piece of jewellery is often associated with a proposal and subsequent engagement to be married.

Ring was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An eject symbol, displayed as an upward-pointing triangle above a horiztonal bar. May be used as a physical button or an icon in a user interface. Represents the action of ejecting physical media such as a floppy disk, videocasette or DVD on a computer or media player.

Eject Button was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
under the name “Eject Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A railway (railroad) car (carriage) that is generally pulled along a railway line by a locomotive. Shown with a pantograph above the carriage on many platforms which makes it look more like a tram car.
Google’s artwork previously looked like a bus and Microsoft's older versions appeared similar to a minecart.

Railway Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Gibraltar, which may show as the letters GI on some platforms.
The Flag: Gibraltar emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Gibraltar was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two fathers, and one daughter.
The Family: Man, Man, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👨 Man and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Man, Girl was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A sweet potato depicted with textured purple, orange, or brown skin and sliced in half to show its golden-brown flesh. Sometimes called a yam, though they are unrelated. Not to be confused with the Potato.
Commonly roasted as a snack in East Asia during winter, much as squash and pumpkin are popular in the United States during fall/autumn. Used as an offering to the full moon in Japan during the Moon Viewing harvest festival.

Roasted Sweet Potato was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Cambodia, which may show as the letters KH on some platforms.
The Flag: Cambodia emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Cambodia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Eight emoji is a sequence of the 8 Digit Eight and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Eight was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An older adult with no gender specified. This may be used as a gender-inclusive alternative to the older man or older woman emoji.

Older Person was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Older Adult”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Cook emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🍳 Cooking emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Cook was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A seedling, or a young plant, as a newly sprouted tree. Depicted as a tiny, light-green plant with a short stem and two leaves. Often shown freshly sprung from a small mound of brown earth.
May be used for various content concerning plant life. May also be used as a symbol of spring or representation of various types of new growth.
Not to be confused with 🌿 Herb, though their applications may overlap.
Facebook’s seedling previously had three leaves.

Seedling was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The oval ball used in the game of American football, known as gridiron in some countries.

American Football was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An ant, a small, industrious insect that lives in a colony. Depicted as a black or red ant in full profile on its six legs facing left, with a prominent abdomen and antennae.
May be used to represent various insects or other bugs.
Microsoft and Facebook’s ants are red. Google’s ant was previously blue, Facebook’s black.

Ant was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman in Steamy Room emoji is a sequence of the 🧖 Person in Steamy Room and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman in Steamy Room was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Getting Massage emoji is a sequence of the 💆 Face Massage and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Getting Massage was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😄 Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Grinning Cat With Smiling Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Grinning Cat Face With Smiling Eyes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Leaves, as a have changed color and fallen from a tree in fall/autumn. Depicted as two or three golden-brown, almond-shaped leaves of various sizes, with stems up, as if falling down.
Commonly used to represent the season of fall/autumn, trees, and nature more generally.
Not to be confused with 🍃 Leaf Fluttering in Wind, though their applications may overlap.
Apple’s design previously featured two leaves. Google, Microsoft, Samsung, and Facebook all once featured a single leaf.

Fallen Leaf was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Guyana, which may show as the letters GY on some platforms.
The Flag: Guyana emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Guyana was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man behind a computer screen, working in the field of technology.
See also: 👩‍💻 Female Technologist
The Man Technologist emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 💻 Personal Computer emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Technologist was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A spool of thread, as used for sewing. Thread color varies across platforms, though often depicted in red or blue and on a wooden spool. Sometimes shown with an end unraveling.
Commonly used for various content concerning sewing, knitting, arts and crafts, clothing and fashion, and metaphorical threads (e.g., a discussion thread online).
WhatsApp’s design includes a needle.

Thread was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Spool of Thread”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Black Square Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and puckered lips giving a kiss. Commonly conveys sentiments of love and affection.
Like 😙 Kissing Face With Smiling Eyes, this emoji is sometimes taken to represent whistling, especially when paired with a musical note. May convey such feelings as surprise, admiration, contempt, or feigned innocence, as a person casually whistling after wrongdoing saying, Nothing to look at here.
Similar to 😙 Kissing Face With Smiling Eyes and 😚 Kissing Face With Closed Eyes but with less intimate eyes.


Kissing Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🚴 Bicyclist emoji.
The Woman Biking emoji is a sequence of the 🚴 Bicyclist and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Biking was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The oval-shaped ball used in the game of rugby. Varies slightly in shape in the two main versions of the game: rugby union and rugby league.
The appearance of this emoji varies, with a brown leather appearance in Apple and Google’s imagery, but a more popular white-with-highlight color in Twitter’s design.

Rugby Football was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic movie camera. Depicted as a black camera with two mounted reels of film, viewfinder, and lens pointed left or right.
Commonly used for various content concerning movies, film, and video as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit. May also be used in relation to the 2017 Emoji Movie.
Facebook’s design previously resembled a video camera mounted on a tripod.
Not to be confused with 📽️ Film Projector.
 

Movie Camera was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A vampire shown wearing a dark cape, and with pointed fangs. This emoji supports skin tones, and variations that are female or male.

Vampire was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A circular symbol, commonly used as a representation of peace. Alternatives include the Victory Hand, or the Dove of Peace.

Peace Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Man Cartwheeling emoji is a sequence of the 🤸 Person Doing Cartwheel and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Cartwheeling was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person with arms crossed forming an ‘X’ to indicate ‘no’ or ‘no good’. This motion is used on the TV game show Deal or No Deal to indicate ‘No Deal’. Intended to be gender-neutral but shown as a woman on most platforms.

Person Gesturing No was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face With No Good Gesture”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Mauritius, which may show as the letters MU on some platforms.
The Flag: Mauritius emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Mauritius was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A pink love heart with stars around it, making it look like it is sparkling or shimmering.

Sparkling Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A sled, otherwise known as a toboggan or sledge.

Sled was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A rhinoceros, a large mammal with one or two massive horns on its nose. Generally shown in light gray with two horns, depicted in full profile on all fours or as a rhinoceros head looking left.
Resembles the white or black rhinoceros.
Apple, Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs feature the full animal; Google, Samsung, and Twitter’s designs feature only a rhinoceros head. Facebook’s design previously featured only a rhinoceros head.

Rhinoceros was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Micronesia, which may show as the letters FM on some platforms.
The Flag: Micronesia emoji is a sequence of the 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Micronesia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A speaker cone displayed with one sound wave, generally used as an icon to indicate the decreasing of volume on a phone or computer.
Previously displayed with two sound waves on Android, instead of one.

Speaker Medium Volume was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Speaker With One Sound Wave”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A two-piece bikini, worn at the beach, pool, or on vacation at a tropical destination.
Shown in a variety of colors and patterns across different platforms.

Bikini was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Thailand, which may show as the letters TH on some platforms.
The Flag: Thailand emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Thailand was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A station, presumed to be a train station. Displays a train alongside a platform, where passengers can board.

Station was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Peru, which may show as the letters PE on some platforms.
The Flag: Peru emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Peru was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for British Virgin Islands, which may show as the letters VG on some platforms.
The Flag: British Virgin Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: British Virgin Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A pointed knife with a steel blade, as used for thrusting in close combat. Generally depicted as double-edged with a brown or black, cross-shaped hilt and positioned at 45° angle, often with its tip at the lower left.
May represent knives and other bladed weapons (cf. ⚔️ Crossed Swords) as well as various senses of cutting and stabbing. Often applied to medieval or fantasy content.
Microsoft’s design features a golden handle. Google’s design, featuring an icy-blue blade and sparkles, suggests a dagger elves may wield in fantasy.
May be paired with (or defended by) 🛡️ Shield. Not to be confused with 🔪 Kitchen Knife.


Dagger was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Dagger Knife”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A beer, as a golden-colored lager, in a frosty mug. Depicted with a frothy head spilling over the brim. Clinking Beer Mugs is a variation that displays two such beer mugs.

Beer Mug was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. Less common than the vertical traffic light.
Similar in appearance to the traffic light controls in the upper-left of every OS X windows.

Horizontal Traffic Light was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A key, as opens a door or lock. Depicted at a 45° angle as a gold, bronze, or copper key with a round head and notched blade. Commonly used for figurative senses of key, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial").
DJ Khaled uses the emoji to indicate his Snapchat stories are official (verified). Apple’s design previously resembled a gold 🗝️ Old Key, which emoji has similar applications.
May also represent digital keys in public-key technology. This may explain why the emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Key was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Brain was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two women holding hands, most likely due to being in a relationship.

Women Holding Hands was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Two Women Holding Hands”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A red envelope, as gifted with money on Chinese New Year or on other joyous occasions, such as weddings, in Chinese and some other Asian cultures around the world.
Depicted as a red, vertical envelope with a gold design, typically featuring the Chinese character 福 (fú, “good fortune, luck, happiness"). Google’s design features the character upside down, indicating “good luck arrives.”
Often used to celebrate and wish good fortune on Chinese New Year (Lunar New Year, Spring Festival). Also used to represent gifts, celebration, Chinese culture, and the color red more generally.
 
Red Envelope was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
under the name “Red Gift Envelope”
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A graph showing a red or green trend line increasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of increase, from numerical data to being metaphorically on the rise. May also represent trending content as well as facts, figures, and charts more generally.

Chart Increasing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Chart With Upwards Trend”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the side, as opposed to the oncoming taxi emoji.

Taxi was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A prawn or shrimp breaded and deep-fried golden-brown. Known as ebi furai in Japan but commonly called shrimp tempura and served in a bento box. Not to be confused with the Shrimp.

Fried Shrimp was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A blue heart emoji.

Blue Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🚶 Pedestrian emoji.
The Woman Walking emoji is a sequence of the 🚶 Pedestrian and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Walking was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The word free, shown enclosed in a square.

Free Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared Free”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A long, green cucumber with bumpy skin. Resembles its derived product, a pickle or gherkin, on many platforms, except on Apple and WhatsApp, which depict it with light-green, seed-y slices.

Cucumber was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with closed eyes wearing a white surgical mask, as used by health workers in hospitals. Also worn in East Asian cultures to avoid sickness or spreading airborne diseases.
Windows 8.1 depicted a ridged dust mask, as used by construction workers, changed to a medical mask in Windows 10.

Face With Medical Mask was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A gender-unspecified person taking a soothing bath in a white tub with a shower head. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and bathrooms more generally. May also represent relaxation and self-care.
The appearance of the person, depicted in default yellow, varies. Apple's person is wearing a green shower cap, WhatsApp's a green washcloth. Google’s person appears to be playing in a bubble bath, with soapsuds atop their ahead. Other major vendors show the head of the bather with short, brown or blonde hair. Skin tone modifiers are available on supported platforms.
Vendors implement the same or a similar tub and shower head as for their 🛁 Bathtub, but with a person taking/having a bath.


Person Taking Bath was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Bath”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two fathers, one daughter, and one son.
The Family: Man, Man, Girl, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👨 Man, 👧 Girl and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Man, Girl, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Headphones, used to listen to music or other forms audio, such as podcasts. Most platforms display this emoji with large over-ear headphones in shades of black, blue, and gray.
Apple previously displayed this emoji as iconic iPod/iPhone white earbuds.

Headphone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Comoros, which may show as the letters KM on some platforms.

🇰🇲 Comoran Flag Emoji

The Flag: Comoros emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Comoros was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A parrot, a brightly colored tropical bird known for its ability to mimic speech. Depicted in full profile facing left standing on its legs. Variously resembles a green lovebird (with red- and-yellow-tipped wings) or a scarlet macaw (with blue-and-yellow-striped wings).
May be used to represent various pet parrots and other pet birds.
Facebook’s parrot is orange with blue-tipped wings. Google's parrot is perched on a branch.

Parrot was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A head of a rich green leaf vegetable, usually shown with white stalks. May be used to represent a variety of greens, including romaine lettuce, chard, and Chinese cabbage like bok choy, as commonly cooked in Asian cuisines. 

Leafy Green was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🙇 Person Bowing Deeply emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Bowing emoji is a sequence of the 🙇 Person Bowing Deeply and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Bowing was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A dish antenna, as used to send or receive information to or from a communication satellite—or 👽 Extraterrestrial Life. Generally depicted as a mounted, metal dish with its antenna positioned at 45° to the upper right.
Commonly used to represent satellite television, radio, and internet, as well as broadcasting, streaming, cellular, and wireless services or technologies. May also represent various concepts of signals and transmission.
Several platforms, including Samsung and Twitter, feature curved, radiating lines, as if transmitting data. Google’s design is depicted in blue.

Satellite Antenna was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person (cyclist) who rides a mountain bike: a type of off-road bicycle. Intended to be gender-neutral.

Person Mountain Biking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Mountain Bicyclist”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes and a large, round mouth, slack with surprise or shock, as if saying Wow! or Oh my! May convey such feelings as awe or disbelief, often milder or more ironic in tone than 😱 Face Screaming in Fear.

Face With Open Mouth was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Strips of crispy, fatty, reddish-brown bacon, as fried for breakfast. Depicted as a pair on most platforms.

Bacon was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A pink or red ribbon, as tied into a bow on a gift or woman's hat.
Often used to indicate something is pretty, cute, or special, including on holidays. Also used of various content concerning baby girls and for its pink or red color more generally.
Google’s ribbon was previously orange, Facebook’s blue.

Ribbon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled faced of a fox, the cunning canine, looking straight ahead. Depicted as an orange fox  face with a black nose, pointed ears, and shaggy, white cheeks.
Often used with an affectionate or playful tone (e.g., slang, foxy). Does not have a full-bodied fox emoji counterpart.
Available as an Apple Animoji.

Fox was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Fox Face”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A green bottle of champagne or sparkling wine with label, its cork popping to shoot out its bubbly contents. Used for a range of celebratory occasions, such as New Year's Eve, birthdays, weddings, or other life accomplishments. 

Bottle With Popping Cork was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Poland, which may show as the letters PL on some platforms.
The Flag: Poland emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Poland was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A white piece of paper, its top right corner curled or dog-eared, with text printed on it, as a business letter or icon for a document on a computer. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.
Most platforms indicate text with dark lines. Apple’s design features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie and signed Take care from John Appleseed with the text of its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:
Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.
Early designs from au by KDDI show a slanted document, suggesting this emoji may have been originally intended to represent a digital document being sent electronically.
Not to be confused with 📃 Page With Curl or other emojis featuring sheets of paper.

Page Facing Up was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A leopard, a large cat with a yellowish-brown coat and black-and-gold spots. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long tail and its distinctive pattern.
Sometimes used to represent jaguars, panthers, cheetahs, and related cats. May also be used to indicate leopard prints in fashion. Not to be confused with 🐅 Tiger.
Google’s design is noticeably more cartoon-styled. Microsoft’s design was previously solid yellowish-brown in color, resembling a cougar or mountain lion.

Leopard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Minus Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Heavy Minus Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A red box for holding and transporting tools, such as a hammer and wrench. Generally depicted as latched shut with silver hardware and a black handle.
Commonly used for literal or metaphorical tools, toolkits, and building.
Google’s design is shown open with two wrenches and a pair of pliers; WhatsApp includes a hammer in front.

Toolbox was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A globe, showing the continents of Europe and Africa in green against blue ocean.
May be used to represent various content concerning the European, African, and Atlantic regions. May also be used to represent Earth and international affairs more generally.
See also 🌎 Globe Showing Americas and 🌏 Globe Showing Asia-Australia.

Globe Showing Europe-Africa was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Earth Globe Europe-Africa”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The sour, yellow-colored citrus fruit of the lemon, usually with a stem and green leaf or leaves.
Spiked in use thanks to Beyoncé’s 2016 album, Lemonade.

Lemon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A heart emoji with an arrow through the center, like the arrow that cupid shoots for love.

Heart With Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Vampire emoji is a sequence of the 🧛 Vampire and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Vampire was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person in a sauna, holding a ladle for pouring water on hot stones, which creates the steamy environment.
Popular in Finland, where people sauna in the nude.

Person in Steamy Room was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A hippopotamus, a squat water mammal with huge jaws. Generally depicted in pinkish gray in full profile on all fours facing left.
Google’s design features a purple, cartoon-styled hippopotamus face. Facebook’s hippopotamus is opening massive jaws, revealing tusks.

Hippopotamus was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for New Caledonia, which may show as the letters NC on some platforms.
The Flag: New Caledonia emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: New Caledonia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A water fountain, found in a park or other public space. Used for decorative purposes. A variety of styles of fountain are shown across different platforms.

Fountain was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Pilot emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and ✈ Airplane emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Pilot was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
An egg with yolk frying in a skillet, as prepared sunny-side up. Though associated with breakfast, the emoji represents the general action of cooking and related concepts.

Cooking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A shamrock, a clover-like plant. Depicted as a bright green sprig with three, heart-shaped leaves.
An emblem of Ireland and symbol of St. Patrick, said to use the shamrock to explain the Christian concept of the Holy Trinity. Commonly used on St. Patrick’s Day and in association with Irish culture and heritage.
Not to be confused with 🍀 Four Leaf Clover, though their applications may overlap.

Shamrock was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Lebanon, which may show as the letters LB on some platforms.
The Flag: Lebanon emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Lebanon was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Cross Mark Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Negative Squared Cross Mark”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow pointing to the left, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a reply icon in an email application.

Right Arrow Curving Left was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Leftwards Arrow With Hook”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Myanmar, which may show as the letters MM on some platforms.
The Flag: Myanmar (Burma) emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Myanmar (Burma) was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A swirl of soft-serve ice cream atop a wafer-style cone, white or cream-colored, as vanilla, on most platforms. Facebook’s design suggests strawberry. May be used more generally for ice cream, frozen yogurt, and frozen treats.

Soft Ice Cream was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A star with eight points, that is commonly shown in orange, and for some reason, with only four points.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Eight-Pointed Star was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Eight Pointed Black Star”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Morocco, which may show as the letters MA on some platforms.
The Flag: Morocco emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Morocco was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person riding a bicycle for leisure, sport or transport. Intended to be gender-neutral.

Person Biking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Bicyclist”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a broad, open smile and scrunched, X-shaped eyes. Often conveys excitement or hearty laughter.
Similar to 😀 Grinning Face but with eyes that might say Squee! or Awesome! An emoji form of the >< or xD emoticons.

Grinning Squinting Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smiling Face With Open Mouth and Tightly-Closed Eyes”
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A small version of the large orange diamond emoji.

Small Orange Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Chad, which may show as the letters TD on some platforms.
The Flag: Chad emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Chad was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Czechia, which may show as the letters CZ on some platforms. This was formerly known as Czech Republic.
The Flag: Czechia emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Czechia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
A flag with six colors of the rainbow, generally including red, orange, yellow, green, blue and purple. Commonly used by the LGBT movement as a gay pride flag, or simply pride flag.
In February 2019 misinformation was spread about a so-called "anti-lgbt emoji" which can be created using a combining character to show a black and white glyph like 🚫 on top of the rainbow flag. This is possible with any emoji on supported platforms, in the same way keycaps are combining characters.
The Rainbow Flag emoji is a sequence of the 🏳 Waving White Flag and 🌈 Rainbow emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Rainbow Flag was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Dominican Republic, which may show as the letters DO on some platforms.
The Flag: Dominican Republic emoji is a sequence of the 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Dominican Republic was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon cat variant of 😚 Kissing Face With Closed Eyes. Depicted as yellow on major platforms.

Kissing Cat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Kissing Cat Face With Closed Eyes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The face of a unicorn, a mythical creature in the form of a white horse with a single, long horn on its forehead. Generally depicted as a white horse head facing left with a pink or purple mane and a yellow or rainbow-colored horn.
In addition to the mythical unicorn, may be used to convey whimsy, fantasy, uniqueness, specialness, peace, and love. Often used for various content related to the LGBTQ community, thanks in part to its rainbow colors on many platforms. Also often used in association with “unicorn” startups. Sometimes used as a rainbow or holographic accent color.
Vendors implement the emoji with the same or similar design as 🐴 Horse Face, but with colorful hair and a horn.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
WhatsApp’s unicorn is facing right. Google’s unicorn previously had a brown mane, Samsung’s a pink mane. Twitter’s unicorn was previously purple-colored with a blue mane.

Unicorn was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Unicorn Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A tennis racket (racquet) with a tennis ball. Only a ball is shown on Apple, LG, Twitter, Facebook, and Mozilla platforms.

Tennis was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Tennis Racquet and Ball”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A pickaxe, a tool with a curved spike for breaking up rocks in mining. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left.
May be used for various content concerning building, construction, digging, mining, or rock climbing. Not to be confused with 🔨 Hammer or Axe.

Pick was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A microscope, as used in science laboratories to magnify small objects, such as cells or insects. Depicted as a compound opitical microscope with an adjustable eyepiece, lens, arm, and slide stage mounted on a base. Generally shown as metal with the viewing apparatus facing left.
Commonly used for various content concerning science and research. May also be used for various senses of inspection (e.g., taking a closer took).
Google’s design is shown in red.

Microscope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An octopus, a sea animal with eight legs, known to change color and release ink. Generally depicted as a pink or orange octopus facing forward, with a large, round head, prominent eyes, and its tentacle-like arms raised at its sides. Platforms vary in the number of arms shown, ranging from four to the full eight, with several designs featuring suckers on them.
Not to be confused with 🦑 Squid, though their applications may overlap.
Twitter’s octopus is purple. Apple’s has a friendly, cartoon-styled appearance. Google and Samsung’s octopuses previously looked surprised, while Microsoft's suggested an 👾 Alien Monster.


Octopus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with open eyes and a skewed frown, as if scrunching its cheeks or chewing its lips. A look of feeling unsure. An Google’s design heightens its intended puzzlement by including contorted eyebrows.
While it can convey confusion, it is commonly used for moderate sadness, disappointment, and frustration, thanks to its frown.
Samsung previously included raised eyebrows, as did Microsoft along with a rotated S-shaped mouth, à la the :S emoticon.

Confused Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A boar, a hairy, wild pig with tusks. Generally depicted as the face of a brown boar, either facing left or looking straight ahead, with prominent tusks projecting from its lower jaw.
Microsoft, Twitter, and Facebook’s design feature a friendly, cartoon-styled face with a snout. WhatsApp’s design displays the animal in full, as Google, Microsoft, and Samsung previously did.
Not to be confused with 🐖 Pig or 🐷 Pig Face, though their applications may overlap.
Available as an Apple Animoji.

Boar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An owl, the hooting, large-eyed bird of the night. Depicted as a reddish-brown owl, as a great horned owl, facing forward, Shown with large, round, gold-rimmed eyes, feet curled on or as if on a branch, wings tucked in, and its distinctive, horn-like tufts of feathers.
May be used to represent wisdom. Popularly used in connection with the hip-hop artist Drake.
Apple and Microsoft’s owls are on a branch. Microsoft’s owl previously resembled a barn owl, Samsung’s was purple.

Owl was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A round, black, cartoon-styled hole, as a manhole or a hole (cup) in golf. May be used to represent various types of literal or figurative holes, e.g., black holes, rabbit holes.
