Hole was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Samoa, which may show as the letters WS on some platforms.
The Flag: Samoa emoji is a sequence of the 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Samoa was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The buttery-white snack of popcorn brimming in a classic red-and-white-striped carton, as enjoyed at a movie theater. 
May be used to express engagement (“edge of one’s seat”).

Popcorn was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A face with small, open eyes, open frown, raised eyebrows, and a pale blue forehead, as if experiencing a cold flash. Samsung’s design shows upper teeth and tongue.
While intended to represent fear (less intense than 😱 Face Screaming in Fear), it also conveys a wide variety of emotions, including feeling amazed, shocked, sad, upset, and cold. Bears the same expression as 😧 Anguished Face on most platforms.

Fearful Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Uruguay, which may show as the letters UY on some platforms.
The Flag: Uruguay emoji is a sequence of the 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Uruguay was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A video camera, as a camcorder used to film home videos in the 1980–90s. Generally depicted as a gray or black video camera with viewfinder, control buttons, and lens pointed left.
Commonly used for various content concerning film and video as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit.
Google’s design is blue and previously featured a flip screen. Samsung’s is fitted with a microphone.

Video Camera was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Question Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Black Question Mark Ornament”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A rice plant, as grown before harvesting and processing. Depicted as a sheaf of Asian rice with green leaves and yellow seed heads drooping over to the right or left.
May be consumed in the form of 🍚 Cooked Rice. May be used to represent a variety of cereal grains (e.g., wheat, corn, oats, sorghum) as well as crops, fields and harvests, and farming more generally.

Sheaf of Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Ear of Rice”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A satellite which orbits the earth, and is generally used for communications, weather, and GPS.

Satellite was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A stick-figure icon of a woman, generally used to indicate a female restroom. The male equivalent is the Mens Symbol emoji.

Women’s Room was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Womens Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An unlocked padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a non-secure connection or open access online. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle, as an open 🔒 Locked.
May be used to represent a lack of or concerns about privacy and security. May also be used for figurative senses of unlocking, e.g., achievement unlocked.
WhatsApp’s design is silver, its shackle turned to the right, as Samsung’s previously was.
This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS).

Unlocked was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Open Lock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A sunset-orange-colored tropical beverage in a stemmed glass, as a rum punch or mai tai. Served with a straw and fruit garnish. Many platforms include a cocktail umbrella, hence umbrella drink. Samsung previously featured an electric-blue concoction. See also Cocktail Glass.

Tropical Drink was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow, pointing up.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Up Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
under the name “Upwards Black Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A style of boot commonly worn on long walks or for hiking. Generally distinct from other footwear-related emojis by the considerable grip on the sole of the shoe.

Hiking Boot was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The cooked sausage of a hot dog in a sliced bun and drizzled with yellow mustard, as eaten at a baseball game. 

Hot Dog was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A whale, the massive marine mammal. Generally depicted as a light-blue whale in full profile facing left, with its tail curving down towards is huge mouth. Shown with a white, textured underside, as a humpback or blue whale.
Not to be confused with the more cartoon-styled 🐳 Spouting Whale, though their applications may overlap.
Apple and Microsoft’s whales have slightly open mouths, revealing baleen.

Whale was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol often used in relation to the religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism.

Om was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Om Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Denim jeans, worn by men or women. A popular form of casual trousers worn by the runner emoji in Apple's emoji artwork

Jeans was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with furrowed eyebrows wearing a monocle. Usually depicted with a small, intent frown and head slightly upturned, as if in careful inspection.
May show that someone is pondering, considering, or questioning something, sometimes with a sense of skeptical or ironic observation or encouraging a closer look at some content. May convey a sense of sophistication or smug intelligence, e.g., smarty-pants.

Face With Monocle was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Japanese sushi, generally depicted as two pieces of raw pinkish-orange fish, as tuna or salmon, on white rice (nigiri). Some platforms show the cylindrical maki, a piece of seafood, vegetables, and white rice wrapped in seaweed (nori).

Sushi was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A board which contains the scene name, number, and film. A person ‘claps’ the board shut at the top while saying “Action” or “Cut” to indicate the start and stop of a scene that is being filmed.
This is used to synchronise the audio of the clap with the visuals.

Clapper Board was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The colorful arc of a rainbow, as may appear after rain. Generally depicted as the left half of a full rainbow, showing six bands of color: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, and violet.
Commonly used to express gay pride. Also commonly used to convey various feelings of love and happiness. See also 🏳️‍🌈 Rainbow Flag.
WhatsApp’s design shows the right arc of rainbow disappearing into a cloud. Facebook’s rainbow is displayed on a blue sky, as Apple, Samsung, and Twitter’s previously were. Google and Microsoft previously displayed full rainbow arcs with clouds.


Rainbow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Senegal, which may show as the letters SN on some platforms.
The Flag: Senegal emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Senegal was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A spiral-bound, flip-style notepad or notebook of lined paper, as used for everyday note-taking. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing.
Most platforms depict a notepad opened to an empty, white page, sometimes shown curled at the bottom. Microsoft’s design is shown closed, with a yellow cover.

Spiral Notepad was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Spiral Note Pad”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person getting his or her face massaged.
Apple’s artwork for this character shows more of a head massage. Google and Microsoft display a more accurate face massage, with hands rubbing the cheeks and face.

Person Getting Massage was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face Massage”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Plus Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Heavy Plus Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person on a surfboard, riding on a wave in the ocean. Wears a wetsuit or board shorts in most versions.

Person Surfing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Surfer”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person downhill-skiiing. Displayed with poles and skis, generally wearing a mask.
Platforms vary in display of scarf, helmet, and color of clothing. No gendered options are provided for this emoji. Skin tones support is not recommended for this emoji, but this is supported by some platforms.

Skier was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A couch (sofa) with a floor lamp on the right, as in the living room of a house. Color and style of the couch and lamp vary widely by platform. Used for various content concerning furniture and housing as well as resting and lounging.

Couch and Lamp was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Sri Lanka, which may show as the letters LK on some platforms.
The Flag: Sri Lanka emoji is a sequence of the 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L and 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Sri Lanka was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Sagittarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents an Archer.

Sagittarius was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An urn, as used to hold the cremated ashes of the dead. Appearance varies, but generally depicted as a covered, bronze container with a rounded body and tapered foot.
May be used for various content concerning death and funerals. May also be used for other types of vessels, such as pots or vases.
Not to be confused with 🏺 Amphora.

Funeral Urn was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The letter M in a circle, commonly used in to identify a Metro (subway, underground train) station in a city area.

Circled M was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Circled Latin Capital Letter M”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Mexico, which may show as the letters MX on some platforms.
The Flag: Mexico emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇽 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter X emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Mexico was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A Japanese wind chime. Depicted as a glass bell with a strip of paper suspended from its clapper, often decorated with cherry blossom-like flowers.
Occasionally used for content concerning various senses of wind and chime. Thanks to its appearance, often used to represent jellyfish.

Wind Chime was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A blouse worn by women in a neat-casual setting.
Shown in pink on Apple devices, yellow on Android, and purple on Twitter.
Similar to the top worn by the Information Desk Person Emoji.

Woman’s Clothes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Womans Clothes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A suburban-looking house, with a tree, flower, or shrubs around it in the garden.

House With Garden was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Two flutes of champagne or sparkling wine being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). Samsung’s design suggests two glasses of white wine. Some platforms include stylized links to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Beer Mugs—and Bottle With Popping Cork for a refill.

Clinking Glasses was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🏃 Runner emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Running emoji is a sequence of the 🏃 Runner and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Running was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A bicycle, sometimes called a push bike, used for transport or sport.

Bicycle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Time’s up! A timer set to count down and sound an alarm after a designated amount of time, as used in the kitchen. Appearance varies by platform. Commonly used for various content concerning time, including countdowns and deadlines.
Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs resemble kitchen timers. Other designs may be confused with 🕰️ Mantelpiece Clock or other clock emojis.

Timer Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Vatican City, which may show as the letters VA on some platforms.
The Flag: Vatican City emoji is a sequence of the 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Vatican City was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Oman, which may show as the letters OM on some platforms.
The Flag: Oman emoji is a sequence of the 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Oman was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A test tube, as used to conduct chemical experiments in a laboratory. Depicted as a clear cylinder, open at one end and containing a green liquid. Positioned at a 45° angle.
May be used for various content concerning chemistry and science more generally. May also represent other liquids, such as potions or medicines, as well metaphorical laboratories and experiments.
Some platforms include volume markings or display the liquid as bubbling. WhatsApp’s design features a blue liquid.

Test Tube was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🚵 Mountain Bicyclist emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Mountain Biking emoji is a sequence of the 🚵 Mountain Bicyclist and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Mountain Biking was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with furrowed eyebrows looking upwards with thumb and index finger resting on its chin. Intended to show a person pondering or deep in thought. Often used to question or scorn something or someone, as if saying Hmm, I don't know about that. Tone varies, including earnest, playful, puzzled, skeptical, and mocking.
May be paired with 💭 Thought Balloon or 💡 Light Bulb to represent thinking, (having) ideas, and learning.
Joins 🤗 Hugging Face, 🤫 Shushing Face, and 🤭 Face With Hand Over Mouth as one of the few smileys featuring a hand.

Thinking Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A latin cross, otherwise known as a Christian cross. This cross symbol is often used as a symbol of Christianity. Similar in appearance to the Orthodox cross.

Latin Cross was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A flame, as produced when something is on fire. Depicted as a red, orange, and yellow flickering flame.
Commonly used for various metaphorical expressions related to fire, including the slang hot (“attractive”) and lit (“excellent”).
Snapchat displays 🔥 Fire next to two users who are on a snapstreak, or have been messaging for more than three consecutive days.

Fire was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A goat, a sturdy, hoofed animal raised for its meat and milk. Depicted as a light brown, white, or multicored goat in full profile on all fours facing left, a scraggly beard, upright tail, and brown or yellow horns curving back.
Frequently used as a visual shorthand for the slang expression GOAT, or the Great of All Time, often said of athletes.
Often considered one of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Also often used to represent ♑ Capricorn in the Western zodiac.
Apple, Google, and Samsung’s goats were previously white, as a Saanen goat. Facebook’s design previously featured only a goat face.

Goat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Two frosty mugs of beer with frothy heads being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). Several platforms include stylized lines to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Glasses.

Clinking Beer Mugs was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A checkbox showing a check mark inside the box. Not to be confused with the similarly named Ballot Box With Ballot emoji.
This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark.

Check Box With Check was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Ballot Box With Check”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The backside of a credit card, showing the magnetic strip and signature. Color and detail vary across platforms, but often shown as gold, silver, or blue. May be used for banking and other ID cards as well for various content concerning money, including payment. 
Some vendors feature easter eggs: Apple’s design features John Appleseed in the signature and a security code of 448, and Samsung’s, the initials KJH and 856 658. Facebook’s design features founder Mark Zuckerberg’s signature and a security code of 123.

Credit Card was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes and a crumpled mouth, as if quivering in frustration or holding back tears. May be used to represent being overcome with various emotions, including irritation, frustration, disgust, and sadness, as if to the point of defeat.  
Microsoft and Twitter’s designs feature eyebrows, Facebook’s a purple forehead.
Vendor designs have noticeably evolved over time. Apple and Google’s designs previously included eyebrows. Earlier versions from Google also displayed a more miserable expression, and Microsoft a more confused one.
Samsung’s design previously featured X’s for eyes, a flushed nose, and vertical lines over its forehead, shorthands in manga and anime for such feelings as anger and embarrassment.

Confounded Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A tall boot generally featuring a slight heel, shown in brown or red on most platforms.
Some platforms display this emoji with two boots, while most display a single boot.

Woman’s Boot was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Womans Boots”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person juggling between three and five colored balls. The person shown in this emoji generally has the appearance of a man, and wears a hat on most major platforms.

Person Juggling was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Juggling”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man of adult age, shown on some platforms with a moustache.

Man was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A speaker with a red line through it, indicating muted volume or silencing of audio.

Muted Speaker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Speaker With Cancellation Stroke”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A grape bunch, as cut from the vine and used to make wine. Depicted as red (purple-colored) grapes.

Grapes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Superhero emoji is a sequence of the 🦸 Superhero and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Superhero was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A heart symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the hearts suit. Generally shown in red, despite the name. Not to be confused with the black heart emoji.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Heart Suit was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Heart Suit”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A sandwich, as eaten at lunch, made with lettuce, tomato, and cheese on slices of white or wheat bread. Apple, Google, and WhatsApp add a deli meat that resembles ham.

Sandwich was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A building used for worship by people of any faith or religion. Examples include a church, mosque, or synagogue. A person is shown on their knees praying, in this symbol.
Multi-faith places of worship are commonly found at airports.

Place of Worship was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Gloves was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A view of city buildings as the last light disappears from the sky. An orange (or blue) glow lingers, before the stars of the night sky become visible.

Cityscape at Dusk was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Guinea-Bissau, which may show as the letters GW on some platforms.
The Flag: Guinea-Bissau emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Guinea-Bissau was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A violin emoji. Sometimes  used in the context of the world’s smallest violin.

Violin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Billed Cap was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A newspaper rolled up and bound, as for delivery to a house. Generally positioned at a 45° angle. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.
See also 📰 Newspaper.

Rolled-Up Newspaper was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
The front of a bus, showing the windscreen, as well as wing mirrors in some versions of this emoji.

Oncoming Bus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A white coat worn in a science laboratory.

Lab Coat was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Three-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Three-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with flat, closed eyes and mouth. May convey a sense of frustration or annoyance more intense than suggested by 😐 Neutral Face, as if taking a moment to collect itself.

Expressionless Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Six-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Six-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Panama, which may show as the letters PA on some platforms.
The Flag: Panama emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Panama was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a tiger looking straight ahead. Generally depicted in yellowish-orange with black stripes on its forehead and cheeks, a white muzzle, and neutral expression.
Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied 🐅 Tiger.
Available as an Apple Animoji.

Tiger Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A roll of paper, as toilet paper (toilet tissue). May also be a roll of kitchen/paper towels. Depicted at various angles, with a sheet unfurling.
Commonly used for toilet paper but may also be used for various content concerning toilets, going to the bathroom, bathrooms, cleaning, or paper more generally.

Roll of Paper was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A  sparkler: a form of hand-held firework often used at parties and celebrations. The sparkler is lit at one end, and held at the other. 
Most platforms display this with the lit end held down, as is the style for senko hanabi ("incense-stick fireworks") which is a traditional sparkler from from Japan.

Sparkler was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Firework Sparkler”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A pager, as worn on the waist to alert a person to a phone call or short text message. Popular in the 1980–90s before mobile phones, though still used by some medical and emergency personnel. Very occasionally used to represent alerts, digital communication, or nostalgia for old technology.
Depicted as a black device with operating buttons and a green screen displaying various (telephone) numbers across platforms, including:

📟 Apple: 555-3215
📟 Google: 8888
📟 Microsoft: [indecipherable]
📟 Samsung: 954-5684 (previously SUNMOON)
📟 WhatsApp: 867-5309 (an allusion to the 1980s hit song "867-5309/Jenny")
📟 Twitter: 40404
📟 Facebook: 543-4800 (previously 02 04 20 04, referring to the company's launch date)


Pager was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A thick (heavy) check mark displayed on some platforms in a handwritten style. Generally displayed in black on most platforms, except Android (blue), Windows (green) and Samsung (red).
This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark.

Check Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Heavy Check Mark”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Has the same grin and eyes as 😄 Grinning Face With Smiling Eyes but with a single, blue bead of sweat, usually over its left eye. Intended to depict nerves or discomfort but commonly used to express a close call, as if saying Whew! and wiping sweat from the forehead. 

Grinning Face With Sweat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smiling Face With Open Mouth and Cold Sweat”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Estonia, which may show as the letters EE on some platforms.
The Flag: Estonia emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Estonia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A police car, shown with an emergency light on the top.
This emoji is displayed from the side, as opposed to the oncoming police car emoji, which is shown from the front.

Police Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A computer printer, as at a home office. Generally depicted as a grayish device with a power button and paper loaded in its tray, sometimes printing out a document. May be used for various content concerning printing, including as a Print icon, as well as for office work and technology more generally.
Not to be confused with 📠 Fax Machine.

Printer was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A black or gray box with a label holder, containing card index dividers with multicolored tabs, as used to organize and store files. Apple and Facebook’s designs include a lid.
Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files, organization, and various types of data, information, and professional or academic work.
Microsoft’s design previously resembled a shoebox.

Card File Box was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Cancer astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Crab.

Cancer was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Sierra Leone, which may show as the letters SL on some platforms.
The Flag: Sierra Leone emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Sierra Leone was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A shoe worn by a man, to work, dinner, or another occasion that requires footwear. Unlike womens shoes, this shoe is likely to be comfortable.

Man’s Shoe was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Mans Shoe”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
The face of a horse, generally facing left. Depicted as a light or reddish-brown horse with a dark brown or black mane, and, on many platforms, a light-colored muzzle.
Not to be confused with the full-bodied 🐎 Horse or 🏇 Horse Racing, though their applications may overlap. Some vendors implement a similar design in 🦄 Unicorn Face and 🦓 Zebra.
WhatsApp’s horse is facing left, as Facebook’s previously was. Microsoft’s horse was previously looking straight ahead, as was Samsung’s, shown with a goofy, full-toothed grin. Softbank previously featured a full-bodied horse.

Horse Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag lowered. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email.
Indicates in the United States that no incoming mail (post) has been delivered. May also indicate that outgoing mail has been picked up.
Compare 📫 Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, 📭 Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📬 Open Mailbox With Raised Flag.


Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A Japanese sweet dumpling made from rice flour and served on a skewer. Depicted as a botchan dango, comprising a pink, white or light yellow, and green ball, as colored by red beans, egg, and green tea. Resembles the Oden and featured in the Moon Viewing Ceremony, used in the Japanese festival to celebrate the full moon. 

Dango was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Shows a map of the country of Japan, which is the only country to have its own emoji map. Other countries can be found on the various globe emojis, or the world map emoji.

Map of Japan was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Silhouette of Japan”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Japanese “Secret” Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Circled Ideograph Secret”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A wristwatch, as used for telling time. Appearance varies across platforms, but widely depicted as an analog timepiece with a white face and brown or black straps.
Used for various content concerning time, including watches as accessories. Apple's design is an Apple Watch, though previously featured a traditional watch before the product’s release.

Watch was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Nauru, which may show as the letters NR on some platforms.
The Flag: Nauru emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Nauru was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A castle, in a style that can be found in France and other parts of Europe.

Castle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “European Castle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A winter jacket, shown in a variety of colors and styles.

Coat was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Vs Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared Vs”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Nicaragua, which may show as the letters NI on some platforms.
The Flag: Nicaragua emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Nicaragua was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Pilot emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and ✈ Airplane emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Pilot was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Woman, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Boy was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A plump, red garden tomato topped with a leafy green stem. May resemble the red apple at small sizes.

Tomato was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a panda—a bear-like mammal known for eating bamboo—looking straight ahead. Depicted as a white panda face with black ears and black circles around its eyes.
Often used with an affectionate tone and in association with China, where the animal is found. Sometimes used to represent a red panda. Does not have a full-bodied panda emoji counterpart.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Google and Facebook’s pandas are shown smiling with an open mouth and tongue.

Panda was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Panda Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic magnifying glass, as used to view small objects, with its lens pointed right. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a black handle and a clear or blue, silver-framed lens titled to the upper right.
Associated with detectives and search or zoom icons on computers. Like 🔍 Magnifying Glass Titled Left, commonly used for various senses of searching, looking, inspecting, etc.

Magnifying Glass Tilted Right was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Right-Pointing Magnifying Glass”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Multiplication Sign was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Heavy Multiplication X”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a big grin, uplifted eyebrows, and smiling eyes, each shedding a tear from laughing so hard. Widely used to show something is funny or pleasing. 
Not to be confused with 😭 Loudly Crying Face or 🤣 Rolling on the Floor Laughing, which expresses more intense laughter.
One of the ten most popular emojis between 2014–2018 and was named the Oxford Dictionaries 2015 Word of the Year.
This emoji has a cat variant, 😹 Cat Face With Tears of Joy.


Face With Tears of Joy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A light aircraft which is shown with propellers on some platforms.

Small Airplane was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Man, Boy, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👦 Boy and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Boy, Boy was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes spewing bright-green vomit. May represent physical illness or disgust, more intensely so than 🤢 Nauseated Face.

Face Vomiting was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Face With Open Mouth Vomiting”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A high-heeled shoe, primarily worn by women. Generally found in a context which requires formal dress, such as social occasions, or some work places.
Displayed in red on most platforms, though the color may vary.

High-Heeled Shoe was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🚶 Pedestrian emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Walking emoji is a sequence of the 🚶 Pedestrian and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Walking was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A classic spider web (cobweb), as spun by a 🕷️ Spider to catch prey. Depicted as a white, symmetrical, wheel-shaped web, as an orb web, with six or eight equal sectors.
Commonly used during Halloween, to represent the superhero Spider-Man, or for a metaphorical web, net, or network. Not to be confused with ❄️ Snowflake.

Spider Web was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The face of a young infant (baby). Shows the face of a baby with a small amount of hair on most platforms, while some variations show a pacifier (dummy) in its mouth. Android previously displayed this emoji as a swaddled baby.
On Snapchat, the baby emoji signifies a new friend on the service.

Baby was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🏄 Surfer emoji.
The Woman Surfing emoji is a sequence of the 🏄 Surfer and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Surfing was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A globe, showing the continents of Asia and Australia in green against blue ocean.
May be used to represent various content concerning the Asian, Australian, and Pacific regions. May also be used to represent Earth and international affairs more generally.
See also 🌎 Globe Showing Americas and 🌍 Globe Showing Europe-Africa.

Globe Showing Asia-Australia was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Earth Globe Asia-Australia”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Ophiuchus is used by some as a 13th sign in the Zodiac. The symbol for ophiuchus appears a U shape with a wavy line through it.

Ophiuchus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
100 emoji: the number one-hundred, written in red, underlined twice for emphasis.
Originating from the number 100 written on a school exam or paper to indicate a perfect score of 100 out of 100.  Teachers in Japan may also use a stamp in addition to the 100 mark, to indicate that a student has performed very well.
This 100 emoji is commonly used as a shorthand for 100%, with the usage meaning “keep it real” or a similar sentiment. A 100 emoji can be used to express pride or general acceptance of an idea.
In Snapchat, the 100 emoji appearing next to a fire emoji indicates a 100 day Snapstreak.

Hundred Points was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Hundred Points Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🏄 Surfer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Surfing emoji is a sequence of the 🏄 Surfer and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Surfing was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Taiwan (officially Republic of China), which may show as the letters TW on some platforms.
This Taiwanese flag is hidden from the emoji keyboard on iOS devices when the region is set to China mainland or (as of iOS 13.1.2) Hong Kong or Macau.
Chinese-model iPhones will not display this emoji and will instead show a missing character tofu (☒) in place of the flag, as will iOS devices with region set to China mainland. Hong Kong and Macua only hide this emoji from the emoji keyboard.
The Flag: Taiwan emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Taiwan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two women displayed kissing, or gesturing a kiss toward each other. At small sizes this may be difficult to discern from two men kissing.
The Kiss: Woman, Woman emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, ❤ Heavy Black Heart, 💋 Kiss Mark and 👩 Woman emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Kiss: Woman, Woman was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A large cloud-like shape more commonly known as a thought bubble.
Used to represent thinking, or thoughts, and commonly used in comics to display the thoughts of a drawn character. May also be used to represent a dream, or daydream.

Thought Balloon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A cactus, a spiky plant that grows in very dry regions. Depicted as a light-green saguaro cactus with two side arms covered in spines.
May be used to represent various succulents, deserts, Southwestern culture, or the Wild West.
WhatsApp’s cactus is topped with three red flowers.

Cactus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man: White Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🦳 Emoji Component White Hair emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man: White Hair was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A man wearing a gua pi mao; a type of Chinese hat. Sometimes referred to as a skullcap.

Man With Skullcap was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Man With Gua Pi Mao”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Christmas Island, which may show as the letters CX on some platforms.
The Flag: Christmas Island emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇽 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter X emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Christmas Island was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with a father, mother, and one daughter.
The Family: Man, Woman, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, 👩 Woman and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Man, Woman, Girl was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Barbados, which may show as the letters BB on some platforms.
The Flag: Barbados emoji is a sequence of the 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B and 🇧 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter B emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Barbados was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
What a good doggo! A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a dog, looking straight ahead. Depicted as the face of a dog of various breeds, generally light-brown and white, with pointed or floppy ears and its tongue hanging out.
May be used with a more playful tone than the full-bodied 🐕 Dog, though their applications generally overlap. See also 🐩 Poodle.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Available as an Apple Animoji.
Many vendors implement the same or similar dog as their full-bodied 🐕 Dog, such as Google and Facebook, which feature a Shiba Inu. Apple, Microsoft, and WhatsApp’s dogs have a white face with brown, floppy ears and a brown patch over one eye.
Included in the earliest Japanese emoji sets from Softbank, Docomo, and au by KDDI.

Dog Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A sign used to indicate roadwork or construction. Generally shown as yellow and black diagonal stripes, and often used to physically block access to a road or area. May be used to imply a website or project in progress or under construction.

Construction was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Construction Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 💇 Haircut emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Woman Getting Haircut emoji is a sequence of the 💇 Haircut and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Getting Haircut was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Uzbekistan, which may show as the letters UZ on some platforms.
The Flag: Uzbekistan emoji is a sequence of the 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Uzbekistan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Germany, which may show as the letters DE on some platforms
The Flag: Germany emoji is a sequence of the 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Germany was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🏊 Swimmer emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Swimming emoji is a sequence of the 🏊 Swimmer and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Swimming was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A male rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope.
Variations exist for 🧗‍♀️ Woman Climbing and 🧗 Person Climbing.
The Man Climbing emoji is a sequence of the 🧗 Person Climbing and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Climbing was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A butterfly, a beautiful winged insect whose larva is a caterpillar. Depicted with its wings outspread, as a blue-and-black morpho butterfly or orange-and-black monarch butterfly.
May be used to represent a moth and ideas of beauty and happiness.
Samsung’s butterfly previously resembled a monarch.

Butterfly was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
The front page of a newspaper, as people once read the news before the internet. Commonly used for various content concerning news, media, and journalism as well as personal news.
Most platforms depict a nondescript masthead, images, and columns of text. Apple’s newspaper is called The Apple Times, featuring a logo based on its 🦅 Eagle and a picture of its 🌋 Volcano. Facebook’s is called Daily Feed, with a headline “El Capitan” and picture of that famous rock formation in Yosemite National Park. WhatsApp’s paper reads Daily News with a picture of a map.
See also 🗞️ Rolled-Up Newspaper.


Newspaper was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A series of three Zs making a Zzz. Represents sleeping, snoring, dreaming, or any sleep-related state. Can also be used in some contexts to represent something that is boring.

Zzz was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Sleeping Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A trophy given as an recognition of achievement, usually in sports. The trophy emoji is a gold cup, with a engraving on the bottom detailing the award.
In Snapchat, the trophy provides access to the Trophy Case for unlocking emoji achievements.

Trophy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 🙍 Person Frowning emoji.
The Man Frowning emoji is a sequence of the 🙍 Person Frowning and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Frowning was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Georgia, which may show as the letters GE on some platforms.
The Flag: Georgia emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Georgia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A plate of orange-brown curry with vegetables or meat, served with a mound of white rice. May represent kare-raisu, or Japanese curry, though commonly associated with India and other Asian cuisines.

Curry Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Curry and Rice”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A flatbread, like pita, stuffed with lettuce, tomato, and/or meat. Resembles a doner kebab, falafel, shawarma, or gyro sandwich, popular in the Middle East and the Mediterranean. Apple and WhatsApp add red onion and cucumber. Not to be confused with the Burrito.

Stuffed Flatbread was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Articulated Lorry was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A rabbit, a hoppy mammal with long ears. Depicted as a white, gray, or brown rabbit in full profile facing left with pink ears and a short tail, sitting on its long, hind legs or on all fours.
May be used in association with spring, Easter, magic, bunny ears, or various rabbit-based characters or expressions (e.g., going down the rabbit hole).
See also 🐰 Rabbit Face. One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac.
Apple’s rabbit has red eyes, WhatsApp’s whiskers. Microsoft’s rabbit was previously brown, Facebook’s white.

Rabbit was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A hotel building, displayed on most platforms as a building with many windows and a letter H on the front.
Can be easily confused with the Love Hotel, or Hospital emoji. Microsoft this emoji as a bed, when viewed using Windows.

Hotel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Turkmenistan, which may show as the letters TM on some platforms.
The Flag: Turkmenistan emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Turkmenistan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A hockey stick and ball, used in the sport of field hockey. Not to be confused with the ice hockey stick and puck.

Field Hockey was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
under the name “Field Hockey Stick and Ball”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Malta, which may show as the letters MT on some platforms.
The Flag: Malta emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Malta was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A digital versatile disc (DVD), a type of optical disc used to play movies before the rise of streaming technology. Generally depicted in gold, though Facebook’s is bluish gray, as a Blu-ray.
Commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, Blu-rays, and related film and music content, especially albums.
Google, Microsoft, Samsung, and Softbank’s designs were once labelled DVD, as to distinguish it from 💿 Optical Disk.
See also 💿 Optical Disc and 💽 Computer Disk.

 DVD was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes and a big grin, sticking out its tongue. Often conveys a sense of fun, excitement, playfulness, hilarity, and happiness, as if saying Squee! or Awesome! 
Similar to 😆 Grinning Squinting Face. Generally more exuberant than 😛 Face With Tongue and 😜 Winking Face With Tongue. Samsung previously featured a more sour expression.
Because of its stuck-out tongue, note that this smiley may be applied or interpreted in suggestive ways.

Squinting Face With Tongue was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face With Stuck-Out Tongue and Tightly-Closed Eyes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A love heart, broken in two. This emoji represents the aching one feels when they are missing the  person they love.

Broken Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A level slider, as adjusts volume on a mixing console. Most platforms depict a silver and black channel fader with scale markings, set to various levels.
Commonly used for various content concerning audio recording and production as well as music more generally. May also be used for figurative senses of level, e.g., next level.
Thanks to its appearance, some may use the emoji to represent a Christian cross.

Level Slider was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description: null

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Aquarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Water-bearer.

Aquarius was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Factory Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🏭 Factory emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Factory Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for St. Martin, which may show as the letters MF on some platforms. This is the French half of the of the Caribbean island of Saint Martin. Not to be confused with Sint Maarten, the Dutch half of the same island.
The Flag: St. Martin emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: St. Martin was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face smiling with thick, black-rimmed eyeglasses and buck teeth on most platforms. Styled after a stereotypical nerd, with buck teeth a racist caricature historically mocking East Asians. Some feature white-taped glasses, another nerd trope. Smile and glasses vary across platforms.
Meaning varies, but often used as a self-deprecating but positive way to express or demonstrate someone is being a nerd, i.e., exceptionally technical, knowledgeable, or excited about something, from school to fashion to sports. Also used to represent eyeglasses or someone wearing them more generally.
😎 Smiling Face With Sunglasses wears similarly shaped sunglasses.

Nerd Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Åland Islands, which may show as the letters AX on some platforms.
The Flag: Åland Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇽 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter X emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Åland Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Double Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Gabon, which may show as the letters GA on some platforms.
The Flag: Gabon emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Gabon was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: St. Kitts & Nevis emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: St. Kitts & Nevis was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A shop that is generally open for longer hours than a regular supermarket, sometimes 24 hours per day.
Sells a range of goods from snacks, meals, hygiene products and household items.

Convenience Store was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man: Bald emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🦲 Emoji Component Bald emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man: Bald was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled whale, shown spouting water from its blowhole. Generally depicted as a light-blue whale in full profile facing left, with a round body and white underside, its tail held upright.
Often used with an affectionate tone. Not to be confused with the more lifelike 🐋 Whale, though their applications may overlap.
WhatsApp’s whale is gray, as Microsoft and Facebook’s whales previously were. Twitter’s whale was previously purple.

Spouting Whale was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with raised eyebrows, enlarged eyes, slight frown, and long nose, indicating it’s telling a lie in the manner of Pinocchio. Like that character, Facebook's design features a wooden nose. 
May represent lying, a liar, and other concepts of deceit and dishonesty to varying degrees of intensity. Sometimes used to convey disbelief (e.g., You must be kidding) or feeling abashed (e.g., as if caught in the act of lying).

Lying Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A guitar, which is mostly shown as an electric guitar and usually in generally red.
Discontinued emoji sets or such as LG and HTC displayed this as an acoustic guitar, as did previous version of Windows and Twemoji.

Guitar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Elf emoji is a sequence of the 🧝 Elf and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Elf was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Rwanda, which may show as the letters RW on some platforms.
The Flag: Rwanda emoji is a sequence of the 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Rwanda was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
White Large Square was approved as part of Unicode 5.1 in 2008
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A graduation cap, worn on the head of students graduating from college or university. Known in some locations as a mortar board with tassel.

Graduation Cap was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Mechanic emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🔧 Wrench emojis.
