These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Mechanic was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A hat worn by women for sun protection, or for fashion.
The Apple version of this hat is made of straw and has a green bow on the front. Google shows a yellow hat on Android (with a ribbon in the latest version), while Windows and Twitter both feature a flower on the front of the hat.

Woman’s Hat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Womans Hat”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A waning gibbous moon (appearing more than half full but getting smaller), the sixth of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, mostly illuminated in gold or silver, but with its right side a dark crescent.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.
Not to be confused with 🌔 Waxing Gibbous Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning gibbous moon in a night sky with stars.

Waning Gibbous Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Waning Gibbous Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Red Circle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Large Red Circle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Mauritania, which may show as the letters MR on some platforms. This design changed in August 2017, adding a red band at the top and bottom.
Only newer vendor updates display the new flag design.
The Flag: Mauritania emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Mauritania was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A golden ball, split in two halves in a shower of multicolored confetti and streamers.
Like 🎉 Party Popper, commonly used to convey congratulations and celebration, as on New Year’s Eve, birthdays, wedding days, graduations, and other special occasions or good times more generally.
Its design across platforms—and inclusion in early sets from au by KDDI—suggest the emoji is a Japanese kusudama, a decorative ball used at such festive occasions as opening ceremonies.

Confetti Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A spade symbol emoji, which is used in card games for the spades suit.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Spade Suit was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Black Spade Suit”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A house which is unoccupied, and has become derelict. In a state of disrepair.

Derelict House was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Derelict House Building”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Men Wrestling emoji is a sequence of the 🤼 Wrestlers and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Men Wrestling was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
An umbrella that is closed, likely as a result of collapsing it prior to going indoors.
Shows as pink on Apple devices, blue on Android, and purple on Twitter.

Closed Umbrella was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A sauropod, a massive, plant-eating dinosaur with a long neck and nail. Depicted as a blue, gray, or green sauropod, as a brachiosaurus, apatosaurus/brontosaurus, or diplodocus. Shown in full profile on all fours facing left.
May be used to represent various dinosaurs. See also 🦖 T-Rex.
Apple, Google, Samsung, and Facebook’s sauropods resemble a brachiosaurus. Samsung’s sauropod was previously green, Facebook’s only a green head.


Sauropod was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family unit shown with two adults and one child. Previously displayed with the same design as 👨‍👩‍👦 Family: Man, Woman, Boy on most platforms, but now has its own gender inclusive appearance.

Family was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A jockey riding a horse in a horse race. Shown riding to the left of screen on all major platforms. Emoji modifiers change the skin tone of the jockey on some platforms, which can be difficult to discern at small sizes.

Horse Racing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description: null

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with small, open eyes and a big grin, playfully sticking out its tongue. Can variously convey a sense of fun, excitement, silliness, cuteness, happiness, or jesting, as if saying Just kidding!
Generally less goofy than 😜 Winking Face With Tongue and less animated than 😝 Squinting Face With Tongue. Google previously featured a more defeated expression and Samsung, a more mocking one.
Because of its stuck-out tongue, note that this smiley may be applied or interpreted in suggestive ways.

Face With Tongue was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
under the name “Face With Stuck-Out Tongue”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A triangle with an exclamation mark inside, used as a warning or alert.

Warning was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
under the name “Warning Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
The sun rising over a mountain range, early in the morning.

Sunrise Over Mountains was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A domestic cat, beloved as a pet. Generally depicted as a light-orange cat with stripes, as a tabby, in full profile on all fours facing left, with its long tell held upright.
See also 🐱 Cat Face.
Google’s cat is cartoon-styled, shown sitting on its hind legs with a friendly expression and whiskers. Facebook’s cat is a gray tabby, though previously was orange. Microsoft and Samsung’s cats were previously gray, Twitter’s brown.

Cat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A moai, one of the famed, giant stone statues of human figures on Easter Island. Depicted as a gray stone carving of a stylized human head with a prominent brow and nose, most often facing left.
Sometimes used for various idiosyncratic purposes, such as conveying a stoic, deadpan, or silly expression.
Its official Unicode name of Moyai and inclusion in early Japanese emoji sets, such as from au by KDDI, suggest the emoji may represent the Moyai Statue near Shibuya Station in Tokyo, Japan; previous designs from Google and Microsoft resemble the Tokyo statue. Other Tokyo landmarks are represented in 🗼 Tokyo Tower and, formerly, Shibuya 109.

Moai was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Moyai”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Slovenia, which may show as the letters SI on some platforms.
The Flag: Slovenia emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Slovenia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two triangles pointing to the right. Most commonly used as a symbol for fast forwarding media such as video tapes, CDs, or digital audio and video.

Fast-Forward Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
White Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Zambia, which may show as the letters ZM on some platforms.
The Flag: Zambia emoji is a sequence of the 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Zambia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, open smile, showing upper teeth and tongue on some platforms. Often conveys general happiness and good-natured amusement.
Similar to 😀 Grinning Face but with taller, more excited eyes. 

Grinning Face With Big Eyes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Smiling Face With Open Mouth”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Faroe Islands, which may show as the letters FO on some platforms.
The Flag: Faroe Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Faroe Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with a flat, neutral mouth and furrowed eyebrows, its left raised higher than its right. Conveys a wide variety of sentiments, including suspicion, skepticism, concern, consideration, disbelief, and disapproval.
Its expression has notably been likened to the signature look of comedian Stephen Colbert as well as actor/wrestler Dwayne “The Rock” Johnson.

Face With Raised Eyebrow was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
 under the name “Face With One Eyebrow Raised”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A motor scooter, which may be displayed as any type of motorbike with or without a step-through frame. Distinct from the racing motorcycle, which is used for sport, not transport.

Motor Scooter was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
3rd Place Medal was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Third Place Medal”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An ancient scroll, unrolled to reveal text on papyrus or parchment paper. May be used to represent the study of history or official documents, such as a diploma.
Many platforms indicate text with dark lines. WhatsApp’s design includes wooden rollers. Apple’s design features an easter egg, script of text from its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign:
…rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They're not fond of rules. And they have no respect for the status quo. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can't do is ignore…

Scroll was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A metal clamp or vice, as screwed to hold or compress materials like wood or metal. Depicted as a C-clamp or F-clamp, its screw in various positions.
Commonly used for various content concerning tools, equipment, and technology. May also represent file compression in computer science. An image of a clamp, for example, is featured in the WinZip icon.
Twitter’s clamp is red. Samsung’s design previously featured a clamp around a cardboard box.

Clamp was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Compression”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A cup of green tea, as the minty-colored Japanese matcha, usually shown on a wooden mat. Matcha is traditionally served in a small bowl that resembles a cup without a handle. Often taken as a bowl of soup, such as a split pea.

Teacup Without Handle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag for Texas (US-TX) emoji is a sequence of the 🏴 Waving Black Flag, 󠁵 Tag Latin Small Letter U, 󠁳 Tag Latin Small Letter S, 󠁴 Tag Latin Small Letter T, 󠁸 Tag Latin Small Letter X and 󠁿 Cancel Tag emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Four control knobs, as adjust audio levels on a mixing console. Generally depicted as a silver square with black knobs, turned to various levels as indicated by white pointers and scale markings.
Commonly used for various content concerning audio recording and production as well as music more generally.

Control Knobs was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A mountain with snow resting at higher altitudes. Similar in appearance to the Mount Fuji emoji.

Snow-Capped Mountain was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Snow Capped Mountain”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Arrows pointing in a clockwise direction, with a number 1 badge in the lower corner.  Used in music player applications to loop a track or album once.

Repeat Single Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows With Circled One Overlay”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Elf emoji is a sequence of the 🧝 Elf and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Elf was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Haiti, which may show as the letters HT on some platforms.
The Flag: Haiti emoji is a sequence of the 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Haiti was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A seashell, as found at the beach. Generally depicted as an empty, spiraling, white seashell, as grown by a sea snail or home to a hermit crab. Positioned at various angles across platforms.
Often used for various content concerning beaches, ocean and ocean life, and summer fun.
Microsoft’s shell is peach-colored. Apple’s design previously resembled a clam shell, Microsoft’s a snail shell. Google’s was previously blue.

Spiral Shell was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Two links of a silver chain, positioned at a 45° angle. Used as an icon for a hyperlink on computers and the internet. May also be used for metaphorical connections.
Not to be confused with ⛓️Chains, 📎 Paperclip, 🖇️ Linked Paperclips, or 🧷 Safety Pin.

Link was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Link Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A white toilet, as used to deposit a 💩 Pile of Poo. (Don’t forget the 🧻 Roll of Paper.) Most platforms depict a porcelain toilet in profile, bowl facing to the left.
Commonly used for various content concerning going to the bathroom or bathrooms more generally. May also be used figuratively, e.g., down the toilet.
Google, Microsoft, and Twitter’s designs left the seat up.

Toilet was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of bear, looking straight ahead. Depicted as a brown bear with round ears and a tan muzzle. Resembles a teddy bear.
Often used with an affectionate tone. Does not have a full-bodied bear emoji counterpart.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Samsung’s bear was previously golden brown.

Bear was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Bear Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
This character translates as meaning a finger or toe pointing to indicate a certain direction.
CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters.

Japanese “Reserved” Button was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6307”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A last quarter moon, the seventh of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its left side half illuminated in gold or silver, its remainder dark.
May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings.
See also 🌜 Last Quarter Moon Face. Not to be confused with 🌓 First Quarter Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme.
Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a last quarter moon in a night sky with stars.

Last Quarter Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Last Quarter Moon Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Kuwait, which may show as the letters KW on some platforms.
The Flag: Kuwait emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Kuwait was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A card index, as a Rolodex, once used to organize and access cards containing the information of personal or business contacts. Depicted as a black or gray rotating device with a contact card displayed, including a graphic and text.
Occasionally used to represent contact details/information and business cards. Thanks to its appearance, this emoji is sometimes mistaken for such things as documents or word processing.
Apple’s design features a picture of its 👩 Woman, identified as Jane Appleseed (previously John Appleseed) with the following contact details as an easter egg:
appleseed@me.com

125 Main St.

City Name, CA 95014

Work: (408) 123-4567

Home: (400) 765-4321
95014 is the zip code (postcode) for Apple’s corporate headquarters in Cupertino, California.
JoyPixels features its 👩‍⚕️ Woman Health Care Worker. WhatsApp's design also shows the picture of a woman.

Card Index was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic hourglass, all of its sand having flowed into the bottom bulb. Indicates time has passed. Color varies across platforms.
Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with ⏳ Hourglass Not Done, whose sand is still flowing.
Used on Snapchat to indicate a Snapstreak is soon to end.

Hourglass Done was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Hourglass”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A silver optical disc, as a CD or DVD, used to play music or movies before the rise of streaming technology. Commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, Blu-rays, and related film and music content, especially albums.
See also 💽 Computer Disk and 📀 DVD.

Optical Disk was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Optical Disc”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Ghana, which may show as the letters GH on some platforms.
The Flag: Ghana emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Ghana was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Puerto Rico, which may show as the letters PR on some platforms.
The Flag: Puerto Rico emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Puerto Rico was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A paper ticket, which may be for a theatre show, sporting event, or other ticketed performance. Shown in blue, yellow or grey on most platforms.

Ticket was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Macau, which may show as the letters MO on some platforms.
The Flag: Macao Sar China emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Macao Sar China was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Black Circle was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
under the name “Medium Black Circle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A symbol for email. Depicted as the back of an envelope imprinted with a capital letter E (for electronic) or @ (at) sign. Commonly used as an icon before an email address.
The envelope is generally white (except for Google’s yellow design) and the E or @, blue. Apple and Google’s designs feature the letter E, Microsoft and Samsung’s the @ sign.

E-Mail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “E-Mail Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A plane taking off from a runway. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane elevated.

Airplane Departure was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Most commonly known as a ✌️ Peace Sign, but traditionally called as a Victory Hand. Two fingers held up on one hand making a V sign.
The reverse of this symbol is considered an offence gesture in British culture, similar to giving the middle finger.

Victory Hand was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for the United States of America (USA), which may show as the letters US on some platforms.
The Flag: United States emoji is a sequence of the 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: United States was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A balloon on a string, as decorates a birthday party. Generally depicted in red, though WhatsApp’s is pink and Google’s orangish-red.
Commonly used to convey congratulations and celebration, especially when wishing someone a happy birthday.
Microsoft and Samsung's balloons were previously blue; SoftBank's was shown floating in the sky.

Balloon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🏋 Weight Lifter emoji.
The Woman Lifting Weights emoji is a sequence of the 🏋 Weight Lifter and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Lifting Weights was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Woman, Boy, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👦 Boy and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Boy, Boy was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman: Curly Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🦱 Emoji Component Curly Hair emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman: Curly Hair was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Aruba, which may show as the letters AW on some platforms.
The Flag: Aruba emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Aruba was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A smiley making a silly face. A yellow face with a big grin and wide, white eyes, one larger than the other and in a wild, cockeyed expression. Many platforms, including Apple, depict its tongue stuck out and head tilted; others feature a full-toothed grin, giving it a more unhinged appearance.
Commonly represents such activities as acting goofy, having fun, and partying as well as various senses of slang terms like crazy, usually in a positive manner. May convey a spirit of wackiness more generally.

Zany Face was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Grinning Face With One Large and One Small Eye”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
An emoji to depict a wedding, displayed by most vendors as a Christian church and love hearts. Some platforms display a cross or bell on the building.

Wedding was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A staff (or stave) showing a treble clef and five horizontal lines.

Musical Score was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A door, as to the entrance of a room, house, or new opportunity. (We’ll see ourselves out 🚪🚶.) Depicted in brown, as made of wood, with a gold handle.
May represent literal doors and related concepts (e.g., rooms, houses) but often used figuratively (e.g., opening or closing metaphorical doors).
Google’s design features a peephole and Microsoft’s a step, as if a front door.

Door was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The flaky, golden-brown crescent of a croissant, a breakfast pastry associated with France and Austria.

Croissant was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 👯 Woman With Bunny Ears emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Women With Bunny Ears emoji is a sequence of the 👯 Woman With Bunny Ears and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Women With Bunny Ears was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
White Circle was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
under the name “Medium White Circle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman wearing business attire. This may include items such as a shirt, blouse, tie, jacket, or headset.
The Woman Office Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 💼 Briefcase emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Office Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Four O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Four O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Mermaid emoji is a sequence of the 🧜 Merperson and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Mermaid was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two hands clapping emoji, which when used multiple times can be used as a round of applause.

Clapping Hands was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clapping Hands Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Meow! A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a cat, looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a yellowish-orange cat face with pointed ears and whiskers.
May be used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied 🐈 Cat, though their applications generally overlap.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Vendors implement the same or similar cat in their 🐈 Cat as well as in their cat-faced variants of smileys:

😼 Cat Face With Wry Smile
😹 Cat Face With Tears of Joy
🙀 Weary Cat Face
😾 Pouting Cat Face
😿 Crying Cat Face
😻 Smiling Cat Face With Heart-Eyes
😺 Grinning Cat Face
😸 Grinning Cat Face With Smiling Eyes
😽 Kissing Cat Face

Google’s cat face was previously orange, Samsung’s gray, and Facebook’s once gray and white. Included in the earliest Japanese emoji sets from Softbank, Docomo, and au by KDDI.

Cat Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Venezuela, which may show as the letters VE on some platforms.
The Flag: Venezuela emoji is a sequence of the 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Venezuela was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A squirt gun (water pistol), as used to spray water for fun.
On major platforms, depicted as a green or orange toy gun with an orange tip and barrel pointed left. Google, Microsoft, and Facebook’s designs include mounted reservoirs.
Originally depicted as a classic handgun, as a revolver or other pistol. In 2016, Apple switched its design from weapon to toy; other major vendors followed suit by 2018. Deprecated emoji sets or smaller platforms still display the emoji as a handgun.
Microsoft initially displayed the emoji as a toy ray gun before switching to a revolver, then squirt gun. Google once featured a blunderbuss.

Pistol was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A gesture showing the index finger and thumb touching to make an open circle. Represents “I’m okay” or “yes, that’s correct / good”.
In American Sign Language (ASL), the number nine is represented with this gesture. The same hand sign can be seen as offensive in some cultures, including in parts of Europe, the Middle East, and South America.
Attempts have been made to imply that this is a symbol of “White Power”, which may be the case depending on context.

OK Hand was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “OK Hand Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A pink hibiscus, a flower that grows in warm climates. Depicted as a single, deep-pink hibiscus flower with green leaves and prominent, yellow stamen.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to convey such ideas as love, happiness, and beauty. Also used as a pink accent color and in association with Hawaii and other Polynesian places and cultures.
Google and Samsung's hibiscus flowers were previously orange.

Hibiscus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Five O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Five O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A raccoon, a nocturnal mammal with a mask around its eyes. Generally depicted as a friendly, cartoon-styled, gray raccoon face looking straight ahead, with black-and-white markings around its eyes and pointed ears and cheeks.
Apple and WhatsApp’s designs feature a raccoon in full profile on all fours facing left with a striped, bushy tail.

Raccoon was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Fairy emoji is a sequence of the 🧚 Fairy and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Fairy was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An elephant, the largest land animal on Earth, with a long trunk and, often, tusks. Generally depicted in gray in full profile on all fours facing left, with tusks and prominent ears, as an African (vs. Asian) elephant.
Google and Facebook’s elephants were previously blue in color. Samsung’s design previously featured a cartoon-styled elephant with a red blanket on its back and blowing a red heart from its trunk.

Elephant was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010

and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with closed eyes, frown, and a bead of sweat dripping from its forehead. Usually depicted with a single sweat bead on its right side, though Microsoft includes two.
Meaning widely varies, but commonly conveys a moderate degree of sadness, pain, frustration, or disappointment, similar to 😢 Crying Face and 😥 Sad But Relieved Face. Not to be confused with 😅 Grinning Face With Sweat or other emojis with tear or sweat droplets.
Google previously featured a blue face. Microsoft previously depicted multiple beads of sweat from around the smiley’s forehead. Earlier designs from Samsung had more pleading eyes.

Downcast Face With Sweat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face With Cold Sweat”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A timepiece set in advance to startle a person awake at the designated time with its two bells. That is, before hitting snooze. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted as a classic, wind-up, bedside alarm clock, often red in color.
May be used for various content concerning alarms, alerts, sleeping, waking, and time more generally.

Alarm Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Keycap Digit Three emoji is a sequence of the 3 Digit Three and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Keycap Digit Three was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A symbol representing Blood Type O. Displayed as the letter O on a red background.

O Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter O”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-left, or north-west direction.

Up-Left Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “North West Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A classic snowman, as Frosty the Snowman, with snowflakes falling on it. Depicted as a snowman, facing forward, made from two or three large snowballs and stick arms, dressed with a top hat, a carrot nose, coal eyes, and two or three buttons on its torso. Sometimes shown with a smile and a red scarf.
Often used for various content concerning winter fun and Christmastime.
Vendors implement the same figure for their ⛄ Snowman Without Snow, which does not have snowflakes.
Google’s snowman is wearing green gloves, thoguh its snowman previously lacked any attire. Samsung's previously lacked a hat.
This snowman predates Unicode emoji support, which explains why it may display as the black-and-white outline of a snowman.

Snowman was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A white bathtub with a silver shower head. Often depicted as a cast-iron tub with claw-foot legs. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and bathrooms more generally.
Several platforms, including Apple and Facebook, feature soap bubbles or suds. Samsung’s design displays streaming water from the shower head.
Vendors implement 🛀 Person Taking a Bath with the same or a similar emoji, but with a person soaking in the tub.

Bathtub was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A yellow sun half covered by a white cloud. Position of the sun varies across platforms.
May be used as a weather icon to represent a partly cloudy day.
Not to be confused with 🌤️ Sun Behind Small Cloud or ⛅ Sun Behind Large Cloud, though their applications may overlap.
Microsoft’s cloud was previously gray, Samsung’s bluish.

Sun Behind Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for South Korea, which may show as the letters KR on some platforms.
The Flag: South Korea emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: South Korea was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A balance scale, as historically used to measure weight. A symbol of justice, as held by Lady Justice, and of the zodiac sign of Libra, the Scales. Depicted as two silver or gold pans suspended from a beam and supported on a base.
Commonly used for various content concerning law and justice as well as various senses of balance and weight.
Samsung’s design previously featured a stylized, white balance scale on a green square, as an icon or symbol of legal matters or institutions.

Balance Scale was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
under the name “Scales”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A blue or black ballpoint pen, as used for everyday writing. Depicted with its cap removed onto its end or as retractable pen. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning writing (e.g., creative, professional) as well as signing (deals, laws, in sports).
Google's design previously featured a brown-colored pen. Not to be confused with ✒️ Black Nib or 🖋️ Fountain Pen, though their applications often overlap.

Pen was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
 under the name “Lower Left Ballpoint Pen”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Two O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A drinking cup with a straw. Depicted on many platforms as a disposable cup with a lid and bendy straw, as used to serve soft drinks at fast-food restaurants. May be used for a range of non-alcoholic beverages, including milkshakes, smoothies, juice, and to-go beverages.
Color and design vary by platform. Twitter's design suggests a glass of water, Samsung displays Slightly Smiling Face on a red label.

Cup With Straw was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A globe, showing the continents of North and South America in green against blue ocean.
May be used to represent various content concerning the North and South American regions as well Atlantic and Pacific regions. May also be used to represent Earth and international affairs more generally.
See also 🌍 Globe Showing Europe-Africa and 🌏 Globe Showing Asia-Australia.

Globe Showing Americas was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Earth Globe Americas”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A form of speech balloon used with angular edges, used to denote angry speech in comics.

Right Anger Bubble was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: St. Pierre & Miquelon emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: St. Pierre & Miquelon was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A bookmark, as used to mark one's place in a book. May also represent bookmarks on an internet browser. Appearance varies across platforms, but generally depicted at a 45° angle as a thin, white or red strip with a decorative tie and design, such as flower or star.
May be used for various content concerning reading, labeling, or tagging.
WhatsApp’s bookmark is purple. Twitter’s design shows a red bookmark in a closed book, similar to previous designs from Microsoft. Twitter and Google’s designs previously featured a blue bookmark.
Not to be confused with 🏷️ Label.


Bookmark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Factory Worker emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🏭 Factory emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Factory Worker was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A metal filing cabinet, as used to organize and store file folders at an office. Depicted in black or gray with two drawers, handles, and label holders.
Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files; filing and organization; various types of data, information, and archives; and office work.
Google’s design was previously blue, Facebook’s had its bottom drawer open.

File Cabinet was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
Japanese sake, an alcoholic beverage made from rice. Shown as a sake set with a carafe (tokkuri) and drinking cup (choko). Color varies widely by platform, with Apple, WhatsApp, and Twitter featuring blue, a traditional ceramic color. Samsung displays the Japanese script for “sake” in red.

Sake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Sake Bottle and Cup”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A type of cards known as hanafuda cards in Japan which are used for a range of different games that require associating pictures (there are no numbers on the cards).
The artwork for this emoji shows the Full Moon with Red Sky card, but could theoretically display any of the available cards.

Flower Playing Cards was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A cartoon-styled bomb, depicted as a black ball with a burning fuse.
Commonly used for various figurative bombs or explosions, e.g., slang bomb, a “home run” in baseball or softball; "excellent" or "attractive." Sometimes applied in contexts of war, weapons, or violence.
Earlier designs from SoftBank and au by KDDI animated the bomb as exploding.

Bomb was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010

and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
The Statue of Liberty, often used as a depiction of New York City.

Statue of Liberty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Guinea, which may show as the letters GN on some platforms.
The Flag: Guinea emoji is a sequence of the 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Guinea was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A light-green variety of a common pear, shown with a stem and sometimes green leaf.
May be used for its namesake expression, pear-shaped (“prominent hips” or “failure”).

Pear was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Norway, which may show as the letters NO on some platforms.
The Flag: Norway emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Norway was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A person dropping litter (rubbish, trash) with a red stroke through it, indicating that littering is prohibited in this area.
Usually implied by the fact that littering is not welcome anywhere, this sign serves as a reminder in areas that are known to attract litter.

No Littering was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Do Not Litter Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Zombie emoji is a sequence of the 🧟 Zombie and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Zombie was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The letters ID in a square.

ID Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared ID”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Cayman Islands, which may show as the letters KY on some platforms.
The Flag: Cayman Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Cayman Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The Woman Playing Handball emoji is a sequence of the 🤾 Handball and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Playing Handball was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A Japanese onigiri, a cone-shaped ball of white rice, a snack wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed.

Rice Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for European Union, which may show as the letters EU on some platforms.
The Flag: European Union emoji is a sequence of the 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: European Union was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An everyday flashlight (electric torch), as used when the power goes out, camping, or telling scary stories. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a gray and black device with a switch, shown illuminated on many platforms.
Used for various content concerning and senses of light and lighting (e.g., spotlight).
Google’s flashlight is orange.

Flashlight was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Electric Torch”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A swan, a waterbird with white feathers and a long neck. Depicted in full profile facing left, with a curving neck, orange bill, black eye marking, and wings and legs tucked in, as if gliding in water.
May be used to represent a goose or, metaphorically, love, grace, and beauty.

Swan was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Iceland, which may show as the letters IS on some platforms.
The Flag: Iceland emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Iceland was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Nine-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Nine-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A pouch with a clasp, generally used to keep coins or other forms of currency.
Color varies by platform, with silver or gold (gray or yellow) the most common type of clasp shown.

Purse was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Nine O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Nine O’Clock”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A villain which may be displayed as a man,woman or gender-neutral / gender-inclusive depending on the platform. This base emoji does not specify a gender, but is used to create the emojis for Man Supervillain and Woman Supervillain.
The Superhero is the nemesis of this emoji.

Supervillain was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A pig, a plump animal farmed for its meat, such as bacon. Depicted in light pink in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long snout and short, curly tail.
May be used to represent the animal, its food products, or various metaphorical senses of pig.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac; 2019 is the Year of the Pig. See also 🐷 Pig Face, 🐽 Pig Nose, and 🐗 Boar.
WhatsApp’s design previously featured a wide grin.

Pig was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A tractor, may be used by a farmer or other occupation on the land.

Tractor was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with scrunched, X-shaped eyes, furrowed eyebrows, and a broad, open frown, as if yawning in exhaustion or groaning in exasperation. Usually shown with upper teeth and sometimes tongue.
While intended to represent tiredness, it commonly conveys various degrees and tones of frustration and sadness as well excitement and affection, as if it just can’t handle how great someone or something is.
Similar in appearance and meaning to 😩 Weary Face, but with scrunched eyes. Not to be confused with 😪 Sleepy Face or 😴 Sleeping Face, which often convey actually being asleep. 
Samsung’s design previously featured three, vertical, blue lines over its forehead, which can indicate fatigue in manga and anime.

Tired Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
Two people in the sport of wrestling.

People Wrestling was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Wrestlers”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman: Bald emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🦲 Emoji Component Bald emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman: Bald was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A red paper lantern, as hangs outside an izakaya, a Japanese bar that serves drinks and casual food. Generally depicted as cylindrical with a black top and base and soft, orange glow.
May be used to represent various lights and lanterns as well as for its red color.

Red Paper Lantern was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Izakaya Lantern”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Ferry was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A skewer of three bites of Japanese oden, a winter dish made with fishcakes, tofu, konnyaku, and a variety of other ingredients, including boiled eggs. Often served as a stew or skewered and dipped into soy sauce. Resembles the Dango and may be used for other skewered foods (e.g., shish kebab, roasting marshmallows) or spears.

Oden was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The round, golden-brown pastry of a Chinese mooncake, a traditional delicacy and lunar symbol of the Mid-Autumn Festival. Many platforms feature a design or character imprinted on the crust, and depict a slice cut out to show a brown paste with a duck egg yolk inside. Twitter displays the Chinese character for “fall/autumn” or “harvest” (秋) on top.

Moon Cake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A person lifting a barbell loaded with weights above their head.

Person Lifting Weights was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Weight Lifter”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a rabbit, looking straight ahead. Generally depicted as a gray and/or white rabbit face with upright ears and pink ears and nose, often with whiskers and a buck tooth.
Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied 🐇 rabbit. Also often used to represent the Easter Bunny.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Microsoft’s rabbit face was previously pink-colored with one ear flopping down. Facebook’s rabbit face was previously gray-colored with both ears flopping down.

Rabbit Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person with a visible beard. Generally displayed with a masculine appearance.

Man: Beard was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Bearded Person”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A hand with thumb and little (pinky) finger extended, making a traditional phone-like shape. May be used in conjunction with a face to suggest “call me” (please).
Not to be confused with the sign of the horns or the shaka sign (which does not yet have an emoji representation).

Call Me Hand was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Scientist emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🔬 Microscope emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Scientist was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A wastebasket, as used to discard trash in an office. Generally depicted as a silver, wire-mesh container. Also known as a wastepaper basket, trash/garbage can, or rubbish bin.
Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative waste. May also be used in the context of basketball. Sometimes paired with 🔥 Fire as a visual representation of the slang expression dumpster fire ("chatoic situation").
Samsung’s design depicts a metal can/bin with a lid, as used for outdoor garbage—or lived in by Oscar the Grouch. Not to be confused with 🧺 Basket.

Wastebasket was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: St. Vincent & Grenadines emoji is a sequence of the 🇻 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter V and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: St. Vincent & Grenadines was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Paraguay, which may show as the letters PY on some platforms.
The Flag: Paraguay emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇾 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Y emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Paraguay was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A pink tulip flower. Depicted as a single, vertical pink tulip on a green stem.
Commonly used for Valentine’s Day, Mother’s Day, and other special occasions. May be more generally used to express such sentiments as love, appreciation, and happiness. Also used in association with the Netherlands and as a pink accent color.
Not to be confused with 🌹 Rose, though their applications may overlap.
Google's tulip was once orange, Microsoft and Samsung's red.

Tulip was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
One-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face One-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for British Indian Ocean Territory, which may show as the letters IO on some platforms. The same flag is used for Diego Garcia.
The Flag: British Indian Ocean Territory emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.
 
Flag: British Indian Ocean Territory was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A scorpion, an arachnid with lobster-like pincers and a stinging tail. Depicted as a light-brown scorpion from above, often facing left, with its pincers and curving stinger raised. Shown with six or, accurately, eight legs in addition to its pincers.
Often used to represent ♏ Scorpio in the Western zodiac.
WhatsApp’s scorpion is reddish in color, as is Microsoft’s stinger.

Scorpion was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The hairy shell of a tropical coconut, cracked in a half to show its milky-white meat. Google displays a whole coconut alongside a half-shell. 

Coconut was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Man Farmer emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man and 🌾 Ear of Rice emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Farmer was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A baby chicken (chick), hatching from an egg and seeing the world for the first time. Depicted as a yellow chick with an orange beak facing forward in the cracked, bottom half of a white egg, generally shown flapping its wings with a cute facial expression.
Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent various types of baby birds. May also be used to represent chicken foods (e.g., poultry, eggs), spring, Easter, or slang senses of chick.
Not to be confused with 🐤 Baby Chick or 🐥Front-Facing Baby Chick (out of its egg), though their applications overlap. See also 🐔 Chicken and 🐓 Rooster.
Twitter and Facebook's designs do not include wings. Google's design previously featured motion lines around the chick's wings, indicating flapping. Facebook's design previously showed part of the egg atop the chick's head.

Hatching Chick was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
A skull and crossbones displayed on a black flag, used on pirate ships, also known as a Jolly Roger.
The Pirate Flag emoji is a sequence of the 🏴 Waving Black Flag and ☠ Skull and Crossbones emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Pirate Flag was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A pushpin, as used to indicate a location on a map. Generally depicted as an upright pin with a red, round head.
Commonly used to indicate locations and notably featured in the Pushpin Emoji Detour and Distance Between memes on Twitter. Also used unofficially as an icon for Pinterest or Google Maps.
Facebook’s pin is oriented at a 45° angle, as were previous designs on several other platforms.
Not to be confused with 📌 Pushpin, though their applications may overlap.

Round Pushpin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010

and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A cricket, a hopping insect that makes a chirping sound. Depicted as a brown or green cricket in full profile on its six legs facing left, with long antennae and large, bent back legs.
May resemble or be used to represent a grasshopper (including locusts) and other bugs. May also be used to represent metaphorical crickets, or "silence," as of a disapproving or uninterested audience.
Not to be confused with 🏏 Cricket Game, the sport.
Google's cricket was previously green.

Cricket was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A single, light blue droplet, as of water, sweat, or tears.
May be used for various types of liquid. May also be used to expression sadness, as in 😢 Crying Face, or for various liquid-based slang expressions (e.g., drip, “exceptional style, swagger").
Not to be confused with 💦 Sweat Droplets, though their applications may overlap.

Droplet was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A cartoon human skull atop an X-shaped pair of bones, as on a pirate flag or poison symbol. Samsung’s design previously displayed a skull and crossbones on a yellow triangle, indicating a hazardous material.
May represent various ideas of death or danger, e.g., dying from laughter or killing it with great skill. May also represent various pirate characters or mascots.
Popular around Halloween. Not to be confused with 💀 Skull, though their applications may overlap.

Skull and Crossbones was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A colorful swirl of hard candy on a stick, called a lollipop. Color varies widely by platform: Google displays rainbow colors, Android shades of pink, and Samsung a candy-cane-colored pinwheel.
"Lollipop" was the name of version 5 of Google's Android operating system.

Lollipop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A beautiful view, featuring an orange sky, with the sun setting over the buildings of a city skyline.

Sunset was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Sunset Over Buildings”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The Gemini astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents Twins.

Gemini was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for St. Helena, which may show as the letters SH on some platforms. This same flag is used for Ascension Island and Tristan Da Cunha.
The Flag: St. Helena emoji is a sequence of the 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S and 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: St. Helena was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Andorra, which may show as the letters AD on some platforms.
The Flag: Andorra emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Andorra was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Nepal, which may show as the letters NP on some platforms.
The Flag: Nepal emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Nepal was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A medical syringe, as used to administer a shot or draw blood. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a needle to the upper right, emitting two droplets of the red fluid in its barrel, as blood drawn for testing or donation at a hospital.
Commonly used for content concerning health, medicine, and related professions as well as various senses of needles, drugs, and blood.
Google and Facebook’s designs previously featured green liquids, Samsung’s syringe was empty.

Syringe was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A bow and arrow used in the sport of archery. May also be used by cupid.

Bow and Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A reanimated human, often found in works of horror fiction. May have a female or male appearance.

Zombie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
A white flag, shown waving on a post. Traditionally used as a sign of surrender, the meaning of this flag as an emoji is less defined.

White Flag was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Waving White Flag”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for French Southern Territories, which may show as the letters TF on some platforms.
