The Flag: French Southern Territories emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: French Southern Territories was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for North Korea, which may show as the letters KP on some platforms.
The Flag: North Korea emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: North Korea was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A slightly open tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for an opened folder when using a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left.
Commonly used for various content concerning filing, organization, and work, especially at an office.
Apple’s folder is gray, Twitter’s is blue. Google’s design features multiple tabs, Microsoft’s a red tab.
Nearly identical in appearance and use to 📁 File Folder, which is closed.

Open File Folder was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The female version of the 🙎 Person With Pouting Face emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Woman Pouting emoji is a sequence of the 🙎 Person With Pouting Face and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Pouting was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The letters OK, shown enclosed in a square. Meaning Okay, denoting approval. The opposite of the Squared NG Emoji.

OK Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Squared OK”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A decorative exclamation mark, where a heart forms the top part of the symbol, and a circle the lower part. Similar to the way to the man in business suit levitating also creates a similar shape.

Heart Exclamation was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “Heavy Heart Exclamation Mark Ornament”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A classic circus or birthday clown. Features white face makeup, a red nose, exaggerated eyes and smile, and two tufts of hair (red or blue). May convey that someone is silly or foolish or that something is creepy or scary.

Clown Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two men standing next to each other, smiling, with a pink love heart floating in the air between them.
The Couple With Heart: Man, Man emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, ❤ Heavy Black Heart and 👨 Man emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Couple With Heart: Man, Man was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
Black Flag was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Waving Black Flag”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A single finger pointing upward, which could be used to represent the number one, or to ask a question.

Index Pointing Up was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “White Up Pointing Index”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A hammer and pick, as used for breaking up rocks in mining, crossed in an X shape. Generally depicted as metal, mallet- and chisel-styled hammers with wooden handles. The heads of the tools face up, with the pick usually at the right. Often used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction.
Facebook implements the same designs as for its 🔨 Hammer and ⛏️ Pick. Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white tools on a green square, as a sign or icon of a mine.

Hammer and Pick was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
An ox, a bovine used as a draft animal. Depicted in brown in full profile on all fours facing left, with a tail and short horns.
Often used to represent a bull. Occasionally paired with 💩 Pile of Poo to stand in for slang terms.
One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac. Often used to represent ♉ Taurus (the Bull) in the Western zodiac.
Not to be confused with 🐃 Water Buffalo.
Facebook’s ox was previously gray.

Ox was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person with arms above her or his head, making an ‘OK’ sign (circle) with the whole body. No gender is specified, but this emoji is generally shown as a woman.
Previously displayed as an alien or blob on Android, and a man on Windows.

Person Gesturing OK was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Face With OK Gesture”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A whole potato—such as a russet, used for baking, mashing, or frying—shown with a few eyes on its golden-brown skin. Not to be confused with the roasted sweet potato.

Potato was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Uganda, which may show as the letters UG on some platforms.
The Flag: Uganda emoji is a sequence of the 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Uganda was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A loaf of white or wheat bread, as before it is sliced for toast or sandwiches.

Bread was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An icon of a outlined sun, used when increasing the brightness of a screen. Appears larger than the Low Brightness Symbol.

Bright Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “High Brightness Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A telescope, as used to gaze at stars and planets in the night sky. Shown with an optical tube mounted on a tripod, positioned at various angles and generally depicted as metal.
Commonly used for various content concerning astronomy, outer space, celestial objects, and science more generally. May also be used for various concepts of sight (e.g., spying, viewing).
Google and Twitter’s designs feature red hardware.

Telescope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
Desert was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
End Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “End With Leftwards Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two hands placed firmly together, meaning please or thank you in Japanese culture. A common alternative use for this emoji is for prayer, using the same gesture as praying hands. Rarely: a high-five.
A previous version of this emoji displayed a yellow burst of light behind the two hands on iOS. Android once showed a blob-character with closed eyes and folded hands.

 Folded Hands was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Person With Folded Hands”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
Eek! A mouse, a small rodent with large ears and a long tail. Generally depicted in white in full profile on all fours facing left, with pink ears, feet, and tail, often with reddish eyes.
See also 🐭 Mouse Face. Not to be confused with 🐀 Rat—or 🖱️ Computer Mouse.
Google’s design is noticeably more cartoon-styled, standing on its hind legs and facing forward with a buck tooth. Facebook’s mouse is sitting on its hind legs. Microsoft’s mouse was previously brown.

Mouse was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A check mark that displays with a white outlined appearance. Shows on most platforms with a bright green rounded rectangle or circle surrounding it.
Android previously displayed this as an outlined blue check mark / blue tick.
This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark.

Check Mark Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “White Heavy Check Mark”
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A wedge of yellow-orange cheese with holes, like a Swiss, but used for the food in general. May be used for various cheese-related slang expressions (e.g., “cheesy,” “say cheese,” “big cheese”).

Cheese Wedge was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A ticket or tickets to an event that may say "Admit One" on the front. Shown in pink or yellow on most platforms.

Admission Tickets was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A middle finger emoji, used in some western cultures as a rude or insulting gesture. The back of the hand is shown with the middle finger raised.

Middle Finger was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Reversed Hand With Middle Finger Extended”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A flat shoe, in a style generally worn by women. More practical than a high-heeled shoe.

Flat Shoe was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A desktop personal computer. Generally depicted as a black or gray monitor with a dark or blue screen.
Like 💻 Laptop Computer, used for various content concerning computer technology, work, and activity. May also be used to represent television, as it resembles a flatscreen TV.
Google and WhatsApp include keyboards. Apple’s design resembles an iMac. Microsoft and Samsung’s designs previously featured PC towers.

Desktop Computer was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A plane approaching a runway for landing. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane facing toward the ground in a position that may result in a crash if attempted in the real world.

Airplane Arrival was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Airplane Arriving”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The male version of the 💂 Guardsman emoji. Currently identical in appearance to the non-gendered base emoji.
The Man Guard emoji is a sequence of the 💂 Guardsman and ♂ Male Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Man Guard was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with open eyes, raised or furrowed eyebrows, and a broad frown. May convey a variety of moderately sad or tense emotions, including concern, anxiety, alarm, disappointment, and unhappiness. 
Apple’s design features the same eye expression as on its 😯 Hushed Face. Not to be confused with 😲  Astonished Face or 😵 Dizzy Face. 
Samsung’s design previously included sweat droplets coming from its cheeks, a shorthand for anxiety in manga and anime.

Worried Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012
 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A 3.5-inch floppy disk, a data storage format popular in the 1980–90s but largely preserved as a Save icon in computer programs. Shown with its silver shutter positioned up and in a black housing with a white label, accented with blue or red.
Occasionally used for various content concerning computers, including nostalgia for old technology, as well as to represent electronic saving.

Floppy Disk was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description: null

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A circular ‘big top’ circus tent, with a triangle flag on top.

Circus Tent was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with closed eyes, furrowed brows, and a broad, open frown, as if distraught to the point of giving up. Usually shown with upper teeth and sometimes tongue.
May convey various feelings of frustration, sadness, amusement, and affection. Often playful in tone.
Similar in appearance and meaning to 😫 Tired Face, but with crescent-shaped eyes. Samsung’s design previously featured large eyes half-closed in tiredness.
This emoji has a cat variant, 🙀 Weary Cat Face, though it more closely resembles 😱 Face Screaming in Fear.


Weary Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with open eyes, raised eyebrows, and an open mouth, as if gasping in shock or surprise. Often depicted showing its upper teeth. May convey a wide range of emotions, including awe, amazement, admiration, disbelief, excitement, or concern.
Similar to 😯 Hushed Face, which features smaller eyes and mouth. Several earlier designs, including Apple’s, displayed X-shaped eyes, making the emoji resemble 😵 Dizzy Face. Google’s design previously depicted a wobbly expression, as if inebriated.

Astonished Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
An apparatus for distilling, as used in medieval alchemy. Generally depicted as a round flask with a neck angled down to the right. Positioned on a short stand and containing a mysterious green, purple, or blue liquid.
Commonly used for various content concerning chemistry and science more generally. May represent various liquids, such as potions or medicines, as well as metaphorical laboratories and experiments.
Thanks to the alembic’s association with alchemy, this emoji may also convey a sense of magic. And, thanks to its resemblance to a glass pipe, some use the emoji to represent a bong or other drug paraphernalia.
Samsung’s design previously featured a copper still, as used for making whiskey.
 
Alembic was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A tent, used for protection from wind and rain when camping. Often shown at night time, under stars.

Tent was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The Flag: Trinidad & Tobago emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Trinidad & Tobago was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Clockwise Vertical Arrows was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A revolving red light seen on top of a police car. Often used in emergency circumstances in addition to a siren making a loud warning sound.

Police Car Light was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Police Cars Revolving Light”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Red Triangle Pointed Down was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Down-Pointing Red Triangle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A knife with a long steel blade, as a chef uses to slice meat or vegetables. Depicted with a black or brown handle and positioned at a 45° angle, often with its point at the lower right.
May be used for content concerning cooking and food preparation, but often represents various senses of cutting and stabbing. Its Unicode name, Hocho, means “kitchen knife” in Japanese and refers to a variety of knives used in Japan.
Not to be confused with 🗡️ Dagger or ⚔️ Crossed Swords.

Kitchen Knife was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Hocho”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A hand shown pressing against the head of a person, commonly written as facepalm. Used to display frustration or embarrassment at the ineptitude of a person or situation.
May be used in a similar context to the acronym SMH (shaking my head), or in relation to the Picard Facepalm meme.

Person Facepalming was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Face Palm”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Marshall Islands, which may show as the letters MH on some platforms.
The Flag: Marshall Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Marshall Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Orange Heart was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Family: Woman, Girl, Girl emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👧 Girl and 👧 Girl emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Girl, Girl was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A four-leaf clover, a symbol of good luck. Depicted as a bright green sprig of clover, with four, heart-shaped leaves.
Not to be confused with the three-leaf ☘️ Shamrock.

Four Leaf Clover was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A wave of water, as breaks at the beach. Depicted as a blue wave with a foamy, white crest, curling to the right.
May be used to represent water in general, various bodies of water like oceans, and water activities, such as swimming, surfing, and sailing. May also be used to represent metaphorical waves.
Apple’s design resembles the iconic wave in Japanese artist Hokusai’s famous woodblock print, The Great Wave off Kanagawa (ca. 1830).

Water Wave was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a koala—a bear-like marsupial known for eating eucalyptus and sleeping—looking straight ahead. Depicted as a gray face with round, fluffy ears and a large, black nose.
Often used with an affectionate tone and in association with Australia, where the animal is found.
Available as an Apple Animoji.
Google’s koala was previously climbing a tree. Softbank’s koala previously resembled 🐻 Bear Face.

Koala was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A classic sad face. A yellow face with simple, open eyes and wide, steep frown. May convey such feelings as moderate concern or disappointment and affectionate sadness, as when missing a loved one. Its sentiment is usually more intense than 🙁 Slightly Frowning Face, which has a smaller frown.
This smiley predates Unicode emoji support. In its Unicode name of White Frowning Face, white does not refer to skin tone or ethnicity, although Samsung’s early designs colored the face white. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names.


Frowning Face was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
under the name “White Frowning Face”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A golden-brown chocolate chip cookie, or biscuit, though representing the baked treat more generally. Samsung, which features a pair of cookies, previously displayed this as two saltine crackers.

Cookie was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Generic profile of two people. Often used in interface design to represent users.

Busts in Silhouette was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
An arrow, pointing left.
See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

Left Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003
under the name “Leftwards Black Arrow”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A thumbtack (drawing pin), as used to pin documents on a bulletin (notice) board. Depicted at a 45° angle with its red, flat head to the upper right.
Often used as an icon for Pinterest or metaphorically pinning content online. Not to be confused with 📍 Round Pushpin, though their applications may overlap.

Pushpin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A raised hand, showing the reverse side of the palm. May be paired with the forward-facing raised hand emoji.

Raised Back of Hand was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The edible fungus of the mushroom, depicted as a toadstool with a white-spotted red cap and stem.

Mushroom was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Ireland, which may show as the letters IE on some platforms.
The Flag: Ireland emoji is a sequence of the 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Ireland was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
White Medium Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A triangle or set square, as used by engineers or architects to draw straight lines at angles. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic right triangle with length markings, its hypotenuse to the right.
Commonly applied to a range of disciplines, including art, design, building, architecture, and STEM (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics). May also represent various concepts of angles and measurement.

Triangular Ruler was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Kazakhstan, which may show as the letters KZ on some platforms.
The Flag: Kazakhstan emoji is a sequence of the 🇰 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter K and 🇿 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Z emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Kazakhstan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and no mouth, as if at a loss for words. Meaning widely varies, but commonly conveys speechlessness, humility, and silence. May also convey moderately negative emotions, such as disappointment, frustration, or sadness. 
Samsung’s design previously featured raised eyebrows and blushing cheeks.

Face Without Mouth was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Montserrat, which may show as the letters MS on some platforms.
The Flag: Montserrat emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Montserrat was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A person in the process of getting their hair cut. This emoji is intended to be gender-neutral, but is commonly shown as a girl or woman smiling, with scissors shown open next to the hair on her head.
Windows previously displayed this emoji as a comb and scissors, instead of a person having their hair cut.

Person Getting Haircut was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Haircut”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Portugal, which may show as the letters PT on some platforms.
The Flag: Portugal emoji is a sequence of the 🇵 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter P and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Portugal was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A chipmunk, a squirrel-like rodent with puffy cheeks. Depicted as a reddish-brown chipmunk in full profile facing left, sitting on its hind legs with a bushy tail and striped face and body. Generally holding an acorn or other nut in its forelimbs.
Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent a squirrel or related animals.
Google’s chipmunk is looking forward, squinting with a buck tooth. Microsoft’s previous black-and-white design could be mistaken for a skunk.

Chipmunk was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
The game of billiards, of which pool is a common version. This emoji displays the black 8 ball on most platforms, which looks similar to the Magic 8-Ball toy.
Samsung displays this emoji with a cue and triangular arrangement of colored balls.

Pool 8 Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Billiards”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A classic film projector, as projects film onto a screen for viewing. Generally depicted as a black or gray projector with two mounted reels and lens pointed right.
Commonly used for various content concerning movies, film, and video as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit.
Google’s design is blue, WhatsApp’s is green.
Not to be confused with 🎥 Movie Camera.

Film Projector was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Five-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Clock Face Five-Thirty”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A chocolate-glazed donut (or doughnut) with rainbow sprinkles. WhatsApp features a pink glaze associated with The Simpsons. May resemble the Bagel at small sizes.

Doughnut was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A church building, generally associated with Christian denominations. In addition quiet prayer, churches hold regular worship services, weddings, baptisms and funerals.

Church was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Division Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Heavy Division Sign”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A family with two mothers, one daughter, and one son.
The Family: Woman, Woman, Girl, Boy emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman, 👩 Woman, 👧 Girl and 👦 Boy emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Family: Woman, Woman, Girl, Boy was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Costa Rica, which may show as the letters CR on some platforms.
The Flag: Costa Rica emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Costa Rica was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A crayon, as children use to color. Depicted as red on most platforms with two black stripes on its label, resembling a Crayola crayon. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning drawing, colors, arts and crafts, and schooling.
WhatsApp’s crayon is green while Facebook’s is orange.

Crayon was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Lower Left Crayon”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Togo, which may show as the letters TG on some platforms.
The Flag: Togo emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Togo was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for U.S. Outlying Islands, which may show as the letters UM on some platforms. This is the same flag as the United States.
The Flag: U.S. Outlying Islands emoji is a sequence of the 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: U.S. Outlying Islands was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Diego Garcia, which may show as the letters DG on some platforms. The same flag is used for British Indian Ocean Territory.
The Flag: Diego Garcia emoji is a sequence of the 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Diego Garcia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
The brown bread of a bagel, shown sliced in two halves. Some platforms depict seeds, as sesame or poppy, and a schmear of cream cheese, with the bagel assembled as a sandwich. May resemble the Doughnut at small sizes.
After complaints, Apple updated the bagel emoji design during the iOS 12.1 beta cycle.

Bagel was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018
and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A red, octagonal sign. Used in many countries as a stop sign.

Stop Sign was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016
under the name “Octagonal Sign”
and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for sports, music, the arts, hobbies and other activities.
emoji_description:
A female rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope.
Variations exist for 🧗‍♂️ Man Climbing and 🧗 Person Climbing.
The Woman Climbing emoji is a sequence of the 🧗 Person Climbing and ♀ Female Sign emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Climbing was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
A red symbol found in Anime/Manga and used to represent the veins popping on a very angry person.
Also used in other comic books to indicate a punch landed, perhaps next to the words “Bam” or “Pow”.

Anger Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The number 10 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap.

Keycap: 10 was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Keycap Ten”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
No Smoking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “No Smoking Symbol”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Two men displayed kissing, or gesturing a kiss toward each other. At small sizes this may be difficult to discern from the two women kissing.
The Kiss: Man, Man emoji is a sequence of the 👨 Man, ❤ Heavy Black Heart, 💋 Kiss Mark and 👨 Man emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Kiss: Man, Man was added to Emoji 2.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A "rock on" hand gesture raising the pinky and index fingers on one hand, which a variety of other meanings.

Sign of the Horns was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Mongolia, which may show as the letters MN on some platforms.
The Flag: Mongolia emoji is a sequence of the 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M and 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Mongolia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A woman and man holding hands, most likely due to being in a relationship.

Woman and Man Holding Hands was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Man and Woman Holding Hands”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Cameroon, which may show as the letters CM on some platforms.
The Flag: Cameroon emoji is a sequence of the 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Cameroon was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for fruit, vegetables, meals, beverages and utensils.
emoji_description:
A block of dark chocolate, usually shown in a red foil wrapper peeled back to show squares of the candy. WhatsApp displays the wrapper in purple, a color commonly associated with Cadbury chocolate.

Chocolate Bar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Back Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Back With Leftwards Arrow Above”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
A tall, ceramic jar with two handles and a narrow neck and foot. Represents an amphora, as used by ancient Greeks and Romans to hold water and wine.
Generally depicted as brownish-red earthenware ornamented with black and a Greek meander pattern.
May represent containers like vases, pottery, museums, history, and antiquity. May also be used in relation to the zodiac sign of Aquarius, the Water-Bearer.
Not to be confused with ⚱️ Funeral Urn.

Amphora was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
A yellow face with simple, open eyes and a closed zipper for a mouth. Meaning widely varies, but commonly conveys a secret or that someone will keep one (e.g., My lips are sealed). May also be used to tell someone to stop talking (e.g., Zip it! or I’ll shut up now).
Google's design for 😯 Hushed Face previously featured a zipper-mouth.

Zipper-Mouth Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Mechanic emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🔧 Wrench emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Mechanic was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: Emojis for varied scenes, locations, buildings and modes of transport.
emoji_description:
A roller coaster in a theme park going down a dip in the ride. Three carriages can be seen with two people in each red carriage.

Roller Coaster was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman Judge emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and ⚖ Scales emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman Judge was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Croatia, which may show as the letters HR on some platforms.
The Flag: Croatia emoji is a sequence of the 🇭 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter H and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Croatia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for household items, celebrations, stationery and miscellaneous objects.
emoji_description:
Two or more silver paper clips linked together, generally forming an inverted V. Microsoft’s design displays three paper clips.
Occasionally used to represent school/office supplies or metaphorical connections. Also sometimes used as an icon before a hyperlink.
Not to be confused with 🔗 Link or ⛓️ Chains.

Linked Paperclips was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Three eighth notes (quavers in British English), used to represent music or singing. Sometimes inserted next to quoted lyrics, to make it clear that they are part of a song.

Musical Notes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Multiple Musical Notes”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
Socks was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Black Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: List of country flag emojis. 🇯🇵 🇰🇷 🇩🇪 🇨🇳 🇺🇸 🇫🇷 🇪🇸 🇮🇹 🇷🇺 🇬🇧 Emoji flags are supported on all major platforms except Windows, which displays two-letter country codes instead of emoji flag images.
emoji_description:
The flag for Nigeria, which may show as the letters NG on some platforms.
The Flag: Nigeria emoji is a sequence of the 🇳 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter N and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis.
These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Flag: Nigeria was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The Woman: White Hair emoji is a sequence of the 👩 Woman and 🦳 Emoji Component White Hair emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

Woman: White Hair was added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
The joker in a deck of cards, usually appearing like a court jester.

Joker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Playing Card Black Joker”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Heart emojis, clocks, arrows, signs and shapes.
emoji_description:
Two triangles pointing up. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° clockwise.

Fast Up Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010
under the name “Black Up-Pointing Double Triangle”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for smileys, people, families, hand gestures, clothing and accessories.
emoji_description:
The silhouette of a person speaking. Faces left-to-right, with lines demonstrating speech being expelled. Sometimes used in the context of shouting or mansplaining.

Speaking Head was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014
under the name “Speaking Head in Silhouette”
and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

category_description: Emojis for animals, nature, and weather.
emoji_description:
A zebra, a horse-like mammal with black-and-white stripes. Variously depicted in full profile on all fours facing left or as a zebra head facing left with a short mane.
Not to be confused with 🐎 Horse. Some vendors implement a similar face as their 🐴 Horse Face.
Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs feature the full animal; Google, Microsoft, and Samsung’s designs feature a head with a short mane and black muzzle. Facebook’s design previously featured only a zebra head.

Zebra was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017
under the name “Zebra Face”
and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.
